<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bosnia Premier Rejects Resignations  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BANJA LUKA, Bosnia-Herzegovina (AP) -- Four Cabinet members from the ruling
coalition in the Serb half of Bosnia handed in their resignations Monday, but
the republic's pro-Western premier refused to accept them.
</P>
<P>
	   Despite the move by the four Socialist Party members, the collapse of
Premier Milorad Dodik's 2-year-old moderate government is unlikely.
</P>
<P>
	   The move ``will not jeopardize institutions in the Republika Srpska,'' said
Krstan Simic, a close ally of Dodik and a member of Bosnian Serb parliament.
</P>
<P>
	   According to the republic's constitution, a minister cannot step down until
the premier has named a replacement.
</P>
<P>
	   The Socialists, who represent the Bosnian branch of Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic's party, decided Sunday to quit the coalition because of
Dodik's ``unprincipled behavior,'' according to a statement.
</P>
<P>
	   The Socialists, who are upset because Dodik fired two party officials, hold
10 seats in the 83-seat parliament and five of 20 Cabinet posts.
</P>
<P>
	   Dodik and his allies still hold a majority in parliament, with 43 seats.
</P>
<P>
	   Svetozar Mihajlovic, vice president of the Serb National Alliance, another
coalition party member, told the Bosnian news agency Onasa he suspected that
Milosevic's government in neighboring Yugoslavia had substantial, ``maybe even
decisive influence'' on the Socialist Party's decision to withdraw from the
coalition.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
