<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 00:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Threatens Unification or War  </HEADLINE>
   By CHARLES HUTZLER Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BEIJING (AP) -- With a month to go in Taiwan's presidential election
campaign, China warned Monday that it might attack the island if Taiwanese
leaders indefinitely refuse to talk unification.
</P>
<P>
	   The threat, delivered in a policy paper from China's Cabinet, was intended
to increase the pressure on Taiwan's three presidential candidates. Although
there was no immediate reaction from Taiwan's government or the candidates'
camps, policy toward China has been at the center of the campaign, which ends
March 18.
</P>
<P>
	   The Mainland Affairs Council, which handles Taiwan's China policy, planned
to have a news conference later Tuesday after the council has had an opportunity
to review the report.
</P>
<P>
	   China's renewed threats helped cause Taiwan's stock market to close sharply
lower Tuesday, analysts said. The jittery market, which ended down 1.8 percent,
has been extremely sensitive in the past to China's saber-rattling.
</P>
<P>
	   Chao Chun-shan, a professor at National Chengchi University in Taipei, said
the policy paper was a disappointment for Taiwanese. In recent months, the
candidates have done a lot of creative thinking about how to improve relations
with China, and Beijing responded by repeating its old line with a new threat,
Chao said.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The presidential candidates have to feel disappointed and the voters have
to feel disappointed,'' Chao said.
</P>
<P>
	   Already this month, China sailed its newly acquired, heavily armed
Russian-built destroyer through the Taiwan Strait. And Chinese President Jiang
Zemin over the weekend toured military bases in southern China that would be the
ones used in any invasion of Taiwan, the Hong Kong media reported.
</P>
<P>
	   Such tactics, and Monday's heated words from the State Council, were ominous
reminders that Taiwan and China remain antagonists in an unfinished,
seven-decade civil war. Although democratic Taiwan has relinquished its claim to
the communist mainland, China considers the island a rebel province.
</P>
<P>
	   China has long vowed to wage war if Taiwan declared independence outright or
foreign forces meddle. The policy paper from the State Council added Taiwanese
foot-dragging over unification talks to the list of provocative circumstances
that would compel China to attack.
</P>
<P>
	   If any of those three situations arose, ``then the Chinese government will
be forced to adopt all drastic measures possible, including the use of force, to
... fulfill the great cause of reunification,'' the document said.
</P>
<P>
	   It included a warning to the United States to scale back arms sales to
Taiwan -- once a close ally whose defense Washington must by law assist -- and
``not to stand in the way of the reunification of China.''
</P>
<P>
	   China's new Taiwan policy statement was not all barbs. It reiterated that
force was a last resort and offered to hold talks as equals with any Taiwanese
politicians so long as they recognized the island as part of ``one China.''
</P>
<P>
	   In Taiwan's last presidential campaign four years ago, China tested missiles
and staged intimidating war games to deter pro-independence Taiwanese and the
United States sent warships to counter the threats. It was the closest the sides
had come to armed confrontation since the late 1950s.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-22-00 0004 </TRAILER>
