<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 00:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton campaign complains about Giuliani "hypocrisy"  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's campaign committee is
returning a contribution it accepted from a source he had earlier criticized
Senate rival Hillary Rodham Clinton for tapping.
<P>
	   At issue is a $750 September donation to the New York City mayor's campaign
committee from a political action committee linked to the Loral Space and
Communications company.
</P>
<P>
	   After being informed of the donation by a reporter Monday, Giuliani campaign
spokeswoman Kim Serafin said "it is our intention to return that money."
</P>
<P>
	   Earlier this month, the Giuliani campaign issued a news release complaining
about "the Clinton campaign's funny-money machine" and "the reemergence of the
same cast of characters at the center of the worst finance abuses that marred
the 1996 presidential campaign."
</P>
<P>
	   As evidence of that, the Giuliani camp cited "Bernie Schwartz of Loral Space
and Communications, which is currently under Justice Department investigation
over the illegal transfer of missile technology to China. Donated to Mrs.
Clinton $40,000."
</P>
<P>
	   Federal election records show the Clinton campaign and related committees
received the $40,000 from Loral chief Bernard Schwartz and his wife.
</P>
<P>
	   In recent years, Schwartz has been one of the Democratic Party's biggest
donors.
</P>
<P>
	   "Rudy Giuliani has cornered the market on hypocrisy," Clinton campaign
spokesman Howard Wolfson said. "Soon the mayor will accuse us of arresting the
homeless and cutting $7 billion from city schools."
</P>
<P>
	   The Clinton camp has been critical of the mayor's push to have homeless
people arrested who refuse to leave the streets and for his attacks on the New
York City school system.
</P>
<P>
	   The latest Clinton attack served to highlight the extensive research that
each is doing on the other's voluminous fund-raising reports that were filed
with the Federal Election Commission at the end of last month. Over the final
six months of last year, Republican Giuliani raised $8.8 million for the Senate
race while Democrat Clinton raised about $8 million.
</P>
<P>
	   In addition to the recent $750 donation from the Loral Spacecom Civic
Responsibility Fund, the Clinton campaign said Giuliani's mayoral campaign
committee received $750 from Schwartz in 1993.
</P>
<P>
	   Meanwhile, the Giuliani camp, citing Clinton's FEC report, has complained
that she has reimbursed the federal government just $34,000 as of the end of
last year for political trips to New York on government aircraft. The mayor's
aides have said she should pay more than $300,000 more than that to cover the
real costs of such travel. Her aides have said they have reimbursed the federal
government for everything they are required to.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-22-00 0008 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
