<DOCNO> APW20000222.0016 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 00:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Group once allied with Pataki now running anti-Pataki ads  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - A group whose backing of George Pataki in 1994 was
helpful in making him governor is running advertisements suggesting he has lost
touch with his conservative roots.
<P>
	   The television and radio ads from Change-New York look and sound like
something that would come from Democrats seeking to drive the Republican
governor from office, and not erstwhile supporters of Pataki.
</P>
<P>
	   But Change-New York has come to the conclusion that the Pataki of the 1994
campaign and his first two years in office is not the Pataki who now occupies
the Executive Mansion, spokesman Brian Backstrom said Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   "I think that there is a mentality, 'Tax cuts? We've done those. Hold the
line on spending? We've done that,"' Backstrom said. "We thought we were in this
for a marriage. We only got the honeymoon."
</P>
<P>
	   Pataki's mandate from voters dating back to his defeat of liberal Democrat
Mario Cuomo was clear, Backstrom said: "To behave in a fiscally prudent and
tax-cutting manner as long as he's in office, not just the moment."
</P>
<P>
	   The group is particularly angered about a $400 million increase on state
cigarette taxes approved by Pataki and the state Legislature in December as well
as a proposed 2000-01 state budget from the governor that Change-New York
believes would increase spending by twice the rate of inflation.
</P>
<P>
	   "This is not the behavior of fiscal conservatives," Backstrom contended.
"One of the reasons we felt a media campaign was warranted was this latest round
of tax hikes and excessive spending was not a blip on the radar screen, but the
next giant step of an intentional move leftward."
</P>
<P>
	   Pataki spokesman Michael McKeon said the group knows it is "deliberately
distorting the facts" with an ad which says upstate New York, if taken as a
separate state, has had job growth ranked 49th nationally since Pataki has
become governor.
</P>
<P>
	   "Upstate is growing jobs faster than many places, such as Illinois, Ohio,
North Carolina and Pennsylvania," McKeon said. "In fact, upstate has more jobs
now than ever before. It's a far cry from the final years of the Cuomo
administration. New Yorkers are not going to be fooled by these misleading ads."
</P>
<P>
	   The group has two anti-Pataki TV ads, one showing scenes of Niagara Falls
and other flowing waters and criticizing Pataki for proposing a fee on water
hookups. The money was to have gone to fund water-quality programs in the state,
though Pataki's office indicated the governor was backing off the proposal.
</P>
<P>
	   The other TV ad says: "While Wall Street is booming, upstate New York is
being left behind." If upstate is treated as a separate state, the commercial
says it would be 49th in the country in job creation since Pataki became
governor in 1995.
</P>
<P>
	   "Governor Pataki," the ad implores, "stop hiking our taxes. Get back to
cutting them."
</P>
<P>
	   Backstrom said the ads are running in major upstate New York television
markets. He declined to say how much the group was paying for the commercials,
how long they will run or if others are in the works. He said the group will
stop airing the "water tax" commercial in light of Pataki's decision to back off
that proposal.
</P>
<P>
	   State Senate Majority Leader Joseph Bruno called the ads "very, very
one-sided" and "unfair." He complained they make no reference to the tax cuts
enacted under Pataki, estimated as having a cumulative savings for taxpayers of
a highest-in-the-nation $29 billion or more.
</P>
<P>
	   Bruno said he was also taken aback by the source of the criticism.
</P>
<P>
	   "They were his biggest supporter in the first election (in 1994) so that's
why this is so surprising," he said on WROW-AM radio in Albany. "These ads are
almost vindictive."
</P>
<P>
	   Among the members of Change-New York's board are two financiers who have
contributed generously to Pataki's campaigns in the past, Richard Gilder and
Bruce Kovner.
</P>
<P>
	   Backstrom said top Change-New York officials were angered when Pataki failed
to show up for a scheduled meeting with them to discuss his taxing and other
policies.
</P>
<P>
	   Pataki insists his budget increases general fund spending by just over 2
percent or about the rate of inflation, but the overall increase when all funds
are factored in would be more than 5 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-22-00 0008 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
