<HEADLINE> Temple Football Player Stabbed  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- A Temple University tailback was in critical but stable
condition after being stabbed outside a dormitory Monday night.
</P>
<P>
	   Elmarko Jackson, 21, from Sharon, Pa., was stabbed several times in the neck
chest and arm at about 6 p.m. on the North Philadelphia campus, police said.
</P>
<P>
	   Jackson had been seen arguing with a man, believed to be another student,
authorities said.
</P>
<P>
	   Jackson, a sports-management major in his senior year, was taken to Temple
University Hospital. He was out of surgery Monday night.
</P>
<P>
	   "Police are questioning a possible suspect who was seen with him outside the
residence hall this afternoon," university spokesman George Ingram said.
</P>
<P>
	   Police found the knife believed to have been used in the attack in a pile of
trash around the corner.
</P>
<P>
	   School security had been increased recently and high-powered lights were
installed on the campus, which sits in a high-crime area of the city.
</P>
<P>
	   University president Peter Liacouras stood outside the White Hall dorm where
the attack took place, talking with concerned students.
</P>
<P>
	   "You can't get used to violence. I don't know enough about the situation to
say any more than that except that we just pray that the injured person will be
all right," Liacouras said.
</P>
<P>
	   Jackson, who has played on the football team for three years, was declared
academically ineligible to play in the season finale against Miami.
</P>
<P>
	   "He was bound to go to the NFL next year. When we heard it was him, we were
all shocked," said teammate Danny Culic.
</P>
</TEXT>
