<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nuggets 123, Kings 117, OT  </HEADLINE>
    By AARON J. LOPEZ AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   DENVER (AP) -- Antonio McDyess had 29 points and 13 rebounds, and the Denver
Nuggets hit 12 3-pointers Monday night in a 123-117 overtime victory over the
Sacramento Kings.
</P>
<P>
	   Nick Van Exel added 27 points and 15 assists for the Nuggets, who overcame
an early 19-point deficit and a career-best performance by Sacramento shooting
guard Predrag Stojakovic.
</P>
<P>
	   Stojakovic, starting in place of ailing Nick Anderson, scored a career-high
30 points -- including 11 straight at one stretch of the fourth quarter. Chris
Webber had 25 points and 15 rebounds for the Kings, who lost their second
straight overtime game.
</P>
<P>
	   The Nuggets got a balanced offensive attack with four players scoring more
than 20 points as Chris Gatling and Bryant Stith each scored 21 off the bench.
</P>
<P>
	   Denver, which trailed by double figures for much of the game, didn't take
its first lead until McDyess made two free throws 1:37 into overtime.
</P>
<P>
	   The Kings never led again as Raef LaFrentz hit Denver's 12th 3-pointer of
the night for a 119-115 lead with 1:29 remaining, and McDyess followed a
Sacramento turnover with an easy basket in the lane 16 seconds later.
</P>
<P>
	   Stith tied the game at 108 on a 3-pointer, his fourth of the game, with 38.6
seconds left. The Kings turned the ball over on their next possession, and Stith
missed a long 3-point try at the end of regulation.
</P>
<P>
	   After watching Sacramento turn away every challenge, the Nuggets used a 12-2
run to pull within a point with 6:02 left. Stojakovic responded with a pull-up
jumper, a layup and two 20-foot shots in a 90-second span to give the Kings a
101-92 lead with 4:06 remaining.
</P>
<P>
	   Denver made its final charge behind back-to-back 3-pointers by Van Exel and
Stith's 3-pointer in the final minute.
</P>
<P>
	   Jon Barry, averaging eight points a game, hit three 3-pointers and had 14
points in the second quarter as the Kings took a 13-point halftime lead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
