<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 00:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Blues 4, Mighty Ducks 2  </HEADLINE>
    By KEN PETERS AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ANAHEIM, Calif. (AP) -- Al MacInnis completed St. Louis' comeback from a
two-goal deficit Monday night when he scored with 1:49 remaining as the Blues
extended their club-record road winning streak to eight with a 4-2 victory over
the Anaheim Mighty Ducks.
</P>
<P>
	   Jochen Hecht scored an empty-net goal, his eighth, with 54 seconds remaining
as the Blues won their fourth in a row and 10th in 11 contests.
</P>
<P>
	   MacInnis' goal, his eighth, sailed over the left shoulder of Anaheim goalie
Dominic Roussel, beating him on the glove side from 45 feet out.
</P>
<P>
	   The Blues' Michal Handzus tied it 2-2 with 11:17 to go on a fine individual
effort, skating down right wing, slicing inside of defenseman Ruslan Salei and
beating Roussel from 30 feet. The goal was Handzus' 17th.
</P>
<P>
	   After the Mighty Ducks scored twice 45 seconds apart early in the second
period, Marty Reasoner cut the deficit to 2-1 at 11:32 of the period.
</P>
<P>
	   Jeff Finley, skating near the boards, shot from the left wing. Reasoner
picked up the rebound and poked a shot past the sprawling Roussel. The goal was
Reasoner's sixth.
</P>
<P>
	   Salei gave Anaheim a 2-0 edge with a 20-foot slap shot from the slot 3:19
into the second for his fourth goal. Ted Donato redirected a shot by Fredrik
Olausson past St. Louis goalie Roman Turek for Anaheim's first goal, 2:34 into
the period. Donato's goal was his ninth.
</P>
<P>
	   Anaheim squandered a two-man advantage for a span of 1:13 late in the
second, failing to get a shot.
</P>
<P>
	   The Mighty Ducks were without leading scorer Paul Kariya, out with a bruised
right foot.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-22-00 0022 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
