<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 00:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stocks Down at Midday  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    TOKYO (AP) -- The U.S. dollar was higher against the yen Tuesday morning
amid continued bullish sentiment toward the greenback. Japanese stocks fell.
</P>
<P>
	   The dollar bought 111.62 yen at late morning, up 1.04 yen from late Monday
in Tokyo and also above its late London level of 111.22 yen overnight. U.S.
markets were closed Monday for a national holiday.
</P>
<P>
	   The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average, which rose some 140 points
early the session, finished the morning down 50.79, or 0.26 percent, to
19,492.96. On Monday, the average closed down 245.28 points, or 1.23 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   In currency dealings, the dollar moved higher as investors in Europe were
buying the U.S. currency in early Asian trading Tuesday after a quiet session
Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   Traders said Japanese exporters probably bid up the dollar later in the
morning.
</P>
<P>
	   The dollar in recent weeks has been gaining ground against the yen amid
sentiment that Japan's economic recovery is not as firm as previously thought.
</P>
<P>
	   Favorable prospects for U.S. economic growth coupled with low inflation were
in turn among positive factors supporting the dollar.
</P>
<P>
	   In other currencies, the euro was traded at 110.80 yen, up from 109.37 yen
late Monday in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
	   On the stock market, prices started slightly higher following Monday's steep
fall but gradually moved into negative territory as selling pressure mounted
ahead of the end of Japan's fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
	   Japanese companies in recent years have started unwinding the
cross-shareholding issues they hold in other companies prior to the end of each
fiscal year, which ends March 31.
</P>
<P>
	   Investors also remained cautious over uncertainty about the direction of New
York markets. On Friday, the Dow Jones industrial average tumbled 295.05 points,
or 2.8 percent, to close at 10,219.52.
</P>
<P>
	   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the first
section was down 23.63 points, or 1.41 percent, to 1,657.09. The TOPIX closed
down 39.05 points, or 2.27 percent, the day before.
</P>
<P>
	   The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond rose to 1.8350
percent from Monday's finish of 1.8000 percent. Its price fell 0.29 point to
98.85. (km-dj)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-22-00 0033 </TRAILER>
