<SUBHEAD>
Clinton: Hospitals Must Report Medical Mistakes
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton wants hospitals to tell patients and
the government how often they kill or seriously injure those in their care.
Hospitals nationwide would have to disclose serious and deadly mistakes if
Congress adopts a White House plan developed in response to a report last year
that estimated medical mix-ups kill as many as 98,000 Americans each year.
Clinton also planned Tuesday to order several new requirements that do not need
congressional approval, including an immediate mandatory reporting requirement
for the 500 Defense Department-administered hospitals that serve an estimated 8
million people.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Final Microsoft Arguments To Begin
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Settlement talks in the Microsoft Corp. antitrust lawsuit
are going so poorly that the trial judge is moving ahead with plans for final
courtroom arguments before his verdict. U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield
Jackson didn't see any need to delay the last round of arguments, set for
Tuesday, to accommodate ongoing secret negotiations in Chicago between
government lawyers and Microsoft officials. Though sources indicate little
progress, negotiations are aimed at averting an agonizingly slow appeals battle
that could wind through the federal courts for years.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Texas Inmates Take Officer Hostage
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   LIVINGSTON, Texas (AP) -- Two death row inmates who were part of a botched
escape in 1998 took a female guard hostage Monday in a new prison that was
supposed to be more secure. The guard was taking one inmate back to his cell at
about 4:15 p.m. when he and another inmate overpowered her, said Texas
Department of Criminal Justice spokesman Larry Fitzgerald. One inmate had
somehow jimmied his cell door, Fitzgerald said. "They have no place to go.
Officers have sealed off the area," he said. "She has not been threatened or
harmed in any way, but it is a tense situation."
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Gore, Bradley Spar in Harlem Debate
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- In an angry Harlem debate, Al Gore accused Bill Bradley of
attack tactics that "divide us as Democrats," while the challenger described the
vice president as a sometime conservative with a suspect record on affirmative
action. The tone of the argument on the stage of the historic Apollo Theater was
set at the start, when the presidential rivals agreed that they'd both take
steps against racial profiling -- and immediately tried to turn the question
against each other. The 90-minute debate -- the candidates ninth presidential
debate -- was televised by CNN. The largely black audience cheered, applauded,
jeered, sometimes booed. Neither candidate was spared the raucous reactions.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
China Warns of Taiwan Attack
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   BEIJING (AP) -- China warned Monday that it might attack Taiwan if the
island's leaders indefinitely refuse to talk unification. The threat, which came
a month before Taiwan's presidential election campaign, was intended to increase
the pressure on Taiwan's three presidential candidates. Although there was no
immediate reaction from Taiwan's government or the candidates' camps, policy
toward China has been at the center of the campaign. Already this month, China
sailed its newly acquired, destroyer through the Taiwan Strait.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Space Shuttle To Land in California
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) -- NASA has informed space shuttle Endeavour's
astronauts that the backup landing site at Edwards Air Force Base in California
appears to be the "only viable option" for tomorrow's landing. Clouds and high
wind were forecast at Cape Canaveral in Florida. The last time NASA had to
divert a space shuttle to Edwards was in 1996. With their mapping of Earth
completed, the astronauts pulled in a 197-foot radar antenna mast after
struggling with it for two tense hours.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stock Prices Close Lower
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   TOKYO (AP) -- The Nikkei shed 153.17 points to close at 19,390.58.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Suns 98, Spurs 89
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   SAN ANTONIO (AP) -- Taking advantage of an injury to Tim Duncan, Rodney
Rogers scored 22 points to lead the Phoenix Suns to a 98-89 come-from-behind
victory over the San Antonio Spurs on Monday night. Duncan left the game with
11:08 to play in the second quarter with a lower abdominal strain. Tom Gugliotta
added 21 points for Phoenix, which extended its winning streak to six games.
David Robinson led San Antonio with 31 points and 18 rebounds, while Malik Rose
chipped in 17 off the bench.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Romanowskis in SI Swimsuit Issue
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- Denver Broncos linebacker Bill Romanowski and his wife,
Julie, are baring a little skin in this year's Sports Illustrated swimsuit
issue. The Romanowskis posed together, with Bill in white football pants with no
shirt and his first Broncos Super Bowl ring prominently displayed on his right
ring finger, and Julie in a silver bikini.
</P>
<P>
	   AP NewsBrief by VINCENT K. WILLIS
</P>
