<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 02:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ga. House OKs Lethal Injection Bill  </HEADLINE>
   By RUSS BYNUM Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ATLANTA (AP) -- The Georgia House has voted overwhelmingly to replace
electrocution with lethal injection, a step toward ending a practice used since
the state stopped hanging inmates in 1924.
</P>
<P>
	   The 162-10 vote came Monday as legislators wondered whether the U.S. Supreme
Court is preparing to outlaw the electric chair. Similar concerns in Florida
prompted a recent switch to lethal injection there; the state is to have its
first execution by that method Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   If the Georgia bill becomes law, Alabama and Nebraska would be the only
states that use electrocution as the sole means of execution.
</P>
<P>
	   Rep. E.C. Tillman, a preacher who has ministered to condemned inmates, said
he sponsored Georgia's bill to fulfill a promise to try to move the state away
from what he called a ``barbaric method.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``Lethal injection, to me, would be a more humane way,'' Tillman said.
</P>
<P>
	   Most of the debate centered on whether Georgia should abolish the death
penalty altogether, rather than change execution methods. An attempt to end
capital punishment was defeated after several lawmakers, mainly black Democrats,
defended executions as a necessary evil.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The death penalty is hard. It's cruel. But it's a necessity,'' said Rep.
Lawrence Roberts, a convenience store owner. ``There's nothing (else) to prevent
robbers and killers from coming in, maiming and killing my employees.''
</P>
<P>
	   Rep. Joe Heckstall said constituents urged him to vote to abolish capital
punishment because they feel it unfairly affects blacks.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I ain't going to make excuses for African-American criminals, white
criminals, Hispanic criminals,'' Heckstall said. ``If you commit an atrocity, I
don't care what your socioeconomic background is. I don't feel sorry for you.''
</P>
<P>
	   Others argued that the risk of executing the innocent is too great to
justify capital punishment. Rep. Ben Allen said Georgia should at least put a
moratorium on executions, as Illinois has done, to study the fairness of the
death penalty.
</P>
<P>
	   The switch to lethal injection would apply to death row inmates convicted of
crimes committed May 1 and thereafter. The 127 inmates now on death row in
Georgia would still die by electrocution, unless the state or U.S. Supreme Court
strikes down that method.
</P>
<P>
	   Democratic Gov. Roy Barnes declined to comment on the lethal injection bill
other than to say he supports the death penalty, said Joselyn Butler, his
spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
	   Since the Supreme Court allowed capital punishment to resume, Georgia has
put 23 inmates to death.
</P>
<P>
	   The Supreme Court dropped a challenge to Florida's death penalty law after
the state switched from electrocution to lethal injection last month. The court
is preparing to hear an Alabama case.
</P>
<P>
	   A bill before the Nebraska Legislature would switch the state's execution
method from electrocution to lethal injection, but it's uncertain when it will
be considered.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-22-00 0236 </TRAILER>
