<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 02:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Detroit Democrats Backing McCain  </HEADLINE>
   By KATHY BARKS HOFFMAN Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   DETROIT (AP) -- Autoworker Sheila McCaulley proudly considers herself a
Democrat through and through -- one with a vote ready to cast today in
Michigan's Republican presidential primary.
</P>
<P>
	   McCaulley -- ``I am a Democrat -- a Democrat all the way'' -- said she
planned to vote for John McCain. Not because she likes McCain, but because she
despises Republican Gov. John Engler, an ardent, visible backer of Texas Gov.
George W. Bush in the GOP presidential race.
</P>
<P>
	   ``If it will send a message to Engler to vote for McCain, I will,''
McCaulley said.
</P>
<P>
	   Her views of Engler are shared by many in predominantly black, mostly
Democratic Detroit, where the governor's decision to turn control of the public
schools over to a board appointed by the mayor drew widespread criticism.
</P>
<P>
	   ``He just took over our school board. We got no say at all,'' said
McCaulley, 46.
</P>
<P>
	   Detroiters also object to Engler's decisions to merge the Detroit Recorder's
Court into the Wayne County courts and to sign a bill doing away with
requirement that city workers live within city boundaries.
</P>
<P>
	   ``As a lifetime Detroiter, I feel real disrespected at this point,'' said
Carol Banks, 39, as she handed out leaflets urging passers-by to vote for
McCain.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I think the only way we're going to send a message is to let him know that
our votes do count.''
</P>
<P>
	   Polls have shown McCain and Bush in a close race in Michigan, with Bush
doing better among Republicans and McCain pulling in support from independents
and Democrats.
</P>
<P>
	   Democratic turnout for the Republican primary was expected to be higher than
usual. Still, pollsters such as Ed Sarpolus of Lansing-based EPIC/MRA say most
of those choosing McCain are genuine supporters, not those trying to make a
point with Engler.
</P>
<P>
	   Detroiter Hyland Gear, a retired IBM manager who shares a military
background with McCain, truly likes the U.S. senator.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I vote for the person I think is the best for the job, and I think McCain
is the best for the job,'' said Gear, who has voted only twice before for a
Republican.
</P>
<P>
	   Gear said he served a combined 14 years in the Army and Air Force and
admires McCain for what he went through as a prisoner of war in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It shows the kind of character this guy has,'' said Gear, 67.
</P>
<P>
	   But state Rep. Lamar Lemmons III, a Detroit Democrat helping to lead the
anti-Engler, pro-McCain movement in the city, made clear his position as he took
the campaign to several Detroit churches on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Should he get it, we're not going to be with John McCain in the fall,''
Lemmons said at the Second Canaan Missionary Baptist Church.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We're going to be with Bill Bradley or Al Gore or whoever the Democratic
nominee is,'' Lemmons said to choruses of ``that's right'' from the
congregation.
</P>
<P>
	   The Rev. Bill McCullum, pastor at Bride of Christ church, said the strategy
was necessary ``to show the governor we are completely dissatisfied with his
lack of support for southeast Michigan.''
</P>
<P>
	   Engler has used the Democrats' pro-McCain strategy as a wake-up call to
Republicans to get out and vote.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Your help is urgently needed because some of Al Gore's leading supporters
here in Michigan ... plan to interfere with our February 22 primary,'' Engler
wrote recently to Bush supporters.
</P>
<P>
	   Peter DeMarco, spokesman for McCain's Michigan campaign, skirted the
question of whether McCain welcomes the votes of Democrats who have no intention
of backing him in the fall.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We're happy to have votes from all voters in Michigan, be they Republican,
Democratic, independent, Libertarian, vegetarian,'' DeMarco said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-22-00 0257 </TRAILER>
