<DOCNO> APW20000222.0068 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 03:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Mall would siphon 28 percent of downtown sales  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) - New Haven's central business district would lose
28 percent of its sales to the proposed mall at Long Wharf, according to a study
being prepared for the state Department of Economic and Community Development.
<P>
	   The mall would also siphon off shoppers from businesses in North Haven,
Orange, Hamden, Milford and Southbury, according to the report obtained by The
Hartford Courant. Even the Brass Mill Center in Waterbury, some 20 miles away,
would lose 8 percent of its sales, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
	   The report contradicts a draft report issued by the development agency last
year that said the mall would have no significant effect on the economy or the
environment.
</P>
<P>
	   "This is the first hard evidence that's been provided by the state itself as
to the economic impact on downtown New Haven. It confirms what we've suspected,"
said Steve Ecker, a lawyer whose clients include New Haven business owners who
oppose the mall.
</P>
<P>
	   "Now they have to justify using taxpayer money to destroy downtown New Haven
and put those taxpayers out of business," Ecker said.
</P>
<P>
	   New Haven Corporation Counsel Thayer Baldwin said a study that estimates
transfers of sales shouldn't apply to New Haven's atypical downtown.
</P>
<P>
	   "People don't go downtown to shop; they go downtown for Yale, for galleries,
museums, entertainment, to work and to live, and they shop while they're there,"
Baldwin said.
</P>
<P>
	   "Even if the 28 percent were true, which I don't believe, that would be a
loss to downtown of about $30 million of sales a year," he said. But the mall
would mean $300 million in sales per year, 3,000 jobs and $6 million a year in
property taxes, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   James Watson, a spokesman for the economic development agency, said he has
not seen the report and couldn't comment.
</P>
<P>
	   The economic agency hired the Connecticut Economic Resource Center, a
nonprofit organization that is a partnership of state government and utilities,
to conduct the study.
</P>
<P>
	   The report is expected to be turned over to the economic development agency
in a few days.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
