<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 3 a.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    Tuesday, Feb. 22, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Bush, McCain Continue To Bicker
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   DETROIT (AP) -- The pulse of the Republican presidential race quickened
Tuesday, with voters going to the polls in GOP contests in Michigan and Arizona,
and Sen. John McCain and Gov. George W. Bush trading fresh charges of negative
campaigning. Aides to the Arizona senator accused religious broadcaster Pat
Robertson of making calls on Bush's behalf implying that former Sen. Warren
Rudman, McCain's national campaign chairman, was "a vicious bigot." Rudman
angered leaders of the religious right in 1995 by defending retired Gen. Colin
Powell against their attacks over abortion.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Iran Reform Leader: U.S. Talks Possible
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   TEHRAN, Iran (AP) -- An influential reform leader has said that talks with
the United States would not be a "sin," a view shared by many reformist
candidates set to take control of Iran's next Parliament. Talks with the United
States, a more liberal press and increased personal freedoms are expected to be
among the issues discussed in the next Parliament, which resumes in June.
Moderates look set to wrest the legislative body from hard-line control for the
first time since Iran's 1979 Islamic Revolution ousted the pro-U.S. shah and
brought the Muslim Shiite clergy to power.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Ga. House OKs Lethal Injection Bill
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   ATLANTA (AP) -- The Georgia House has voted overwhelmingly to replace
electrocution with lethal injection, a step toward ending a practice used since
the state stopped hanging inmates in 1924. The 162-10 vote came Monday as
legislators wondered whether the U.S. Supreme Court is preparing to outlaw the
electric chair. Similar concerns in Florida prompted a recent switch to lethal
injection there; the state is to have its first execution by that method
Wednesday. If the Georgia bill becomes law, Alabama and Nebraska would be the
only states that use electrocution as the sole means of execution.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton: Hospitals Must Report Medical Mistakes
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton wants hospitals to tell patients and
the government how often they kill or seriously injure those in their care.
Hospitals nationwide would have to disclose serious and deadly mistakes if
Congress adopts a White House plan developed in response to a report last year
that estimated medical mix-ups kill as many as 98,000 Americans each year.
Clinton also planned Tuesday to order several new requirements that do not need
congressional approval, including an immediate mandatory reporting requirement
for the 500 Defense Department-administered hospitals that serve an estimated 8
million people.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Final Microsoft Arguments To Begin
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Settlement talks in the Microsoft Corp. antitrust lawsuit
are going so poorly that the trial judge is moving ahead with plans for final
courtroom arguments before his verdict. U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield
Jackson didn't see any need to delay the last round of arguments, set for
Tuesday, to accommodate ongoing secret negotiations in Chicago between
government lawyers and Microsoft officials. Though sources indicate little
progress, negotiations are aimed at averting an agonizingly slow appeals battle
that could wind through the federal courts for years.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Texas Inmates Take Officer Hostage
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   LIVINGSTON, Texas (AP) -- Two death row inmates who were part of a botched
escape in 1998 took a female guard hostage Monday in a new prison that was
supposed to be more secure. The guard was taking one inmate back to his cell at
about 4:15 p.m. when he and another inmate overpowered her, said Texas
Department of Criminal Justice spokesman Larry Fitzgerald. One inmate had
somehow jimmied his cell door, Fitzgerald said. "They have no place to go.
Officers have sealed off the area," he said. "She has not been threatened or
harmed in any way, but it is a tense situation."
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stock Prices Close Lower
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   TOKYO (AP) -- The Nikkei shed 153.17 points to close at 19,390.58.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Nuggets 123, Kings 117, OT
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   DENVER (AP) -- Antonio McDyess had 29 points and 13 rebounds, and the Denver
Nuggets hit 12 3-pointers Monday night in a 123-117 overtime victory over the
Sacramento Kings. Nick Van Exel added 27 points and 15 assists for the Nuggets.
Predrag Stojakovic scored a career-high 30 points and Chris Webber had 25 points
and 15 rebounds for the Kings, who lost their second straight overtime game.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Suns 98, Spurs 89
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   SAN ANTONIO (AP) -- Taking advantage of an injury to Tim Duncan, Rodney
Rogers scored 22 points to lead the Phoenix Suns to a 98-89 come-from-behind
victory over the San Antonio Spurs on Monday night. Duncan left the game with
11:08 to play in the second quarter with a lower abdominal strain. Tom Gugliotta
added 21 points for Phoenix, which extended its winning streak to six games.
</P>
<P>
	   AP NewsBrief by VINCENT K. WILLIS
</P>
