<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 03:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Makes Little Headway in Suits  </HEADLINE>
   By JIM ABRAMS Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Once again this year, House Republicans are pushing
through legislation to protect businesses from costly, pernicious lawsuits. And
once again, there is almost no chance their determination to enact change will
succeed.
</P>
<P>
	   Legal reform was a cornerstone of the ``Contract With America'' campaign
manifesto that guided Republicans after they seized control of the House five
years ago. Their inability to overcome opposition from the White House,
Democrats and their powerful trial lawyer and consumer group allies has been an
abiding frustration.
</P>
<P>
	   In 1996 President Clinton vetoed a far-reaching bill limiting punitive
damage awards in cases involving faulty products. Two years later the Senate
came close, but eventually failed to pass a more modest bill covering small
businesses.
</P>
<P>
	   This year Republican leaders have shifted to a strategy similar to one they
are employing for tax cuts: Instead of putting forth one giant bill that has no
chance of escaping a veto, they are pursuing smaller bills they hope will be
more palatable to the White House.
</P>
<P>
	   The party is taking ``an incremental and pragmatic way by focusing on a few
narrowly crafted reforms,'' said Rep. James Rogan, R-Calif., whose bill to set a
$250,000 punitive damage cap on awards against companies with fewer than 25
employees passed the House last week.
</P>
<P>
	   As with taxes, ``we want to take one bite out of the apple at a time,'' said
Pete Jefferies, spokesman for House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill.
</P>
<P>
	   The White House, however, has shown no more inclination to accept narrow
measures than a broad one. It says the president will veto Rogan's bill because
it could seriously undermine the rights of victims to be compensated for
wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
	   Similarly, a veto threat hangs over a bill the House passed last fall that
would curb what some say are abuses in class-action lawsuits. Also facing a veto
is a bill passed this month that would prevent workers injured by aging
equipment from suing the manufacturer if the piece of machinery was more than 18
years old.
</P>
<P>
	   The House Judiciary Committee, meanwhile, is in an uphill struggle to find
an acceptable formula for processing asbestos claims and putting a cap on
punitive damage in asbestos cases.
</P>
<P>
	   The debate over liability lawsuits dates back to the 1960s when state courts
expanded the rights of claimants, ruling that they can make a case against a
defendant who sold a product that caused damage without proving that the
defendant was negligent or involved in intentional wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
	   Business groups say this has been a windfall for trial lawyers -- noting
that in 1998 there were eight jury verdicts topping $100 million -- and a
serious drag on economic growth. Supporters of the small business bill in the
House said 20 percent of small businesses refrain from expanding or hiring new
workers because they fear being sued.
</P>
<P>
	   Trial lawyers and consumer groups argue that stories of a system out of
control are overblown. Tom Bantle of Public Citizen's Congress Watch said there
are only about 15 product liability punitive damage awards a year. ``We don't
really think there is a huge problem out there.''
</P>
<P>
	   They also argue that it's ill-advised to change a system that has made the
nation a safer place to live and work. ``All of these tort reform measures are
corporate welfare, shifting the burden of responsibility and the cost of injury
caused by a company to the victim and the taxpayer,'' said Carlton Carl,
spokesman for the Association of Trial Lawyers of America.
</P>
<P>
	   Victor Schwartz, general counsel of the American Tort Reform Association,
says he feels the battle for change has shifted. The big threat now, he says, is
an effort by the federal government to regulate through litigation. He cites the
Justice Department's lawsuit against the tobacco industry.
</P>
<P>
	   Republicans have had some success. In 1995, Congress overrode Clinton's veto
of legislation limiting claims against security firms when stocks change in
value.
</P>
<P>
	   And the president has stated his support for ``common sense'' litigation
reform. Last year, for example, he signed a bill giving suppliers of raw
materials for medical devices some protections from lawsuits. After lengthy
discussions with lawmakers, Clinton also signed a bill to limit what some people
feared would be a deluge of Y2K computer-related lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
	   Supporters of change say it may take a new president to get any more. They
point to Republican hopeful Gov. George W. Bush's push for lawsuit limits in his
home state of Texas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-22-00 0307 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000222.0073 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 03:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Some Stores To Get Irradiated Meat  </HEADLINE>
   By PHILIP BRASHER AP Farm Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Beef that is irradiated to kill deadly bacteria will
begin appearing in some stores as early as March as processors start testing the
public's reaction to the treated meat.
</P>
<P>
	   New rules that allow the irradiation of raw beef, pork and lamb take effect
today.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We view this as a consumer choice issue. The consumer will ultimately
determine the success,'' said Gary Mickelson, a spokesman for the nation's
biggest beef processor, IBP Inc., which plans to begin test-marketing irradiated
hamburger patties next month.
</P>
<P>
	   No. 2 Excel Corp. plans to start shipping treated beef to its food service
customers the first week of March.
</P>
<P>
	   Initially, irradiated meat is likely to be most popular with hospitals and
nursing homes, because of the danger E. coli poses to patients with weakened
immune systems. But its use there could generate interest from consumers, said
Tim Willard, a spokesman for the National Food Processors Association.
</P>
<P>
	   Christine Bruhn, director of the Center for Consumer Research at the
University of California-Davis, said the public is ready to try the meat.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Most people are ready. They are sick and tired of hearing of cases of
food-borne outbreaks,'' said Bruhn.
</P>
<P>
	   The meat is expected to cost an extra three to five cents per pound but the
price is likely to drop as it becomes more widely available.
</P>
<P>
	   Irradiation has long been allowed for poultry, as well as fruits, vegetables
and spices. It is seldom used on poultry, partly because the primary pathogens
aren't as dangerous as E. coli, and chicken processors haven't thought it was
worth the expense, say industry experts. One big recall for E. coli, however,
can devastate a meatpacker financially.
</P>
<P>
	   The irradiation is done by three methods -- gamma rays, X-rays, or electron
beams. In addition to eliminating E. coli, the treatment can significantly
reduce levels of other pathogens, including listeria, salmonella and
campylobacter. The food isn't radioactive, and while there is a slight loss of
nutrients, the food is largely unchanged, according to the Food and Drug
Administration.
</P>
<P>
	   FDA also is considering allowing irradiation for hot dogs, luncheon meats
and other ready-to-eat products.
</P>
<P>
	   Special labels are required, carrying the international symbol of
irradiation, known as a ``radura,'' and a statement that they were treated. The
symbol, colored green on a white background, depicts two leaves resting in a
semicircle, with a green dot above it beneath a broken-lined semicircle.
</P>
<P>
	   E. coli O157 can cause serious illness and sometimes death, especially in
children and the elderly. An estimated 73,480 people are infected every year,
and about 600 cases are fatal, according to the federal Centers for Disease
Control and Prevention.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This is an extra layer of food safety,'' said Mark Klein, a spokesman for
Excel, which blasts beef carcasses with steam to kill E. coli. ``We definitely
view it as an additional tool and not a replacement for other technologies or
food safety programs.''
</P>
<P>
	   A smaller, Florida-based processer, Colorado Boxed Beef Co., plans to sell
irradiated meat through grocery chains in the Southeast.
</P>
<P>
	   The company had to recall 359,000 pounds beef products in November 1998
because of possible contamination with the deadly E. coli bacteria, and Florida
officials have been promoting irradiation heavily.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-22-00 0308 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
