<HEADLINE> NYC Police Shooting Case Nears End  </HEADLINE>
   By TOM HAYS Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Was Amadou Diallo's death at the hands of New York City
police a mistake or murder?
</P>
<P>
	   Closing arguments were to begin today in the trial of four white officers
accused of killing the unarmed black immigrant.
</P>
<P>
	   Defendants Sean Carroll, 37, Edward McMellon, 27, Kenneth Boss, 28, and
Richard Murphy, 27, have pleaded innocent to second-degree murder charges in the
February 1999 death of Diallo, 22.
</P>
<P>
	   The trial was moved to Albany after the shooting sparked protests and
allegations of widespread police abuse of minorities.
</P>
<P>
	   If convicted of murder, the officers face a maximum sentence of 25 years to
life in prison. However, Supreme Court Justice Joseph Teresi opened the door for
a compromise verdict last week by ruling jurors will be able to convict on less
serious charges such as second-degree manslaughter, which carries a minimum
penalty of probation.
</P>
<P>
	   Prosecutors allege officers cornered Diallo in the vestibule of his Bronx
apartment building before unleashing a ``wall of lead.'' Forty-one shots were
fired, and Diallo was hit 19 times.
</P>
<P>
	   The officers were in street clothes as they searched Diallo's neighborhood
for armed suspects. They contend they had good reason for stopping him, and for
firing in self-defense.
</P>
<P>
	   In testimony last week, the officers all told a similar story: Diallo
ignored repeated orders by Carroll and McMellon to stop for questioning after
they got out of their unmarked car, badges out.
</P>
<P>
	   They said he darted into the dimly lit vestibule and pointed a black object
they were certain was a gun, and that he also remained upright during a
continuous volley that lasted about 10 seconds.
</P>
<P>
	   Boss testified that when he first spotted Diallo, he thought, ``My God, I'm
gonna die.'' And Carroll wept on the stand while he recalled the shock of
realizing the black object ``was just a wallet.''
</P>
<P>
	   But Diallo's neighbors, testifying for the prosecution, said they didn't
hear officers' voices before sporadic gunfire erupted. And a coroner who
performed Diallo's autopsy told jurors that wounds showed he was either falling
or flat on his back when most of the rounds hit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
