<HEADLINE> Notes and Quotes From Campaign 2000  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT (AP) -- Gov. George W. Bush and Sen. John McCain on the same ticket?
</P>
<P>
	   It seemed a distant possibility for a moment Monday when Bush answered a
reporter's question about whether his rival for the GOP presidential nomination
would make a good running mate.
</P>
<P>
	   Bush thought he was asked about another John -- his supporter, Michigan Gov.
John Engler.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I've always said, 'Should the person be president, do we share the same
philosophy and does he like me?' And I think the man fills those three
categories, but nevertheless, I haven't put lists together,'' Bush said, giving
his usual answer to queries about potential running mates.
</P>
<P>
	   When pressed on whether he thought McCain fit the third category -- of
liking him -- press secretary Karen Hughes stepped in to correct Bush's
misinterpretation of the question.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Oh, you said John McCain, or John Engler?'' Bush asked, Engler standing at
his side.
</P>
<P>
	   When told the question was about McCain, he said, ``Oh, let me start over.''
</P>
<P>
	   Bush then apologized to McCain, saying he did not want to demean the senator
by talking about him in terms of being a running mate.
</P>
<P>
	   ``As long as he's a viable presidential candidate, he deserves the respect
and ought not to be talked about in terms of the vice presidency,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   BY THE NUMBERS:
</P>
<P>
	   4 minutes, 45 seconds -- Average nightly news time devoted to the
presidential campaign by NBC since Feb. 1.
</P>
<P>
	   4 minutes, 20 seconds -- ABC.
</P>
<P>
	   3 minutes, 21 seconds -- CBS.
</P>
<P>
	   (Source: Alliance for Better Campaigns)
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   VOTER'S VOICE:
</P>
<P>
	   ``Without strong competition like John McCain, I think he (Bush) probably
would have thought he could coast to the nomination. I think he's shown us he
has the right stuff.'' -- Barbara Gattorn, 63, of Grosse Pointe, Mich., after
hearing Texas Gov. George W. Bush speak Monday at the Economic Club of Detroit.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   THIS DATE FOUR YEARS AGO:
</P>
<P>
	   In frosty Fargo, N.D., Sen. Bob Dole pored over the math of his narrow New
Hampshire loss to Pat Buchanan and declared, ``We get the message.''
</P>
<P>
	   Promising to campaign more aggressively, Dole depicted the contest as ``a
race between mainstream conservatism and extremism.''
</P>
<P>
	   As he moved west into what he hoped would be more fertile political ground,
Dole's campaign sought to persuade Indiana Sen. Dick Lugar to quit the
presidential race and support him.
</P>
<P>
	   Dole described his humbling loss to Buchanan as ``a little bump in the
road.''
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   MONDAY'S ROUNDUP:
</P>
<P>
	   McCain accused Bush of running a campaign by ``character assassination''
with TV ads leading up to Michigan's GOP primary Tuesday. Bush, who said he was
``taking nothing for granted'' in Michigan after his victory in South Carolina,
focused on his economic proposals with a speech in Detroit.
</P>
<P>
	   Warming up for their debate at the Apollo Theatre, Vice President Al Gore
walked the streets of Harlem. Bill Bradley questioned Gore's willingness to help
people who don't have health insurance.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
