<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 04:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Search finds missing snowmobiler's body  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   MINETTO, N.Y. (AP) - An autopsy is scheduled today for a junior high
school teacher who died in 20 feet of icy river.
<P>
	   Kip L. Kelsey, 28, died sometime after he drove along the Oswego River late
Saturday or early Sunday as he was returning home after a day of snowmobiling
with friends.
</P>
<P>
	   Kelsey had illegally crossed the Minetto bridge on his snowmobile and then
took a risky route along the partially frozen Oswego River toward Fulton, police
said.
</P>
<P>
	   Kelsey attempted to skim over a 100-yard expanse of open water, State
Trooper Joseph Saarie told the Syracuse Herald-Journal. But his skis apparently
caught the edge of the ice, sending him and the sled under water.
</P>
<P>
	   State police divers found the body Monday evening in 20 feet of water about
300 feet from shore. They found his snowmobile in the same spot the day before.
</P>
<P>
	   The other snowmobilers said Kelsey had consumed alcohol on Saturday,
according to state police Sgt. Dale R. Crisp.
</P>
<P>
	   On Sunday morning, friends found Kelsey's helmet on a patch of ice atop the
river. Divers located the snowmobile in the river Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
	   Rough terrain along the icy river made the search difficult. State police
used a front-end loader to dump sand over a steep bluff so rescuers had better
footing as they carried down heavy rafts and other equipment, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Divers had to fight swift currents, Crisp said.
</P>
<P>
	   Kelsey, who had an infant daughter with his girlfriend, was a popular
technology teacher at Fulton Junior High School, where he taught for the past
five years.
</P>
<P>
	   Three weeks earlier, Kelsey had shattered his left ankle in a snowmobile
accident and he was still wearing a cast during his last ride.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
