<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Federal prosecutors try to strip dentist of license  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) - Federal prosecutors plan to push for the revocation
of a dentist's license today in U.S. District Court.
<P>
	   Last fall, prosecutors accused Dr. Tejbir Oberoi, of Amherst, of giving his
patients painful unnecessary dental procedures and cheating the health care
system out of thousands of dollars.
</P>
<P>
	   Dr. Oberoi allegedly submitted claims to MetLife, Blue Cross and Blue
Shield, Aetna and other insurers for expensive procedures that he did not
perform.
</P>
<P>
	   Oberoi, who operates Khalsa Dental and Implant Center in Buffalo, pleaded
innocent in October before U.S. Magistrate Judge Carol Heckman. He said the
billing problems were simple mistakes.
</P>
<P>
	   But authorities claim the alleged fraud was widespread. Four months later,
Oberoi is still practicing dentistry in his downtown Buffalo clinic and
authorities claim he is still committing crimes.
</P>
<P>
	   Among the 157 fraud counts against Oberoi is the allegation that he billed a
Cheektowaga widow for 550 dental visits over a 12-year period, including
numerous gum surgeries, root canals, tooth implants and crowns that were
unnecessary and, in many cases, performed incorrectly.
</P>
<P>
	   Another claim against him is that when a woman drove her sister to the
clinic for dental treatment, Oberoi followed the driver out to her car and
convinced her that she, too, must come in for a root canal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
