<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 'American Beauty' Interests Marietta  </HEADLINE>
    By CHAD ROEDEMEIER Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   MARIETTA, Ga. (AP) -- "American Beauty" never reveals the exact location of
its achingly generic setting. The homogeneous homes, strip malls and SUVs could
be anywhere.
</P>
<P>
	   But many residents of this conservative suburb just across the Chattahoochee
River from Atlanta suspect there's more than a little of Marietta up there on
the screen.
</P>
<P>
	   Folks here aren't just paranoid. After all, screenwriter Alan Ball, who
received one of the film's eight Academy Award nominations, grew up in Marietta.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's so real it makes some people uncomfortable," said Corky Pratt,
technical director at Theatre in the Square in Marietta. "I think it's a great
depiction of suburban life."
</P>
<P>
	   Marietta is perhaps best known as the headquarters of former House Speaker
Newt Gingrich. Exactly how much of Marietta seeped into "American Beauty" is
unclear. Ball said some of his inspiration came from observing his family and
neighbors while growing up here, but he insists Marietta wasn't the model for
the satire.
</P>
<P>
	   "American Beauty" tells the story of Lester Burnham, a middle-aged man
sedated by life in the suburbs. Burnham, played by Kevin Spacey, hates his job
and can't understand his petty, grasping wife.
</P>
<P>
	   "I never intended the movie to be an indictment of suburbia," Ball told The
Associated Press last week. "There are plenty of well-adjusted, healthy,
spiritual people living in the suburbs."
</P>
<P>
	   But the suburbs weren't the happiest place for Ball. His parents moved to
Marietta in the late 1950s just before he was born. His mother suffered from
depression and his father had troubles of his own, Ball said.
</P>
<P>
	   In a recent interview with the Los Angeles Times, Ball described his
Marietta neighbors as "shut down and living in total denial," a theme that turns
up in his movie. "To me, it was a town I had to get out of."
</P>
<P>
	   Ball left to pursue his writing career, but he also wanted to leave because
he felt his homosexuality wasn't always accepted in Marietta.
</P>
<P>
	   "Marietta is not exactly the most friendly place for gay people," Ball told
the AP. "I would rather be in a place where no one cares, as opposed to a place
where people are going to define me by that one aspect of my personality."
</P>
<P>
	   Marietta is the seat of Cobb County, whose commissioners passed a resolution
in 1993 condemning the "gay lifestyle." That prompted Olympic officials to move
all its events out of the county in 1996, even the ceremonial torch run.
</P>
<P>
	   Just this week, a downtown Marietta restaurant displayed a sign saying,
"John Rocker for President," a reference to the Atlanta Braves pitcher who said
he didn't want to ride on a subway in New York next to, among others, "some
queer with AIDS."
</P>
<P>
	   But even if some of "American Beauty" has its roots in Marietta, residents
here may still have reason to cheer. The film is the favorite to win several
Oscars, including best original screenplay for Ball.
</P>
<P>
	   "We're just so proud of him and his work and his accomplishments," said
Marietta Mayor Ansley Meaders, who has not seen the movie. "That's just a
wonderful honor for him and for our community."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-22-00 0853 </TRAILER>
