<DOCNO> APW20000222.0089 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 10:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jury hears closing arguments in Diallo trial  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - The officers involved in the shooting death of
Amadou Diallo had an obligation to stop the West African immigrant as he stood
in the vestibule of his Bronx building because he was acting suspiciously, a
defense attorney said during closing arguments today.
<P>
	   Attorney James Culleton said he expected prosecutors to argue that Diallo
had a right to stand in front of his home and was not doing anything wrong.
However, he asked jurors to remember a neighbor's testimony that Diallo had been
peering out and looking up and down the street.
</P>
<P>
	   "On Feb. 4, 1999, these four police officers, they didn't know who Mr.
Diallo was. They didn't know he lived in that building," said Culleton, who
represents Officer Richard Murphy. "And they had an obligation, following proper
police procedure, to stop, to walk up to Mr. Diallo and ask, 'Who are you?' and
'Why are you in this area?"'
</P>
<P>
	   "Mr. Diallo was alone. It was a cold night and it was 12:40 a.m. in the
morning," the attorney said. "Would you, or would you expect any police officer
in the Bronx, Albany or anywhere else in the United States, do anything less?"
</P>
<P>
	   Culleton urged the jurors to listen carefully to the judge's charges on
"proper police conduct."
</P>
<P>
	   "The police officers did nothing wrong in stopping their vehicle this
night," he said. "This case is really about what happened after they got out of
the vehicle. It's about an incident that escalated and resulted in a tragedy in
a few seconds."
</P>
<P>
	   He reminded jurors that prosecutors admitted police had the right to stop
people who are acting suspiciously and ask them what they were doing, which is
what he said the four officers did the night of the shooting.
</P>
<P>
	   "Why Mr. Diallo acted the way he did to this simple request to talk, we'll
never know," Culleton said.
</P>
<P>
	   Murphy, 27, and co-defendants Sean Carroll, 37, Edward McMellon, 27, Kenneth
Boss, 28 - all white - have pleaded innocent to second-degree murder in the
killing of Diallo, 22, a black West African immigrant. Their trial was moved to
Albany after protests and allegations of widespread police abuse of minorities.
</P>
<P>
	   If convicted of murder, the officers face a maximum sentence of 25 years to
life in prison. However, State Supreme Court Justice Joseph Teresi opened the
door for a compromise verdict last week by ruling that jurors would be able to
convict on less serious charges such as second-degree manslaughter, which has a
minimum penalty of probation.
</P>
<P>
	   Prosecutors allege the defendants cornered the victim in the elevator-size
vestibule of his apartment building at 12:40 a.m. on Feb. 4, 1999, then, without
warning, unleashed 41 bullets - a "wall of lead." The victim was hit 19 times.
</P>
<P>
	   The officers were in street clothes as they searched Diallo's neighborhood
for armed suspects. They contend they had good reason for stopping him and for
firing in self-defense with their rapid-fire semiautomatics.
</P>
<P>
	   In testimony last week, the officers told a similar story: Diallo ignored
repeated orders by Carroll and McMellon to stop for questioning after they got
out of their unmarked car, badges out. He darted into his dimly lighted
vestibule and pointed a black object they were certain was a gun. He also
remained upright as they fired a continuous volley lasting less than 10 seconds.
</P>
<P>
	   Boss testified last week that when he first spotted Diallo, he thought, "My
God, I'm gonna die." Carroll wept on the stand while he recalled the shock of
realizing the black object "was just a wallet. ... I said, 'Where's the
(expletive) gun?"'
</P>
<P>
	   But several prosecution "ear witnesses," mainly neighbors of Diallo,
testified they never heard the officers' voices before sporadic gunfire erupted.
A coroner who autopsied the victim told jurors his wounds showed that he was
either falling or flat on his back when most of the bullets hit.
</P>
<P>
	   Carroll and McMellon were the first to shoot, squeezing off all 16 rounds
from their guns. Boss fired five times and Murphy four while backing up their
partners, leading to speculation they have the best chance at acquittal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-22-00 1016 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000222.0090 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 10:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Court To Study Traffic Stops  </HEADLINE>
   By RICHARD CARELLI Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court today agreed to decide whether police
routinely can set up traffic checkpoints and stop motorists in hopes of catching
people who sell or use illegal drugs.
</P>
<P>
	   The justices will review a federal appeals court ruling that said
checkpoints where Indianapolis police detained most motorists for about three
minutes likely amounted to unreasonable and unlawful seizures.
</P>
<P>
	   At issue is the scope of the Constitution's Fourth Amendment and its
protection against unreasonable searches and seizures.
</P>
<P>
	   Police generally need a court warrant or a reason to suspect someone of a
crime before detaining them for several minutes. But in past rulings, the
nation's highest court allowed police to set up sobriety checkpoints aimed at
randomly detecting inebriated motorists and border roadblocks to intercept
illegal immigrants.
</P>
<P>
	   The 7th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals said the checkpoints formerly used by
Indianapolis are different. ``The city concedes that its proximate goal is to
catch drug offenders in the hope of incapacitating them, and deterring others,
by criminal prosecution,'' the appeals court said.
</P>
<P>
	   If Indianapolis police had reason to believe a terrorist was driving toward
the city in a car packed with dynamite, they could block all roads and stop
thousands of drivers ``without suspecting any one of them with criminal
activity,'' the appeals court said. ``But no such urgency has been shown here.''
</P>
<P>
	   The city began its ``narcotics checkpoints'' operation in the summer of
1998. A predetermined number of cars are pulled over at one time and drivers are
asked to show police their licenses and car registration while drug-sniffing dog
walks around the parked cars.
</P>
<P>
	   In the program's first four months, police conducted six roadblocks in
high-crime areas and stopped 1,161 vehicles. The stops led to 104 arrests, 55 of
them on drug-related charges.
</P>
<P>
	   Two Indianapolis residents, James Edmond and Joell Palmer, challenged the
program in a lawsuit that called the police tactics unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
	   A federal trial judge ruled that the city was not violating any rights, but
a three-judge panel of the 7th Circuit court reversed that ruling by a 2-1 vote
last July.
</P>
<P>
	   The appeals court said the trial judge may find another reason to uphold the
checkpoint program, which has been suspended. ``The high hit rate of
Indianapolis' roadblock scheme suggests ... areas of the city in which drug use
approaches epidemic proportions. If so, the roadblocks may be justified,'' it
said.
</P>
<P>
	   In the appeal acted on today, city officials said federal and state courts
are deeply divided over the legitimacy of such initiatives. They urged the
justices ``to restore predictability and rationality to the rules that guide''
encounters between police and citizens.
</P>
<P>
	   But lawyers for the program's challengers said most courts have barred
police from setting up checkpoints ``whose sole purpose is to investigate
criminal activity.'' Courts are deeply split only over those checkpoint programs
that combine routine traffic-law regulation and drug interdiction, they said.
</P>
<P>
	   The case is Indianapolis vs. Edmond, 99-1030.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-22-00 1020 </TRAILER>
