<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 10:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pork Tongue Blamed for Listeria  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    PARIS (AP) -- Officials said Tuesday that pork tongue in gelatin was the
likely culprit in a listeria epidemic that has killed seven people in France.
</P>
<P>
	   Dominique Gillot, the deputy minister for health and social action, advised
everyone against eating the product "while waiting for formal confirmation."
</P>
<P>
	   Since the end of November, the bacteria, which most often flourishes in
cheese and meat products, has contaminated 23 people, killing seven of them and
leading to one abortion.
</P>
<P>
	   Agriculture Minister Jean Glavany has called the poisonings an "epidemic."
</P>
<P>
	   A 74-year-old man hospitalized in Grenoble since Thursday with listeria is
an unrelated case, local officials there said Tuesday -- not part of the
epidemic.
</P>
<P>
	   A statement from the Labor Ministry said that epidemiological tests have
pointed to pork tongue in gelatin as "very likely the main mode of transmission"
of the Listeria monocytogenes bacteria.
</P>
<P>
	   It said, however, that no brand name had been identified and that tests were
continuing.
</P>
<P>
	   The pork tongue "was eaten by the majority of people" who contracted the
illness and were questioned, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
	   A bacteriological investigation of the food chain is in progress, the
ministry statement said, and should allow for confirmation of the initial
findings in the coming days.
</P>
<P>
	   Healthy people rarely contract listeriosis, which can cause high fever,
severe headaches, neck stiffness and nausea. It can be potentially fatal to
people with weak immune systems -- infants, the elderly, chemotherapy patients
and people with HIV infections or other chronic diseases. Listeriosis, which can
take up to eight weeks to incubate, can also cause miscarriages and stillbirths.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
