<HEADLINE> Dow Down 108.66; Nasdaq Down 59.15  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks dropped in early trading today, continuing last
week's big decline. Computer and telecommunications shares were mostly higher on
earnings and acquisition news.
</P>
<P>
	   In the first hour of trading, the Dow Jones industrial average gave up early
gains and was down 108.66 at 10,110.86.
</P>
<P>
	   The technology-focused Nasdaq composite index was off 59.15 at 4,352.59. The
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was off 6.03 at 1,340.06.
</P>
<P>
	   Trading was tentative in the first session following Friday's big drop. The
Dow fell 295 points and the Nasdaq lost 137 after Federal Reserve Chairman Alan
Greenspan suggested more rate increases may be needed to cool off the economy
and keep inflation under control.
</P>
<P>
	   But some individual stocks moved solidly higher.
</P>
<P>
	   SBC Communications, a regional telephone company, announced it would spend
$3.9 billion in cash to acquire Sterling Commerce Inc., a provider of Internet
integration software. SBC's shares rose 1/16 to 36 1/2, while Sterling's shares
soared 12 to 43 9/16.
</P>
<P>
	   In other news moving the markets, Nextel Communications, a wireless phone
company, reported a lower-than-expected loss in its most recent quarter, and
said it would split its stock 2-for-1. Nextel's shares jumped 7 to 125 11/16.
</P>
<P>
	   Shares of Oracle rose 2 9/16 to 61 1/8 on news the software maker formed
several partnerships with Internet-related companies.
</P>
<P>
	   The Russell 2000 index of small company stocks was down 0.77 at 544.91.
</P>
<P>
	   Volume on the New York Stock Exchange was 137.41 million shares down from
the 168.99 million the same time Friday. The markets were closed Monday in
observance of Presidents Day.
</P>
<P>
	   Advancing issues slightly outnumbered declining issues on the NYSE.
</P>
<P>
	   In overseas markets, the Nikkei average in Tokyo fell 0.78 percent. In
Europe, markets were mixed, with Britain's FTSE index down 0.15 percent, the
Paris CAC up 0.41 percent and the German DAX up 0.88 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
