<HEADLINE> Ex-New York Mob Boss Loses Appeal  </HEADLINE>
   By RICHARD CARELLI Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Former mob boss Vittorio ``Vic'' Amuso, who once ran the
third largest of New York City's five crime families, lost a Supreme Court
appeal today.
</P>
<P>
	   The court, without comment, rejected an appeal in which Amuso said federal
courts failed to fully consider his claim that he was denied effective legal
help when convicted in 1992 for 14 murders and other crimes.
</P>
<P>
	   Amuso, former leader of the Lucchese crime family, was sentenced to life
imprisonment without parole and fined $250,000 for convictions on 54 counts of
racketeering, extortion, fraud, bribery and murder.
</P>
<P>
	   One court spoke of Amuso's ``murderous campaign'' to eliminate anyone
connected with his criminal organization suspected of disloyalty.
</P>
<P>
	   The Supreme Court rejected Amuso's direct appeal in 1994. He began a second
round of appeals in 1997, contending before a federal judge that his trial
lawyer, Gerald Shargel, provided ineffective assistance because of alleged
conflicts of interest.
</P>
<P>
	   Shargel's potential conflicts -- he was under government investigation and
had represented some people who were possible trial witnesses -- had been
discussed before Amuso's trial, and Amuso had told the trial judge, ``I still
want him as my attorney.''
</P>
<P>
	   Lawyers later hired by Amuso said some of the alleged conflicts had been
``unwaiveable as a matter of law.''
</P>
<P>
	   In the appeal acted on today, Amuso's lawyers said the consideration of his
ineffective-assistance claim was unfairly truncated by restrictions on court
review imposed by a 1996 law, the Antiterrorism and Effective Death Penalty Act,
which was aimed at streamlining the appeals process.
</P>
<P>
	   The case is Amuso vs. U.S., 99-1075.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
