<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Animals Studied As Quake Predictors  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    TOKYO (AP) -- Chinese and Japanese scientists exchanged views Tuesday on the
possibilities of using animal behavior to predict earthquakes.
</P>
<P>
	   Yoshihiro Hayashi, a professor of veterinary science at Tokyo University who
helped organized the seminar, acknowledged that the conventional scientific
wisdom is that earthquakes can't be predicted.
</P>
<P>
	   He added that the question of whether animal behavior can be used to
foretell quakes is almost impossible to prove scientifically, and such findings
may even do more harm than good by setting off panic if publicized prematurely.
</P>
<P>
	   "But it is an interesting possibility. Animals have evolved to avoid
dangers," Hayashi said in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
	   Zheng Guorong, vice director of the earthquake department in Tangshan in
Hebei Province in northern China, presented findings about fish that jumped out
of the water as well as moles, bugs and hibernating animals popping out from the
ground right before an earthquake.
</P>
<P>
	   Zheng and another Chinese researcher, Wang Anbin, told the gathering that
they were able to use animal behavior along with other observed natural changes
to predict several earthquakes in China.
</P>
<P>
	   A handful of Japanese scientists are also carrying out studies on how
animals act before earthquakes. Mitsuaki Ota, a professor at Azabu University
who has done research with dogs, also attended the seminar.
</P>
<P>
	   Earlier in the week, the Chinese scientists gave a similar presentation in
Kobe, the city devastated by a quake that killed more than 6,000 people in 1995.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-22-00 1044 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000222.0102 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 10:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> California Franchise Tax Law KO'd  </HEADLINE>
   By RICHARD CARELLI Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- California unfairly taxes out-of-state businesses under a
franchise tax law in place since 1955, the Supreme Court ruled unanimously
today.
</P>
<P>
	   The court struck down the law, saying it discriminated against interstate
commerce and allowed the state to indirectly tax income it has no authority to
tax directly.
</P>
<P>
	   The decision is a victory for Hunt-Wesson Inc., which had challenged the
franchise tax law's impact on the California taxes it had to pay for the three
years 1980-82.
</P>
<P>
	   The eventual impact on California's state treasury could be significant.
More than $400,000 in taxes and more than $1 million in interest was at stake
for Hunt-Wesson in those three years. About 40,000 other companies file returns
with the state Franchise Tax Board, which collected $5.8 billion in 1998.
</P>
<P>
	   It was not immediately clear whether today's decision entitles other
companies to seek partial refunds for taxes previously paid. It definitely will
reduce the amount of taxes collected under the law from now on.
</P>
<P>
	   The justices found fault with the law's restriction on deductions that
companies not based in California could claim for interest paid as business
expenses.
</P>
<P>
	   Under the franchise tax law, those deductions were offset dollar for dollar
against the interest and dividend income a company received from its
subsidiaries outside California -- income the state is barred from taxing.
</P>
<P>
	   California's tax law appeared to be unique. The justices were told that no
other state counts 100 percent of such earnings against business-expense
deductions.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Because California's offset provision is not a reasonable allocation of
expense deductions to the income that the expense generates, it constitutes
impermissible taxation of income outside its jurisdictional reach,'' Justice
Stephen G. Breyer wrote for the court.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The provision therefore violates the due-process and commerce clauses of
the Constitution,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   The law seemed in trouble when the case was argued before the nation's
highest court in January. ``It's just irrational,'' Justice Antonin Scalia said
then of the tax scheme, and Justice Sandra Day O'Connor told a deputy California
attorney general: ``I haven't found anything in what you said to find this
reasonable.''
</P>
<P>
	   Hunt-Wesson markets Hunt's tomato products, Wesson oil, Butterball turkey
and Swiss Miss cocoa. When the tax dispute began, the taxpayer was Beatrice
Companies Inc., which later merged with Hunt-Wesson.
</P>
<P>
	   The corporation was based in Illinois back then but since has moved to
California. It received $75 million from its out-of-state subsidiaries in the
three years in question, and state tax officials did not attempt to tax that
income.
</P>
<P>
	   But when the corporation claimed a $153 million deduction for interest paid
as a business expense, the franchise tax board said the interest paid had to be
offset by the subsidiary income. The result: a smaller deduction and a larger
tax bill.
</P>
<P>
	   The case is Hunt-Wesson Inc. vs. Franchise Tax Board, 98-2043.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-22-00 1057 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
