<HEADLINE> Truckers head for Washington to protest high fuel prices  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   DEEPWATER, N.J. (AP) - Irate over rising fuel prices, dozens of truckers
headed for the nation's capital this morning in hopes of raising the federal
government's awareness of their dilemma.
<P>
	   Members of the National Owner-Operators Trucking Association sent a convoy
of more than 40 dump trucks, tractor-trailers and tractor cabs from here at
dawn.
</P>
<P>
	   They rendezvoused at a truck stop near the Delaware Memorial Bridge,
departing for Washington about 7:15. State police cars escorted the convoy from
Joe's Truck Stop on Route 40 onto Interstate-295 as they began the trip south.
</P>
<P>
	   Two other groups from Maryland were to meet them and converge on the
nation's capital by about 11 a.m. today, organizers said.
</P>
<P>
	   About 100 trucks traveled through Baltimore's Fort McHenry tunnel beginning
about 9:30 a.m., and were joined by about 75 more trucks in Jessup, Md.,
Maryland state police spokesman Pete Piringer said.
</P>
<P>
	   Police along the route reported no major problems.
</P>
<P>
	   "They're going about 30-40 mph and are restricted to one lane. So far,
there's no major problems, but they are causing a bit of spectacle in Howard
County," Piringer said.
</P>
<P>
	   Charles Hentz, a spokesman for the New Jersey group, said he expected about
300 trucks to be in the procession once it reaches the Washington area.
</P>
<P>
	   The truckers want President Clinton to repeal the federal excise tax on
diesel fuel, which Hentz said is 24 cents a gallon, until the price of fuel goes
back down to $1 a gallon.
</P>
<P>
	   He said diesel fuel now costs up to $2.50 a gallon in some places and that
truckers can't charge enough to meet their overhead. The price of diesel fuel
has doubled over the last year, Hentz said.
</P>
<P>
	   "This is a funeral procession," he said. "If you don't do something about
the cost of fuel and tolls in the next 60 days, we're buried."
</P>
<P>
	   The trucks were adorned with hand-lettered signs. Among them was one on the
back of a dump truck that read: "Thank a trucker. If you live in it, if you wear
it, if you eat it, we brought it to you."
</P>
<P>
	   Mark Cornell, 35, of Browns Mills, N.J., was among the participants. He said
he's frustrated by his inability to get ahead.
</P>
<P>
	   "The rates are less than they were 10 years ago. Everything else costs
more," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Pointing to the sign on the dump truck, he said: "Like the sign says, that's
the honest to God truth."
</P>
<P>
	   Cornell said he'll sacrifice $400 by not working today and for the cost of
the fuel and tolls for the trip. But he said he thinks it's worth it to make the
point.
</P>
<P>
	   Mike Nirdlinger, 35, also of Browns Mills, agreed.
</P>
<P>
	   "Hopefully it'll prove a point and something will happen. Otherwise we'll be
turning trucks back in to the dealerships," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Today's convoy to Washington follows protests earlier this month in which
truckers drove their rigs around the state capitols in Trenton and Providence,
R.I. New Jersey and Pennsylvania truckers also have staged demonstrations at
port facilities in Port Newark/Port Elizabeth, N.J., and Philadelphia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
