<HEADLINE> Riley To Propose Full-Year Teachers  </HEADLINE>
   By ANJETTA McQUEEN AP Education Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- In his yearly speech on the state of American schools,
Education Secretary Richard Riley will propose extending teachers' schedules and
pay to a full year in efforts to raise the bar on teacher quality.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We can no longer get teachers on the cheap anymore,'' he said in remarks
prepared for his seventh and final State of American Education address. ``I
believe school districts should begin moving to make teaching a year-round
profession over the course of the next five years and pay teachers accordingly
for these additional months.''
</P>
<P>
	   In the teacher proposal, being outlined today at Southern High School in
Durham, N.C., Riley suggests that the extra time can and should be used for
intensive teacher training and supply a workforce for students who need extra
help in summer schools.
</P>
<P>
	   Riley said he is not proposing sending children to school all year:
``Decisions about school schedules are best left up to each individual school
district.''
</P>
<P>
	   On average, teachers work under contract for 186 school days, said Kathleen
Lyons, spokeswoman for the 2.5 million member National Education Association
teachers' union.
</P>
<P>
	   The starting times range from mid-August and until June, and a teachers'
work year could be up to 10 months. And the average salary for a public school
teacher is was $40,582 for 1998-99. And the average teacher spends $400 in
out-of-pocket expenses for student supplies and works more than 50 hours a week,
though they were only paid for 36 hours, she said.
</P>
<P>
	   So the proposal is welcome: ``They are being compensated for much less than
what they are actually working. The year-round plan and increased pay would move
us toward treating teachers as professionals and compensating them as they
deserve,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
	   And as the nation's summer schools and after-school programs are growing to
accommodate the children who fail, many school districts already have their
teachers working 10 months or more.
</P>
<P>
	   But, Riley said, their pay is not catching up to the demands made on them.
Recent studies show that the annual income gap between experienced teachers with
masters' degrees and people in other fields with the same level of education is
at least $32,000.
</P>
<P>
	   ``In this time of economic prosperity, with state coffers expanding, there
can be no excuse for shortchanging our students and their teachers,'' Riley
said.
</P>
<P>
	   Riley, the longest-serving Education Department secretary, is also releasing
a five-year report card, highlighting progress claimed by the administration.
</P>
<P>
	   The report will show, Riley said in prepared remarks, that reading, math and
science scores are up, that girls are catching up to boys in taking math and
science courses, that high school students are taking tougher courses and
scoring better on college entrance exams such as the SAT and ACT, and that more
minority students are going on to college than ever before.
</P>
<P>
	   ``While positive things are happening, loud and negative voices tell us,
again and again, that public education is not up to the task of educating our
children,'' he said. ``Unlike some in politics, I do not get a kick out of
bashing teachers.''
</P>
<P>
	   He also critiqued calls to give public funds to children in low-performing
schools to attend private or parochial schools.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Vouchers are a mistake,'' he said. ``Vouchers drain funds from public
education and they divert us from the real challenge of lifting up all of our
children.''
</P>
<P>
	   However he cautioned states to be careful in the rush to increase academic
standards with high-stakes tests tied to a child's promotion to the next grade
or high school graduation.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Setting standards in January and testing in June is not realistic or
fair,'' he said. ``Promotion standards must be phased in sensibly, not rushed.
This is a step by step process.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
