<HEADLINE> Court Upholds Tax Refund Time Limit  </HEADLINE>
   By RICHARD CARELLI Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- People cannot gain more time to seek a federal income tax
refund by filing their tax return late, the Supreme Court said today.
</P>
<P>
	   The unanimous decision said the three-year time limit for seeking a refund
begins running when someone's withholding and estimated tax payments are made to
the government. The deadline does not depend on when a person's income tax
return is filed, the court said.
</P>
<P>
	   The ruling is a defeat for a District of Columbia man who sought a refund
when he filed his federal tax return four years late.
</P>
<P>
	   The federal tax code imposes a ceiling on the amount of a refund a taxpayer
can claim as the result of an overpayment. The code says the amount ``shall not
exceed the portion of the tax paid within the period immediately preceding the
filing of the claim, equal to three years plus the period of any extension of
time for filing the return.''
</P>
<P>
	   Justice Clarence Thomas wrote for the court today that the tax is ``paid''
on the date a taxpayer's return was due -- not when the return is actually
filed.
</P>
<P>
	   Today's ruling upheld a federal appeals court decision that said David H.
Baral waited too late to seek a tax refund.
</P>
<P>
	   Baral worked in 1988 in the mail room of The Washington Post, which
submitted to the Internal Revenue Service $4,104 in tax withholding for the
year. Baral became concerned that amount might be inadequate and sent the IRS an
additional $1,100 in January 1989.
</P>
<P>
	   In April 1989, he filed a form extending his deadline to file his 1988
income tax return from April 15 until Aug. 15, 1989.
</P>
<P>
	   However, Baral did not file his 1988 tax return until June 1993. His return
showed that he had overpaid his 1988 taxes by $1,175, and he asked the IRS to
credit the overpayment against his 1989 taxes.
</P>
<P>
	   The IRS refused, saying Baral had missed the refund deadline of three years
plus the four-month extension.
</P>
<P>
	   Baral sued, but a federal judge and the U.S. Court of Appeals for the
District of Columbia Circuit ruled against him. Today, the Supreme Court said
those courts were right.
</P>
<P>
	   The case is Baral vs. U.S., 98-1667.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-22-00 1120 </TRAILER>
