<HEADLINE> Stocks Continue Fall; Dow Off 81.28  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks moved sharply lower today, continuing last week's
big decline, although some software and telecommunications shares rose on
earnings and acquisition news.
</P>
<P>
	   The Dow Jones industrial average dropped for its fourth day in a row. By
late morning, the index was down 81.28 at 10,138.24.
</P>
<P>
	   The technology-focused Nasdaq composite index was off 79.97 at 4,331.77. The
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was down 9.06 at 1,337.03.
</P>
<P>
	   Stocks continued their slide after a one-day respite for the President's Day
holiday. On Friday, the Dow fell 295 points and the Nasdaq lost 137 after
Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan suggested more rate increases may be
needed to cool off the economy and keep inflation under control.
</P>
<P>
	   But some individual stocks moved solidly higher today after releasing upbeat
news.
</P>
<P>
	   SBC Communications, a regional telephone company, announced it would spend
$3.9 billion in cash to acquire Sterling Commerce Inc., a provider of Internet
integration software. SBC's shares dipped 3/8 to 36 1/16, while Sterling's
shares soared 11 15/16 to 43 1/2.
</P>
<P>
	   Nextel Communications, a wireless phone company, reported a
lower-than-expected loss in its most recent quarter, and said it would split its
stock 2-for-1. Nextel's shares jumped 7 15/16 to 126 5/8.
</P>
<P>
	   Shares of Oracle rose 1 19/32 to 60 5/32 on news the software maker formed
several partnerships with Internet-related companies.
</P>
<P>
	   Not all computer companies fared so well. Investors said they are starting
to worry about profits in the coming months. Intel, the chip maker, saw its
shares slip 2 11/16 to 102 11/16, and Cisco's shares fell 3 13/64 to 122 39/64.
</P>
<P>
	   The Russell 2000 index of small-company stocks was down 10.82 at 534.86.
</P>
<P>
	   Volume on the New York Stock Exchange was 321.14 million shares down from
the 330.98 million the same time Friday. The markets were closed Monday in
observance of Presidents Day.
</P>
<P>
	   Declining issues overtook advancing issues by a 5-to-8 margin on the NYSE.
</P>
</TEXT>
