<HEADLINE> Dow Down 14.27; Nasdaq Down 68.37  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were down today but recovering from an early sharp
drop as interest rate fears, the spark for last week's big decline, lingered
over trading desks.
</P>
<P>
	   The Dow Jones industrial average dropped for its fourth day in a row, and
was down 14.27 at midday to 10,205.25. In earlier trading the Dow was off nearly
115 points.
</P>
<P>
	   The technology-focused Nasdaq composite index was off 68.37 at 4,343.37,
having also regained some ground. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was down 4.33
at 1,341.76.
</P>
<P>
	   "The average investor is looking for the opportunity to step in here, but
with the pressure that's been created by the Federal Reserve, this could drag on
for a while," Bob Dickey, managing director of technical analysis at Dain
Rauscher Wessels.
</P>
<P>
	   Stocks continued to slide after a one-day respite for the Presidents Day
holiday. On Friday, the Dow fell 295 points and the Nasdaq lost 137 after
Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan suggested more rate increases may be
needed to cool off the economy and keep inflation under control.
</P>
<P>
	   But some individual stocks moved solidly higher today after releasing upbeat
news.
</P>
<P>
	   SBC Communications, a regional telephone company, announced it would spend
$3.9 billion in cash to acquire Sterling Commerce Inc., a provider of Internet
integration software. SBC's shares dipped 7/16 to 36, while Sterling's shares
soared 12 to 43 9/16.
</P>
<P>
	   In another telecom deal, Global Crossing Ltd., a long-distance phone
company, said it would pay $3.8 billion for IXNet, an Internet networking
company. Global Crossing's stock fell 3 1/2 to 48 7/8, while IXNet's shares rose
2 7/8 to 55 3/8.
</P>
<P>
	   Nextel Communications, a wireless phone company, reported a
lower-than-expected loss in its most recent quarter, and said it would split its
stock 2-for-1. Nextel's shares jumped 8 3/16 to 126 7/8.
</P>
<P>
	   Shares of Oracle rose 1 3/4 to 60 5/16 on news the software maker formed
several partnerships with Internet-related companies.
</P>
<P>
	   Not all computer companies fared so well. Investors said they are starting
to worry about profits in the coming months. Intel, the chip maker, saw its
shares slip 2 5/8 to 102 3/4, and Cisco's shares fell 2 3/16 to 123 5/8.
</P>
<P>
	   The Russell 2000 index of small-company stocks was down 10.38 at 534.30.
</P>
<P>
	   Volume on the New York Stock Exchange was 455.15 million shares down from
the 463.55 million the same time Friday. The markets were closed Monday in
observance of Presidents Day.
</P>
<P>
	   Declining issues outnumbered advancing issues by a 5-to-8 margin on the
NYSE.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
