<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jury hears closing arguments in Diallo trial  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Prosecutors failed to prove that the officers
involved in the death of Amadou Diallo acted unreasonably when they fired 41
shots at the unarmed man, defense attorneys argued today in urging a jury to
find their clients innocent.
<P>
	   Attorney Steven Brounstein said his client, Officer Kenneth Boss, believed
Diallo had a gun and was firing at fellow officers, Sean Carroll and Edward
McMellon. And he said prosecutors offered "not one scintilla of proof" to show
otherwise.
</P>
<P>
	   James Culleton, attorney for Officer Richard Murphy, said the prosecutors'
main argument was, "How do you fire 41 shots at someone who has no weapon? How
does that happen?"
</P>
<P>
	   But after hearing the officers' account of the seconds leading up to the
shooting, Culleton said, "You know now. You know about the chaos that was going
on."
</P>
<P>
	   The defense argued the officers believed Diallo had hit McMellon, who
actually fell backwards off a step and was not shot.
</P>
<P>
	   "They tell you he's guilty of murder. That he wasn't justified? Shame on
them," Culleton said. "Would any reasonable person have acted differently? How
could you fault him?"
</P>
<P>
	   Brounstein also referred to the prosecution's "mantra of 41 bullets" and
said, "Ken Boss did not fire 41 shots. He fired his gun five times. He perceived
a threat based on what he heard, what he observed. ... This is not a case of 41
shots."
</P>
<P>
	   Culleton said the officers followed police procedure when they stopped to
question Diallo because he was acting suspiciously.
</P>
<P>
	   "On Feb. 4, 1999, these four police officers, they didn't know who Mr.
Diallo was. They didn't know he lived in that building," said Culleton. "And
they had an obligation, following proper police procedure, to stop, to walk up
to Mr. Diallo and ask, 'Who are you?' and 'Why are you in this area?"'
</P>
<P>
	   "Why Mr. Diallo acted the way he did to this simple request to talk, we'll
never know," Culleton said.
</P>
<P>
	   Brounstein told jurors the fact that Diallo was home and did not have a gun
were "Monday morning quarterbacking arguments" offered by prosecutors desperate
to prove their case.
</P>
<P>
	   "Don't turn a mistake, a tragedy, into an injustice," Brounstein said. "I
implore you, I beg of you, to find Ken Boss not guilty of all charges. The
people have failed in their burden of proof."
</P>
<P>
	   Murphy, 27, and co-defendants Carroll, 37, McMellon, 27, and Boss, 28 - all
white - have pleaded innocent to second-degree murder in the killing of Diallo,
22, a black West African immigrant. Their trial was moved to Albany after a
judge ruled they could not get a fair trial in New York City because of the
publicity surrounding the case.
</P>
<P>
	   If convicted of murder, the officers face a maximum sentence of 25 years to
life in prison. However, State Supreme Court Justice Joseph Teresi opened the
door for a compromise verdict last week by ruling that jurors would be able to
convict on less serious charges such as second-degree manslaughter, which has a
minimum penalty of probation.
</P>
<P>
	   Prosecutors allege the defendants cornered the victim in the elevator-size
vestibule of his apartment building at 12:40 a.m. on Feb. 4, 1999, then, without
warning, unleashed a "wall of lead." The victim was hit 19 times.
</P>
<P>
	   The officers were in street clothes as they searched Diallo's neighborhood
for armed suspects. They contend they had good reason for stopping him and for
firing in self-defense with their rapid-fire semiautomatics.
</P>
<P>
	   In testimony last week, the officers told a similar story: Diallo ignored
repeated orders by Carroll and McMellon to stop for questioning after they got
out of their unmarked car, badges out. He darted into his dimly lighted
vestibule and pulled out a black object they were certain was a gun. He also
remained upright as they fired a continuous volley lasting less than 10 seconds.
</P>
<P>
	   Boss testified last week that when he first spotted Diallo, he thought, "My
God, I'm gonna die." Carroll wept on the stand while he recalled the shock of
realizing the black object "was just a wallet. ... I said, 'Where's the
(expletive) gun?"'
</P>
<P>
	   But several prosecution "ear witnesses," mainly neighbors of Diallo,
testified they never heard the officers' voices before sporadic gunfire erupted.
A coroner who autopsied the victim told jurors his wounds showed that he was
either falling or flat on his back when most of the bullets hit.
</P>
<P>
	   Carroll and McMellon were the first to shoot, squeezing off all 16 rounds
from their guns. Boss fired five times and Murphy four while backing up their
partners, leading to speculation they have the best chance at acquittal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
