<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 13:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Who Wants To Watch Loony TV?  </HEADLINE>
    By FRAZIER MOORE AP Television Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- Is it just me, or is TV extra loony of late?
</P>
<P>
	   Just consider the case of David Letterman. To everyone's delight, he was
back at his desk on "Late Show" Monday night after a month-long absence.
</P>
<P>
	   Except he was never gone.
</P>
<P>
	   Sure, in real life Dave went under the knife, then spent weeks convalescing
from heart surgery.
</P>
<P>
	   But being well (or even alive) is no precondition for being on TV. Despite
his emergency quintuple bypass Jan. 14, Letterman was never off the air. Some
nights, an old "Late Show" was rerun. Other nights, past guests came on to
reminisce about appearing with Dave, then clips of those appearances with Dave
were shown.
</P>
<P>
	   Even with Dave missing, Dave was never not there.
</P>
<P>
	   At least, until now. Although he's back for real, to ease his returnhe will
sometimes relinquish his duties to a substitute host (such as Bill Cosby, who
fills in Tuesday night).
</P>
<P>
	   Go figure: Now that Dave's back, more often than not he'll be gone.
</P>
<P>
	   An affair of another heart also has its screwy overtones. Airing last week,
"Who Wants to Marry a Multimillionaire?" convened 50 women who wanted to be wed
in the worst way. And then one was, to a guy none of them had even glimpsed
until real estate investor/romantic fool Rick Rockwell stepped from the shadows
and popped the question. Talk about a pig in a poke!
</P>
<P>
	   The two-hour Fox special boasted "television's most-watched marriage
ceremony since Charles and Diana." And like the marriage of those royal lovers,
the nuptials of Rockwell and nurse/comely blonde Darva Conger seem star-crossed.
Fox was forced to cancel a rebroadcast of the event after learning that Rockwell
had once been accused of beating a girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
	   "I am humbled and embarrassed by the fact that everyone went to all this
trouble for me," Rockwell said in a happier moment, just before dropping to one
knee. Which suggests that he was blinded by the light. "Who Wants to Marry a
Multimillionaire" isn't about Rick Rockwell. It's about TV.
</P>
<P>
	   And for the eligible bachelor initially identified only as "Mr.
Multimillionaire," as well as his eventual bride and the Spurned 49, TV was
justification and reward.
</P>
<P>
	   In short, this program bears out the First Law of Television: If you search
hard enough, you can find someone to do anything you can think of ... providing
you put them on TV while they do it.
</P>
<P>
	   The Second Law of Television: Whatever it is, other people will watch.
</P>
<P>
	   Granted, the inmates of North Carolina's Davidson County Jail weren't
watching. There, no TV is allowed. Just TV stars.
</P>
<P>
	   "We're here," Deborah Norville told viewers last week, "because we want to
give you an inside look at what it's really like inside jail."
</P>
<P>
	   For "Inside Edition," the syndicated newsmagazine she anchors, Norville had
entered Davidson County Jail as an honest-to-gosh inmate. For five days. And TV
journalism was a little wackier for it.
</P>
<P>
	   Now, we're not talking Christiane Amanpour reporting from Kosovo. But you'd
never have guessed from the buildup for Deborah Behind Bars. Check the
announcer's snarling intro to her first report, then remind yourself this isn't
a "Saturday Night Live" spoof:
</P>
<P>
	   "Doing time in Cell Block A! No special treatment. Just bars. And you will
see it all. The booking. The rules. The shackles. The prison stripes.
</P>
<P>
	   "And no makeup!"
</P>
<P>
	   Over and over we were reminded that it's "the toughest jail in America," a
title granted by Sheriff Gerald Hege, the man who runs it. A law-and-order P.T.
Barnum, he, like his celebrity guest, is a TV star of sorts: Since last summer,
Hege has been the host of Court TV's jailbird chat show, "Inside Cell Block F."
</P>
<P>
	   Now he was Norville's host at the pinkest jail in America. For some reason,
Hege has had everything painted pink. On TV it looked divine.
</P>
<P>
	   But pink wasn't foremost on Norville's mind as she accepted a misspelled
name tag (NORVILL, D) and exchanged her loafers for the prison-issue
flip-flops.	   "I think the lady who booked me was more nervous than I was,"
reported Norville, posed in the doorway of her pink cell. "I heard a quiver in
her voice and I wasn't sure that she wasn't a little uncertain about this
adventure that we're only hours into."
</P>
<P>
	   Even so, Norville had to maintain the goofball pretext for this stunt: that
she was penetrating prison life as just another inmate, subject to the same
tough policies that governed everybody else.
</P>
<P>
	   Meanwhile, "Inside Edition" viewers might have quibbled that no other inmate
was attended by TV cameras and a producer as she mopped a floor or did a guest
shot on CNN's "Larry King Live."
</P>
<P>
	   During five days in the slammer, Norville took pains to find some larger
truths of jail life. Mostly what she found was a hair in her producer's food,
and that her fellow inmates were "very respectful of one another's privacy."
</P>
<P>
	   Unlike (come to think of it) her.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   Elsewhere in television ...
</P>
<P>
	   'MONKEE' AROUND: VH1 is looking for the perfect Micky, Davy, Peter and Mike
to play the lead roles in the network's upcoming original movie "The Monkees."
(And no, they don't have to play their own instruments.) On Thursday, VH1 will
hold open auditions in both New York and Los Angeles to cast four young men to
portray the original Monkees as rock music's original Pre-Fab Four. Only the
first 1,000 applicants will be auditioned for the roles of Mike Nesmith, Peter
Tork, Micky Dolenz and Davy Jones, who themselves were cast under similar
circumstances for the 1966-68 television series. The film is slated to begin
production in mid-March in Toronto. Hey hey, good luck.
</P>
