<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 13:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Snow capital's winter celebration will bask in sun again  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) - Meteorologists are stumped. The National Weather
Service has no explanation. Not even triple Doppler radar can solve this
mystery.
<P>
	   Why does Syracuse's Winterfest celebration always appear to cause winter to
melt away?
</P>
<P>
	   Organizers even tried moving the date of the annual festival, which features
ice sculpting, human dogsled races, skating, chili cookoffs and other wintertime
merriment.
</P>
<P>
	   No luck. The thaw followed.
</P>
<P>
	   With temperatures expected to climb to near 50 degrees through the weekend,
the town reputed to be America's snowiest big city again faces a slushy
celebration.
</P>
<P>
	   "I think it will only help us with attendance," said Bill Cooper, chairman
of the Syracuse Winterfest Committee, trying to keep a positive outlook.
</P>
<P>
	   This will be the fifth consecutive year that the annual midwinter thaw has
coincided with the wintertime carnival. In fact, only three times in the past 12
years has the weather really been wintry with subfreezing temperatures.
</P>
<P>
	   Organizers shifted the dates of Winterfest from late January to mid-January
back to late January before finally deciding in 1996 to move it to late
February.
</P>
<P>
	   The opening day of the festival that year brought 52 degrees and rainy
skies.
</P>
<P>
	   In 1997, the first day of Winterfest saw 63 degrees and light rain.
</P>
<P>
	   In 1998, the temperatures stayed above freezing all week.
</P>
<P>
	   And who could forget 1999?
</P>
<P>
	   Winterfest fell in the middle of one of the warmest Februarys in Syracuse
history. The 5.7 inches of snow for the month made it the second-least snowy
February on record.
</P>
<P>
	   Organizers forced to think creatively, held the human dogsled race on wheels
in 1997 and 1998 due to the lack of snow. Last year, they trucked in artificial
snow made by machine at a nearby ski resort.
</P>
<P>
	   As of Tuesday, Syracuse had up to two feet of snow on the ground in some
places. However, forecasters says a retreating jet stream will let warm, moist
air push into upstate New York for the next several days. The outlook is for
sunny skies with temperatures near 50 for Saturday for the human dogsled race.
</P>
<P>
	   "We're hoping we have quality snow left at a city parking lot or the airport
so we can truck it away and dump it ... for the race," Cooper said. "Otherwise,
we're in trouble."
</P>
<P>
	   The lack of snow could jeopardize the snow volleyball game scheduled for
Sunday in the same location.
</P>
<P>
	   Syracuse typically averages 114 inches - nearly 10 feet - of snow a year.
But it hasn't even had an average snowfall in the past three years. Currently,
the city is at 76.6 inches.
</P>
<P>
	   Its reputation has been taking a knock recently. The ultimate insult was
this year when producer Albie Hecht decided to shoot his hit comedy "Snow Day"
in Alberta, Canada, even though the story takes place in Syracuse.
</P>
<P>
	   Not enough snow in Syracuse, Hecht said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
