<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Defense rips detective's handling of Louima inquiry  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - Abner Louima picked his torturer out of a police photo
array, but was unable to identify a second officer in the precinct house
bathroom when he was sodomized with a broken broom handle, a police investigator
testified Tuesday.
<P>
	   Lt. Reinaldo Daniels, who tape-recorded a hospital interview with Louima
while heading the department's internal investigation of the August 1997
incident, also admitted under defense questioning that he improperly corrected
errors in his written report.
</P>
<P>
	   The veteran detective conceded that he never showed Louima a picture of
Officer Thomas Wiese, who claims that he entered the bathroom as fellow officer
Justin Volpe stood over the Haitian immigrant, bloody stick in hand.
</P>
<P>
	   "Did he (Louima) tell you the second officer was just standing there, doing
nothing?" asked Ronald Fischetti, the attorney for defendant Charles Schwarz.
</P>
<P>
	   "Yes," replied Daniels.
</P>
<P>
	   Wiese, 37, Schwarz, 34, and Officer Thomas Bruder, 37, are on trial in
Brooklyn federal court for conspiring to obstruct justice by concealing
Schwarz's role as the second officer who held Louima down during the broomstick
attack.
</P>
<P>
	   Last May, Volpe pleaded guilty to violating Louima's civil rights and was
sentenced to 30 years. Last week, telling the full story for the first time
under oath, Volpe said that Wiese - not Schwarz - was present, but did not
intervene.
</P>
<P>
	   Schwarz, who already faces a possible life sentence for violating Louima's
civil rights, claims he was never in the bathroom.
</P>
<P>
	   Fischetti sharply questioned Daniels, a senior member of the police Internal
Affairs Bureau, on differences between his written report on the Louima
interview and the actual transcript. He suggested several times that the tape
might have been doctored, despite a tag identifying it as "original."
</P>
<P>
	   Fischetti focused on Daniels' report quoting Louima as saying the second
officer in the room was white, with a "light crew cut," and about 5 feet, 7
inches tall - a fairly accurate description of Wiese. But on the tape, the
5-foot-7 reference is to Louima's own height, not the second officer.
</P>
<P>
	   "That's my error, that's my mistake," the clearly uncomfortable Daniels
testified.
</P>
<P>
	   Fischetti got Daniels to admit he changed that part of his written report by
"whiting out" and typing over some words, a violation of police policy.
</P>
<P>
	   Fischetti showed jurors the four photo arrays, each containing six cop mug
shots, that were shown to Louima at the hospital.
</P>
<P>
	   The victim failed to pick out Schwarz from the third array, Daniels
testified, but when he was shown the fourth and last, which contained Volpe's
mug shot, "his eyes opened up like half dollars."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
