<HEADLINE> State awards $6 million in open space grants  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) - The state has socked away another 26 parcels of
open space, bringing Connecticut's total of preserved land to 6,089 acres.
<P>
	   About $6 million in grants were awarded Tuesday to towns, water companies
and land preservation organizations promising to save 1,886 acres in 23 towns.
</P>
<P>
	   "(The parcels) represent more than money in the bank," Lt. Gov. M. Jodi Rell
said. "They represent land in the bank. And that's a great investment."
</P>
<P>
	   The preserved areas include shorelines, wetlands, a dairy farm, woodlands,
greenways and municipal parks.
</P>
<P>
	   The smallest parcel of land being saved is a 2-acre patch in Vernon. The
largest area is 238 acres in Washington.
</P>
<P>
	   In Woodbridge, a 200-acre parcel will connect other open space holdings that
are part of the Woodbridge Greenway.
</P>
<P>
	   In Essex, 8 acres will preserve the largest remaining piece of natural land
along the lower Falls River.
</P>
<P>
	   "These purchases will ensure that residents across the state will have
access to natural resources while preserving the environment for future
generations," said Arthur Rocque, commissioner of the Department of
Environmental Protection.
</P>
<P>
	   The money awarded Tuesday is the third round of grants handed out since the
Legislature in 1998 approved Gov. John G. Rowland's open space spending program.
</P>
<P>
	   Last year, the first two rounds of grants totaled about $10 million and
preserved 4,200 acres of land.
</P>
<P>
	   The goal of the open space program is to preserve 673,210 acres - or 21
percent - of Connecticut's land by 2023. The state would own 10 percent of the
land; the remaining 11 percent would be owned by towns, private and nonprofit
land preservation organizations and water companies.
</P>
<P>
	   "This grant program is an opportunity for organizations at the local level
to call the state's attention to locally important pieces of land which are rich
in natural significance and should remain preserved," Rocque said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
