<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 14:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New York to formally knock standing eight count out of ring  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - The state Athletic Commission plans to follow the
lead of other boxing states by proposing the elimination of the standing eight
count in all New York professional bouts.
<P>
	   The commission is also gathering public comment on rules to implement fight
judge selection and pay reforms prompted by the Evander Holyfield-Lennox Lewis
draw controversy last year at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
	   The standing eight count was originally designed to protect the safety of
boxers by allowing the referee to step in and give a fighter who is being
pummeled an eight-second respite.
</P>
<P>
	   "The reason for initially putting it in is if a fighter was sustaining blows
to the head, and you weren't sure how serious it was, the eight count gave you a
chance to stop the fight," said Dr. Barry Jordan, a White Plains neurologist who
has served as ringside physician during many New York bouts.
</P>
<P>
	   But the consensus has grown among doctors that "it is probably best not to
have the standing eight count," Jordan said.
</P>
<P>
	   "If a boxer is sustaining enough punishment to have to count to eight to
assess his condition, then he's probably suffered enough punishment to stop the
fight," the doctor said.
</P>
<P>
	   Athletic Commission counsel Lawrence Mandelker said boxing officials believe
some referees were using the count to give beleaguered boxers a rest, which is
unfair to their opponents.
</P>
<P>
	   "If a fighter is ahead and he is on the verge of getting a knockout, they
are depriving him of a chance to finish the bout and score the knockout," said
Steve Acunto, a deputy state athletic commissioner in New York and head of the
American Association for the Improvement of Boxing.
</P>
<P>
	   Championship bouts in New York already are staged under the rules of the
national Association of Boxing Commissions, which in 1998 did away with the
standing eight count. The association represents boxing officials in the 48
states in which professional bouts are allowed.
</P>
<P>
	   The standing eight count in New York could be eliminated as early as April,
depending on the comments the commission receives, according to Mandelker.
</P>
<P>
	   "I would be surprised if we get negative comments," Mandelker said.
</P>
<P>
	   The regulations also contain the previously announced revision of rules
about the selection of judges to work title fights in New York. Those changes
were prompted by the uproar caused when the Holyfield-Lewis heavyweight title
match was declared a draw, though most ringside observers thought Lewis was a
clear winner.
</P>
<P>
	   The new rules will provide for judges at future championship matches in New
York to be selected by the state Athletic Commission and not boxing's
sanctioning organizations.
</P>
<P>
	   They also create a sliding scale for what referees and judges at such bouts
will be paid, based on the fight's purse.
</P>
<P>
	   For a fight with a combined purse of between $1 million and $2.5 million,
for instance, judges and the referee will get $3,333 each. For the biggest-money
bouts, with a combined purse of $10 million or more, judges and the referee will
earn $6,000 each.
</P>
<P>
	   The new regulations also provide for reimbursement for judges' and referees'
travel, lodging and meal expenses for title fights.
</P>
<P>
	   The state will also require the filing of affidavits declaring that no one
at a bout's sanctioning body received any payments from that fight's promoters.
</P>
<P>
	   The work of the judge selected by the International Boxing Federation at the
Lewis-Holyfield fight, Eugenia Williams, underwent particular scrutiny after she
scored the bout for Holyfield. She denied she was unduly influenced by IBF
officials, who recognized Holyfield as its champion.
</P>
<P>
	   IBF president Robert Lee Sr. has since been indicted in New Jersey for
selling his federation's rankings of some fighters and for demanding kickbacks
from promoters to sanction bouts.
</P>
<P>
	   Lewis won a rematch between the two fighters last November in Las Vegas -
this time with many ringside observers thinking Lewis got the benefit of some
sympathetic scoring from judges.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-22-00 1402 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000222.0131 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 14:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bradley questions Gore's consistency  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   GARDEN CITY, N.Y. (AP) - Pulling his criticisms of Al Gore together into
a single theme, Bill Bradley said Tuesday his own views on abortion, guns and
other issues were "clear, consistent, reliable." He asked: "What do we really
know about Al Gore?"
<P>
	   In a speech at Adelphi University, Bradley expanded on the refrain he
previewed in Monday night's Democratic presidential debate, drawing a rebuke
from the front-runner. "You're sounding a little desperate because you're trying
to build yourself up by tearing everybody else down," Gore said during the
debate at Harlem's Apollo Theatre.
</P>
<P>
	   On tighter gun control, guaranteed abortion rights and stricter campaign
finance laws, Bradley repeated over and again: "It's what I believe, it's what
I've always fought for, and it's what I'll do as president."
</P>
<P>
	   "My record on these fundamental Democratic issues is clear, consistent,
reliable," the former New Jersey senator said. He drew a contrast with the vice
president, saying as a Tennessee congressman Gore voted against abortion rights
and was "a reliable vote for the National Rifle Association ... a dependable
vote for the tobacco companies."
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley said Gore's "old politics of distortion and attacks and polls and
consultants" has contributed to a new high in public skepticism. "I have a right
to try to change that skepticism. ... I believe the American people deserve a
president who will tell them the truth," Bradley said.
</P>
<P>
	   The speech was meant to package his criticism of Gore in one neat argument
that Bradley hopes will sink in with voters during the furious two-week sprint
to the March 7 primaries. Eric Hauser, Bradley's spokesman, said the campaign
hasn't ruled out television ads showcasing the new theme.
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley began Tuesday with a stop at the Titan Food Greek grocery in
Astoria, N.Y., sampling the feta cheese and baklava. He assured Greek-Americans
that he's "on your side" in the dispute with Turkey over Cyprus. "This is a
problem we can solve. We know what the answer is, and it's the Turkish Army has
to get off Cyprus," Bradley said.
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley, who lost to Gore in Iowa and New Hampshire, has two weeks to stage
a comeback in the balloting in more than a dozen states. Beginning Wednesday,
Bradley will spend a whopping six days in Washington state working toward what
spokesman Eric Hauser called a "momentum-boosting" win in the state's nonbinding
primary Feb. 29.
</P>
<P>
	   Gore, who is backed by the Democratic Party establishment, accused Bradley
of attack tactics that "divide us as Democrats." He was taking Tuesday off at
home in Washington.
</P>
<P>
	   Gore said he was an advocate of affirmative steps to open opportunities for
blacks, and to improve education as well, calling them "the best reparation" for
slavery.
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley argued Gore was concealing a more right-leaning record. "Calling
attention to the fact that he was a conservative Democrat before he was Bill
Clinton's vice president is simply truth-telling," Bradley said.
</P>
<P>
	   "He was a conservative Democrat, did not support national health insurance,
(had) an 84 percent right-to-life voting record and was the poster boy for the
NRA."
</P>
<P>
	   Yet, for all the clatter about Gore's veracity, Bradley volunteered this
answer when an analyst for CNN, which broadcast the 90-minute debate, asked
whether Gore had "the trustworthiness, the intellectual honesty" to make a good
president: "The people will make this decision. My view also is that if Al were
the nominee, I would support him."
</P>
<P>
	   Neither rival was spared from jeers and boos by the raucous and largely
black audience.
</P>
<P>
	   Among those in the crowd were Whoopi Goldberg (Gore supporter), film
director Spike Lee (for Bradley) and O.J. Simpson defense attorney Johnnie
Cochran (alliance unclear).
</P>
<P>
	   "It was heartwarming to see two candidates fight over us rather than take us
for granted," said the Rev. Al Sharpton, who added that he will probably make an
endorsement next week.
</P>
<P>
	   The candidates used the forum, centered on urban and minority issues, to
appeal to non-white voters - who are expected to account for anywhere between 20
percent and 35 percent of New York's Democratic primary turnout.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
