<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 14:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> High court clears way for lawsuit over HIV infection  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) - A woman infected with the AIDS virus during a
blood transfusion can sue Danbury Hospital, the state Supreme Court ruled
Tuesday, reviving a lawsuit thrown out by a lower court.
<P>
	   Roberta Ann Sherwood had sued the hospital for negligence in 1996, 11 years
after she contracted HIV from contaminated blood she received while undergoing
back surgery.
</P>
<P>
	   A Superior Court judge had rejected the lawsuit, ruling that the claim
exceeded the three-year statute of limitations on filing suit in a medical
malpractice case.
</P>
<P>
	   The lower court also ruled against Sherwood's claim that the hospital
violated the Connecticut Unfair Trade Practices Act by making a business
decision to use unscreened blood.
</P>
<P>
	   The timing of Sherwood's discovery she was infected with HIV, and when she
learned the source of the infection, are the key issues in the high court's
ruling.
</P>
<P>
	   On April 19, 1985, Sherwood was admitted to the hospital for back surgery
and was given four units of blood which had not been screened for the presence
of HIV antibodies.
</P>
<P>
	   A few days after the surgery the hospital received a notice from the
American Red Cross recalling all such untested blood.
</P>
<P>
	   On September 1, 1994, after a routine blood test ordered by her doctors,
Sherwood learned for the first time she had contracted HIV.
</P>
<P>
	   An investigation followed. According to the court's decision, Sherwood
learned for the first time on March 14, 1995, that the source of the infection
was the 1985 blood transfusion.
</P>
<P>
	   The high court agreed that the hospital had not violated the state's unfair
trade practices statutes.
</P>
<P>
	   But Justice William J. Sullivan, writing for the majority, said a reasonable
jury could have found that basic standard of care required that Danbury Hospital
"to have taken steps to notify the plaintiff, after the transfusion, that the
blood she had received ... was not tested for HIV."
</P>
<P>
	   The decision sends the case back to Danbury Superior Court for trial on the
negligence issue.
</P>
<P>
	   Hospital officials could not be reached. A message was left at the
hospital's public relations office.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
