<HEADLINE> Dow Down 14.27; Nasdaq Off 72.60  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were down today but recovering from an early sharp
drop as interest rate fears, the spark for last week's big decline, lingered
over trading desks.
</P>
<P>
	   The Dow Jones industrial average dropped for its fourth day in a row, and
was down 14.27 in afternoon trading at 10,205.25. In earlier trading, the Dow
was off nearly 115 points.
</P>
<P>
	   The technology-focused Nasdaq composite index was off 72.60 at 4,339.14,
having also regained some ground. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was down 6.92
at 1,339.17.
</P>
<P>
	   William McDonough, president of the New York Federal Reserve, reinforced
expectations that the Federal Reserve will likely raise interest rates again.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's very clear that we will have to use the interest rate tool as long as
the demand side of the economy stays this robust," he said in New York.
</P>
<P>
	   His comments echoed testimony last week from Fed Chairman Alan Greenspan,
who suggested more rate increases may be needed to cool the economy and keep
inflation under control. On Friday, the Dow fell 295 points and the Nasdaq lost
137 points.
</P>
<P>
	   Markets were closed Monday for the Presidents Day holiday, and today
investors traded cautiously.
</P>
<P>
	   "The average investor is looking for the opportunity to step in here, but
with the pressure that's been created by the Federal Reserve, this could drag on
for a while," Bob Dickey, managing director of technical analysis at Dain
Rauscher Wessels.
</P>
<P>
	   But some individual stocks moved solidly higher today after releasing upbeat
news.
</P>
<P>
	   SBC Communications, a regional telephone company, announced it would spend
$3.9 billion in cash to acquire Sterling Commerce Inc., a provider of Internet
integration software. SBC's shares dipped 1/2 to 35 15/16, while Sterling's
shares soared 11 15/16 to 43 1/2.
</P>
<P>
	   In another telecom deal, Global Crossing Ltd., a long-distance phone
company, said it would pay $3.8 billion for IXNet, an Internet networking
company. Global Crossing's stock fell 4 5/16 to 48 1/16, while IXNet's shares
rose 2 5/16 to 54 13/16.
</P>
<P>
	   Nextel Communications, a wireless phone company, reported a
lower-than-expected loss in its most recent quarter, and said it would split its
stock 2-for-1. Nextel's shares jumped 7 3/4 to 126 7/16.
</P>
<P>
	   Investors, however, said they are starting to worry about profits in the
coming months. Intel, the chip maker, saw its shares slip 2 1/4 to 103 1/8, and
Cisco's shares fell 1 7/8 to 123 15/16.
</P>
<P>
	   The Russell 2000 index of small-company stocks was down 7.57 at 538.11.
</P>
<P>
	   Volume on the New York Stock Exchange was 644.47 million shares down from
the 750.46 million the same time Friday. The markets were closed Monday in
observance of Presidents Day.
</P>
<P>
	   Declining issues outnumbered advancing issues by a 5-to-8 margin on the
NYSE.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
