<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 14:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Defense: Diallo gave officers no choice but to shoot  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Amadou Diallo gave four police officers no choice
but to fire 41 bullets at him when he refused to stop for questioning and drew
what appeared to be a gun, defense attorneys argued Tuesday.
<P>
	   "That's not unreasonable behavior on their part," attorney John Patten said
in closing arguments at the officers' murder trial. "That's unreasonable on his
part."
</P>
<P>
	   The black object in the unarmed Bronx man's hand turned out to be a wallet.
But when he pulled it out, "that was it," Patten told jurors. "You can't expect
(the officers) to stand there and get blasted away."
</P>
<P>
	   Patten, his voice sometimes booming, argued that with bullets ricocheting
around the tiny vestibule where Diallo died, the defendants thought they were in
a firefight. The result was a mistake, not a crime, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   The officers "were wrong," he said. "They made a mistake. But they honestly
believed this guy was shooting at them."
</P>
<P>
	   Patten's arguments came after nine days of testimony in the trial of Sean
Carroll, 37, Edward McMellon, 27, Kenneth Boss, 28, and Richard Murphy, 27. The
defendants - all white - have pleaded innocent to second-degree murder in the
killing of Diallo, a black West African immigrant, on Feb. 4, 1999.
</P>
<P>
	   Prosecutors allege the plainclothes officers cornered the victim in the
vestibule of his apartment building, then, without warning, unleashed 41 bullets
- a "wall of lead." The victim was hit 19 times.
</P>
<P>
	   The case was moved to Albany after a judge ruled the defendants could not
get a fair trial in New York City because of the publicity surrounding the case.
The case could go to the jury as early as Wednesday after prosecution final
arguments.
</P>
<P>
	   If convicted of murder, the officers face a maximum sentence of 25 years to
life in prison. However, State Supreme Court Justice Joseph Teresi opened the
door for a compromise verdict last week by ruling that jurors would be able to
convict on less serious charges such as second-degree manslaughter, which would
mean the defendants could get only probation.
</P>
<P>
	   The defense argued Tuesday there was not enough proof to convict the
officers on any charge. They said a medical examiner's theory that most of the
bullets hit Diallo as he was going down or already on the ground was flawed and
biased.
</P>
<P>
	   Attorneys also attacked prosecutors for not calling the only eyewitness
other than the officers. Called by the defense, the witness, Schrrie Elliott,
testified that she heard one officer yell "Gun!" before the gunfire erupted, and
that the victim appeared to stay upright.
</P>
<P>
	   Murphy's attorney, James Culleton, argued that his client opened fire only
after Carroll and McMellon shot first. Murphy also saw McMellon fall off the
stoop, and assumed he had been shot, the lawyer said.
</P>
<P>
	   "They tell you he's guilty of murder. That he wasn't justified? Shame on
them," Culleton said.
</P>
<P>
	   Another defense attorney, Steven Brounstein, warned against the
prosecution's "mantra of 41 bullets."
</P>
<P>
	   "Ken Boss did not fire 41 shots," Brounstein said. "He fired his gun five
times. He perceived a threat based on what he heard, what he observed. ... This
is not a case of 41 shots."
</P>
<P>
	   Culleton also said the officers followed police procedure when they stopped
to question Diallo because he was lurking around a doorway in the middle of the
night.
</P>
<P>
	   "On Feb. 4, 1999, these four police officers, they didn't know who Mr.
Diallo was. They didn't know he lived in that building," said Culleton. "And
they had an obligation, following proper police procedure, to stop, to walk up
to Mr. Diallo and ask, 'Who are you?' and 'Why are you in this area?"'
</P>
<P>
	   "Why Mr. Diallo acted the way he did to this simple request to talk, we'll
never know," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
