<P>
   Tuesday, Feb. 22, 2000
</P>
<P>
	   German Computer Fair Goes Mobile
</P>
<P>
	   FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) -- Mobile communications will take center
stage when the world's biggest computer and technology convention
starts Thursday in Hanover. Nearly 8,000 companies will show off
the latest gadgets, coolest computers and hot-selling software.
``This year, going mobile is hot -- making things cheaper and
smaller -- especially being able to communicate with the Internet
from handheld devices,'' said Monika Brandt, spokeswoman for the
CeBit 2000 fair. Hundreds of companies will be showcasing mobile
technologies ranging from handheld computers to satellites. Part of
the new push is toward machines that communicate with each other,
such as parking meters or vending machines that radio in when they
are full of coins.
</P>
<P>
	   SEC Sues Two Day-Trading Firms
</P>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal regulators today sued two day-trading
firms and nine people for allegedly making loans to trader
customers that exceeded legal limits. One firm, Investment Street
Co., and two of its executives agreed in a settlement with the
Securities and Exchange Commission to pay fines; the other,
All-Tech Direct Inc., is disputing the charges. The SEC alleged, in
separate lawsuits filed in federal court, that Investment Street
and All-Tech violated federal margin lending rules. Investors buy
stocks on margin by borrowing part of the purchase price from their
brokerage firm or day-trading firm and putting up the securities as
collateral for the loan.
</P>
<P>
	   Gov't Makes Last Microsoft Argument
</P>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The government urged a judge today to rule
that Microsoft Corp. violated the nation's antitrust laws by
wielding its enormous influence in the technology industry to crush
competitors and potential rivals. Government lawyers repeatedly
cited findings late last year by U.S. District Judge Thomas
Penfield Jackson that Microsoft had abused its monopoly power and
hurt consumers, and they repeated a list of complaints they lodged
against the software giant during a lengthy trial. Today's final
round of arguments in the trial suggests that settlement talks are
going poorly.
</P>
<P>
	   TI Unveils Fast Chips for Portables
</P>
<P>
	   DALLAS (AP) -- Texas Instruments says it has developed faster,
more-efficient computer chips for wireless phones, digital cameras
and other portable devices. The company introduced yesterday two
updated lines of digital-signal processors, the chips that drive
many those devices. Dallas-based TI is the largest maker of
digital-signal processors. The new version of TI's leading DSP
communications chip will deliver 10 times the performance of
today's fastest chips, possibly speeding the development of mobile
devices that exploit newer wireless technologies, the company said.
</P>
<P>
	   Dow Down 44.36; Nasdaq Off 90.18
</P>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were down today but recovering from an
early drop as interest rate fears, the spark for last week's big
decline, lingered over trading desks. Just before 3 p.m. EST, the
Dow Jones industrial average was down 44.36 at 10,175.16. In
earlier trading, the Dow was off nearly 115 points. The
technology-focused Nasdaq composite index was off 90.18 at
4,321.56. Comments by William McDonough, president of the New York
Federal Reserve, reinforced expectations that the Federal Reserve
will likely raise interest rates again.
</P>
<P>
	   Telecom Acquisitions Planned
</P>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP -- Some individual stocks that released upbeat news
moved solidly higher today despite the overall decline on Wall
Street. SBC Communications, a regional telephone company, announced
it would spend $3.9 billion in cash to acquire Sterling Commerce
Inc., a provider of Internet integration software. SBC's shares
dipped  1/2 to 35 15/16, while Sterling's shares soared 11 15/16 to
43 1/2. In another telecom deal, Global Crossing Ltd., a long-distance
phone company, said it would pay $3.8 billion for IXNet, an
Internet networking company. Global Crossing's stock fell 4 5/16 to
48 1/16, while IXNet's shares rose 2 5/16 to 54 13/16.
</P>
