<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 15:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Advocates defend dredge-and-dump plan before congressional panel  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   TOMS RIVER, N.J. (AP) - Supporters of a plan to dump contaminated New
York Harbor sediment off the New Jersey coast traveled to unfriendly territory
Tuesday, defending the plan before a congressional subcommittee.
<P>
	   In the third of a series of hearings on the plan, representatives of the
U.S. Army Corps of Engineers, the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency and a
coalition of pro-dumping businesses testified before the House Subcommittee on
Fisheries Conservation, Wildlife and Oceans.
</P>
<P>
	   "This is not chemical or medical waste. This is dirt, " said Sam Crane,
coordinator of Nation's Port, a coalition of business and labor leaders.
</P>
<P>
	   The Corps of Engineers has granted permits that will allow mud to be dredged
from Brooklyn Marine Terminal and Castle Astoria Terminals and deposited in the
underwater dump. Some of the Brooklyn Marine dumping has occurred already;
Castle Astoria's has not begun yet.
</P>
<P>
	   The plan faces a chorus of opposition in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
	   Environmental advocates, political leaders, recreational fishermen and
others say it violates the letter and spirit of a 1996 agreement to close the
so-called Mud Dump, an underwater depository located about six miles off the
coast of Sandy Hook.
</P>
<P>
	   They say the dumping would turn back the clock on efforts to clean the
ocean, jeopardizing the state's tourism industry.
</P>
<P>
	   Only clean material, as defined by the government, can be dumped at the site
as a means to cover toxic materials already in the dump, now known officially as
the Historic Area Remediation Site.
</P>
<P>
	   The EPA, the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service and the U.S. Army Corps of
Engineers say the dredged sediment - which contains mercury, arsenic, zinc and
other heavy metals - is clean enough to serve as a cap on the material already
in the underwater dump, which closed Sept. 1, 1997.
</P>
<P>
	   The plan was the subject of a raucous Jan. 24 hearing at Fort Monmouth in
which members of the International Association of Longshoremen shouted down
opponents as they tried to speak and a Feb. 12 hearing in Long Branch that was
attended almost entirely by the opponents.
</P>
<P>
	   Venturing into the lion's den Tuesday, Crane and the two government
officials faced U.S. Reps. Frank LoBiondo, Chris Smith, James Saxton and Frank
Pallone - all of whom oppose the dumping - while a standing-room-only crowd of
about 300 looked on in the Dover Township Municipal Building hearing room.
</P>
<P>
	   The crowd broke into applause twice as Saxton grilled Deputy Regional
Administrator William Muszynski of the EPA and Corps of Engineers environmental
scientist Robert Engler about the government's criteria for determining the
sediment to be "clean."
</P>
<P>
	   "You would permit, under your regulations, significantly increased levels of
contaminants? That obviously flies in the face of what we're all here trying to
protect," said Saxton, R-Mount Holly.
</P>
<P>
	   Muszynski acknowledged that the EPA had failed to establish a new set of
remediation standards to evaluate the material proposed for dumping, as the
government was supposed to do under the 1996 agreement. He said the EPA is
re-evaluating the scientific basis at the heart of its existing standards, which
were developed sometime in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
	   Engler said the Corps of Engineers does not believe that the sediment will
cause "acute toxicity" in the dump area and said there is no evidence the
contamination would move up the food chain to humans.
</P>
<P>
	   Crane called the dredge-and-dump plan the least expensive, most practical
method of deepening New York harbor and completing the remediation needed at the
underwater dump.
</P>
<P>
	   Failure to dredge the harbor will result in cargo ships being diverted to
other ports, costing the New York area jobs, Crane said.
</P>
<P>
	   But Saxton said New Jersey has plenty to lose, too. The pollution is one
thing, he said. The perception can be even worse, as New Jersey shore towns
learned in the 1980s, when medical waste and hypodermic needles washed up on
beaches, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   "We're going to see (summer rental) leases canceled. We're going to see our
economy go down the tubes," Saxton said.
</P>
<P>
	   Later Tuesday, the Port Authority of New York and New Jersey called on the
Corps and the EPA to hold meetings to "clarify the facts" underlying the
controversy.
</P>
<P>
	   In a letter to the agencies, Port Authority Commerce Director Lillian
Borrone said the meetings should include elected officials and representatives
of federal and state agencies, business, labor and environmental groups.
</P>
<P>
	   "There is a lack of agreement on some basic facts: What are the current
federal standards for determining whether sediments are clean? Have they been
changed in the past three years? What is the status of an EPA review of those
standards? We need to foster a common understanding of these basic facts in
order to resolve the dispute," Borrone said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-22-00 1523 </TRAILER>
