<HEADLINE> Dow Up 39.09; Nasdaq Down 50.77  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- Prices were mixed on Wall Street today as investors, while
searching for bargain stocks, were dogged by worries about interest rates.
</P>
<P>
	   The Dow Jones industrial average, reversing a three-day losing streak, was
up 39.09 at 10,258.61 in afternoon trading.
</P>
<P>
	   The technology-focused Nasdaq composite index, however, was unable to shake
off concerns about interest rates and was down 50.77 at 4,360.97. The Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 index was up 2.63 at 1,348.72.
</P>
<P>
	   "The average investor is looking for the opportunity to step in here, but
with the pressure that's been created by the Federal Reserve, this could drag on
for a while," Bob Dickey, managing director of technical analysis at Dain
Rauscher Wessels.
</P>
<P>
	   In the morning, William McDonough, president of the New York Federal
Reserve, reinforced expectations that the Federal Reserve will likely raise
interest rates again.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's very clear that we will have to use the interest rate tool as long as
the demand side of the economy stays this robust," he said in New York.
</P>
<P>
	   His comments echoed testimony last week from Fed Chairman Alan Greenspan,
who suggested more rate increases may be needed to cool the economy and keep
inflation under control. On Friday, the Dow fell 295 points and the Nasdaq lost
137 points as investors were unnerved by the prospect of higher rates.
</P>
<P>
	   Markets were closed Monday for the Presidents Day holiday, and today
investors traded cautiously. Volume on the New York Stock Exchange was 756.77
million shares down from the 827.93 million the same time Friday.
</P>
<P>
	   Declining issues outnumbered advancing issues by a 5-to-8 margin on the
NYSE.
</P>
<P>
	   The computer industry was one of the weaker sectors today as investor
started to fret about proftis in the coming months. Intel, the chip maker, saw
its shares slip 1 5/16 to 104 1/16, and Cisco's shares fell 2 to 123 13/16.
</P>
<P>
	   The exception, however, was Texas Instruments, which unveiled two new
processors. The company's stock shot up 8 13/16 to 143 11/16.
</P>
<P>
	   In other news, SBC Communications, a regional telephone company, announced
it would spend $3.9 billion in cash to acquire Sterling Commerce Inc., a
provider of Internet integration software. SBC's shares dipped 5/8 to 35 13/16,
while Sterling's shares soared 11 15/16 to 43 1/2.
</P>
<P>
	   A second telecom deal: Global Crossing Ltd., a long-distance phone company,
said it would pay $3.8 billion for IXNet, an Internet networking company. Global
Crossing's stock fell 4 13/16 to 47 13/16, while IXNet's shares rose 2 1/8 to 54
5/8.
</P>
<P>
	   Nextel Communications, a wireless phone company, reported a
lower-than-expected loss in its most recent quarter, and said it would split its
stock 2-for-1. Nextel's shares jumped 9 7/16 to 128 1/8.
</P>
<P>
	   In other markets, the Russell 2000 index of small-company stocks was down
7.45 at 538.23.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
