<HEADLINE> Home Depot Posts Gain in 4Q Income  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    ATLANTA (AP) -- Continued strong buying by home fixer-uppers spurred a 38
percent rise in fourth-quarter earnings at The Home Depot.
</P>
<P>
	   Net income for the three months ending Dec. 31 were $578 million, or 25
cents per share, compared with $418 million or 18 cents per share for the same
period in 1998.
</P>
<P>
	   The results announced Tuesday surpassed by a penny the expectations of
analysts surveyed by First Call/Thompson Financial.
</P>
<P>
	   In late afternoon trading on the New York Stock Exchange, Home Depot shares
were down 12 1/2 cents at $53.62 1/2.
</P>
<P>
	   Home Depot said warm weather in November helped extend the building season
in many areas. Also, sales of flooring and kitchen and bath materials were
higher than average, company spokesman Jerry Shields said.
</P>
<P>
	   Sales for the quarter were $9.2 billion, up 26 percent from the $7.2 billion
Home Depot posted in the year-ago period.
</P>
<P>
	   For all of 1999, the company earned $2.3 billion, or $1 per share, up 44
percent from $1.6 billion or 71 cents per share in 1998. Sales for 1999 were
$38.4 billion, 27 percent higher than for 1998.
</P>
<P>
	   During the fourth quarter, The Home Depot opened 52 new stores and moved its
Greenville, S.C., store to a bigger location.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
