<DOCNO> APW20000222.0157 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 15:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Urges Burundi Peace  </HEADLINE>
   By CRAIG NELSON Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ARUSHA, Tanzania (AP) -- In his first-ever foray into video diplomacy,
President Clinton urged Burundi's leaders Tuesday to ``accept the risks of
peacemaking'' and reach a peace settlement before violence ruins their chances
for future prosperity.
</P>
<P>
	   In a speech beamed via satellite to negotiators in Tanzania, Clinton said
the United States supported efforts to resolve the civil war in the neighboring
African country of Burundi, where fighting between Hutu rebels and the
Tutsi-dominated army has killed more than 200,000 people and uprooted more than
1.2 million since 1993.
</P>
<P>
	   ``America cares about the peace process there and America wants all the
parties to succeed,'' Clinton said, his image glowing from four 33-inch
television screens arrayed across the floor of a conference hall in the northern
Tanzanian town of Arusha. Clinton's aides said it was the first time the White
House had engaged in video diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
	   Flanked by Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and national security
adviser Sandy Berger, Clinton spoke at the invitation of former South African
President Nelson Mandela, who took over last month as mediator of the
20-month-old talks. The talks stalled in August after the previous mediator,
former President Julius Nyerere of Tanzania, became too ill to continue. He died
of leukemia in October.
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton's appearance was part of Mandela's campaign to turn the glare of
international attention on the seemingly intractable problems of Burundi, a
country of 6.2 million people the size of Maryland.
</P>
<P>
	   On Monday, six African heads of state converged on Arusha to hear Mandela's
assessment of the progress of the talks, which are aimed at reconciling the
often deadly differences that have divided the Hutu majority and the minority
Tutsi, who dominate the country's government, military and economy.
</P>
<P>
	   Previous glimmers of progress have often ended tragically. The first
democratically elected president, a Hutu, was assassinated by Tutsi paratroopers
seven years ago, ushering in the current era of bloodshed.
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton promised that the United States would do ``all it can'' to help the
negotiations succeed.
</P>
<P>
	   ``All the great peacemakers find a way to let their hurts and grievances
go,'' Clinton told the representatives of 18 Burundian political, government and
civic groups.
</P>
<P>
	   Those grievances spilled across the conference hall earlier Tuesday, as one
by one, the negotiators recited the familiar litany of offenses they have
suffered at the hands of their enemies sitting nearby.
</P>
<P>
	   Mandela grew impatient and finally erupted in a bitter denunciation.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This is what leads the people, even the donors, to say we're wasting our
money. We are dealing with a leadership that does not really care for the people
of Burundi who are being slaughtered ... There is no appreciation of urgency.''
</P>
<P>
	   The European Union and the United States have donated more than $8.2 million
to stage the talks. A confidential report prepared for the French government
last year said negotiators, who are paid a $100 a day, had no incentive to
quickly reach a settlement.
</P>
<P>
	   By day's end, the champion of the anti-apartheid struggle, who spent 27
years in a South African jail cell, had cooled. He congratulated Gaetan
Nikobamye, leader of the miniscule Liberal Party, for announcing his eagerness
to consider draft peace proposals. He also reiterated his intention to meet with
representatives of the two main Hutu rebel groups, who so far have not
participated in the talks.
</P>
<P>
	   According to Mandela's aides, agreement remains to be reached on the thorny
issues of integrating Hutu rebels into the armed forces, election ground rules
and amnesty for human rights violators.
</P>
<P>
	   Among the leaders at the peace conference were presidents Pierre Buyoya of
Burundi, Yoweri Museveni of Uganda, Benjamin Mkapa of Tanzania, Joaquim Chissano
of Mozambique, Thabo Mbeki of South Africa and Pasteur Bizimungu of Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
	   For all the talk on Tuesday of knotty international problems, there was
still time for references to U.S. domestic politics.
</P>
<P>
	   Soon after the presidential seal of the United States appeared on the
television screen, followed by Clinton himself, Mandela asked Clinton to convey
his greetings to his family.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Tell Hillary we wish her all the luck,'' Mandela said, referring to the
first lady's campaign for a U.S. Senate seat from New York.
</P>
<P>
	   ``You'd be proud of her,'' Clinton remarked, even though she ``is not as
good as you are'' at getting out votes.
</P>
<P>
	   ``But almost,'' the president quickly added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
