<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 15:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Court: minimum wage OK for welfare recipients on workfare  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Welfare recipients in New York City are entitled to
only minimum-wage credit for their workfare job assignments instead of the
usually-higher prevailing wages regular workers get, the state's highest court
ruled Tuesday.
<P>
	   In a victory for the Giuliani administration, the Court of Appeals
unanimously said the state has traditionally not recognized that the prevailing
wage, civil service rules and other protections for workers extend to welfare
recipients working for public assistance benefits.
</P>
<P>
	   A group of New York City welfare beneficiaries has been contending for more
than two years that the Giuliani administration was unconstitutionally
shortchanging them by setting their pay scale according to the then-federal
minimum wage level of $4.75 an hour. The minimum wage has since gone up to $5.15
an hour.
</P>
<P>
	   Under the city's Work Experience Program (WEP) - usually referred to
informally as "workfare" - the welfare recipients were put to work by the city's
parks, sanitation and other departments. Some welfare recipients were doing
"skilled" tasks like painting, plastering and electrical work while others did
more mundane tasks like clerical work, according to court papers.
</P>
<P>
	   The welfare recipients contended that their fellow workers at those agencies
were often receiving twice as much or more for the same work. They said that
violated the state constitution's guarantees that employees under public works
contracts be given the "prevailing wage," which is same amount that other
workers in the region get for the same tasks.
</P>
<P>
	   The welfare workers didn't actually get paychecks for their work, but were
rather allowed to continue getting benefits if they put in the required number
of hours on the job each month.
</P>
<P>
	   But the seven Court of Appeals judges Tuesday said it would be illogical to
apply the prevailing wage to workfare situations.
</P>
<P>
	   Workfare participants "simply are not 'in the employ of' anyone" within the
meaning of the state constitution, Judge Joseph Bellacosa wrote for the court.
</P>
<P>
	   "That is the very reason they are receiving welfare benefits and are
required to participate in the (workfare) program, until they can find or be
placed in jobs with the customary array of traditional indicia of employment,"
Bellacosa wrote.
</P>
<P>
	   The judge also took a dim view of the workers seeking to reduce the hours in
which they would have to participate in workfare jobs if the court ruled in
their favor.
</P>
<P>
	   "The relief sought by this lawsuit - fewer working hours - is not what the
important prevailing wage protection is designed to address," he wrote. "That
provision is New York's proud enforcement of the value of work and the dignity
of earned wages."
</P>
<P>
	   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani said Tuesday that workfare assignments are for 16
hours or 20 hours a week and not "anything near full-time work."
</P>
<P>
	   "WEP workers are not employees," Giuliani said. "They are people who are on
welfare that we're hoping to get off welfare that are working doing transitional
assignments as they try to find permanent assignments."
</P>
<P>
	   There are about 38,000 people on workfare assignments in New York City,
according to court papers.
</P>
<P>
	   Richard Blum, Legal Aid Society lawyer for the workfare clients, said he was
disappointed by the ruling.
</P>
<P>
	   "What's most unfortunate about it is it means the city will continue to
operate a two-tier labor force in which an entire class of workers who are
providing very valuable services to the public will not have their labor
adequately valued or respected," Blum said.
</P>
<P>
	   But Blum noted that Bellacosa took pains to note that the judges Tuesday
were only considering the challenge to the constitutionality of not paying the
welfare workers prevailing wage. There could be other grounds under state law to
mount further court fights, Blum said.
</P>
<P>
	   The state AFL-CIO, which filed a friend-of-the-court brief supporting the
workfare workers' arguments, criticized Tuesday's decision.
</P>
<P>
	   "I just don't understand, someone goes to work every day, performs their
labor and serves their boss, how can they not be an employee?" union spokesman
Mario Cilento said.
</P>
<P>
	   Tuesday's ruling affirmed a decision by the mid-level Appellate Division of
state Supreme Court. A trial court judge had sided with the workers against city
and state welfare officials.
</P>
<P>
	   State officials had argued before the court that by affirming the welfare
recipients' arguments, the judges could be jeopardizing the state's receipt of
some $2.4 billion in federal welfare funds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-22-00 1550 </TRAILER>
