<HEADLINE> Grains, Soybeans Down on Weather  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    CHICAGO (AP) -- Wet weather forecasts for Midwestern growing regions sent
corn prices to a two-week low Tuesday on the Chicago Board of Trade. Other
grains and soybeans also retreated.
</P>
<P>
	   Corn sank on the outlook for precipitation every day this week in the
Midwest. But trading was quiet and the downside was limited in what remains a
bull market for corn.
</P>
<P>
	   Wheat, too, was pressured by soggy weather forecasts, dipping on
expectations that much of the U.S. winter wheat belt will get needed moisture
this week.
</P>
<P>
	   Soybeans fell late in the session after initially surging higher in
carryover momentum from Friday's rally. A report that the Brazilian government
will exceed market estimates when it releases its crop estimate on Thursday was
bearish on the market.
</P>
<P>
	   Wheat for March delivery fell 2 1/2 cents to $2.62 1/4 a bushel; March corn
fell 1 1/4 cent to $2.19 1/4 a bushel; May oats were unchanged at $1.15 1/4 a
bushel; March soybeans fell 1 1/2 cent to $5.13 a bushel.
</P>
<P>
	   Beef futures retreated on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, while pork
futures advanced.
</P>
<P>
	   April live cattle fell 1.03 cent to 69.87 cents a pound; March feeder cattle
fell .80 cent to 82.30 cents a pound; April lean hogs rose .43 cent to 57.65
cents a pound; March frozen pork bellies rose 1.95 cent to 90.40 cents a pound.
</P>
</TEXT>
