<HEADLINE> Most Europe Stocks End Lower  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    LONDON (AP) -- European telecom stocks made gains Tuesday but other sectors
lost ground.
</P>
<P>
	   The Dow Jones Stoxx Index of shares in European companies fell 2.72 points,
or 0.7 percent, to 371.76, while the Dow Jones Stoxx 50 Index fell 4.41 points
to 4694.35.
</P>
<P>
	   The Dow Jones Euro Stoxx Index, which tracks companies in countries that
joined the single currency, fell 0.61 points to 430.21. The Dow Jones Euro Stoxx
50 Index fell 9.28 points to 5024.05.
</P>
<P>
	   Vodafone AirTouch gained 10 percent and British Telecommunications added
almost 5 percent. France Telecom and Telecom Italia also advanced.
</P>
<P>
	   In domestic markets, London's FTSE-100 Share Index fell 1.1 percent to
6,014.7, Frankfurt's Xetra DAX Index rose 0.2 percent to 7,607.94, the Paris
CAC-40 Index was down 0.1 percent to 5,963.31, Milan's MIBtel Index was up 0.1
percent to 31,777 and Amsterdam's AEX Index down 0.3 percent to 647.28.
</P>
<P>
	   London's financial stocks were affected by concerns over interest rates.
Halifax fell 9.8 percent and Abbey National was down 9.0 percent. Bank of
Scotland was down 7.7 percent and Woolwich fell 7.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   Lufthansa ended up 6.1 percent, after Deutsche Post said it was discussing
future partnerships with the airline. Deutsche Bank rose 4.3 percent after
unveiling Internet plans.
</P>
<P>
	   In Madrid, shares in electricity companies Endesa and Iberdrola closed
strongly as investors continued their defensive move into these stocks.
Iberdrola closed up 1.7 percent and Endesa shares closed up 4 percent. Shares in
construction company ACS closed 1.7 percent higher.
</P>
</TEXT>
