<HEADLINE> SBC To Acquire Sterling Commerce  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    SAN ANTONIO (AP) -- SBC Communications Inc. is acquiring Sterling Commerce
Inc. for $3.9 billion in a bid to grab part of the fast-growing
business-to-business Internet commerce market.
</P>
<P>
	   SBC's $44.25 a share offer for Sterling, which makes software that lets
businesses buy and sell goods and services on the Internet, is a 40 percent
premium over Sterling's Friday closing stock price.
</P>
<P>
	   Shares of Sterling jumped nearly 38 percent Tuesday afternoon on the New
York Stock Exchange, up $11.93 3/4 to $43.50. SBC shares were down $2 to $36.25
</P>
<P>
	   Stephen McGaw, SB1C's managing director for corporate development, defended
the purchase price, saying Sterling had been undervalued by the market, but also
acknowledged a short-term effect on SBC stock.
</P>
<P>
	   "All on its own, this business is slightly dilutive to SBC," McGaw said, but
added the company is not changing its earnings outlook for 2000.
</P>
<P>
	   The acquisition follows other moves by San Antonio-based SBC to transform
itself from just a provider of local phone service to a player in Internet
access and other services.
</P>
<P>
	   Last year, SBC said it will invest $6 billion to become a leading provider
of high-speed Internet access.
</P>
<P>
	   Sterling Commerce, based in Dublin, Ohio, operates online "communities"
where businesses can buy and sell goods and services and sells software that
lets customers exchange information. It reported 1999 revenues of $561 million.
</P>
<P>
	   SBC will merge Sterling with an SBC subsidiary. The deal is expected to
close in the next few months. Sterling, which has 2,300 employees, will keep
operations in Columbus.
</P>
<P>
	   Sterling began as a unit of Sterling Software, a provider of management
software. It has more than 42,000 customers -- including SBC -- in banking,
health care, telecommunications and other industries.
</P>
<P>
	   SBC, which leapfrogged over Bell Atlantic to become the nation's No. 1 phone
company when it bought Ameritech, operates nearly 60 million U.S. phone lines.
It has also made investments in fiber optics -- it is seeking federal approval
to begin long-distance service -- and recently struck a partnership with Prodigy
Communications, an Internet service provider.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
