<HEADLINE> Fired employee return to store, kills boss  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) - An unreliable employee fired from an electrical
supply store for once again showing up late for work returned early the next
morning and stabbed his boss to death, authorities said Tuesday.
<P>
	   Kelvin Owes, 33, pleaded innocent at his arraignment Tuesday to charges of
second-degree murder. Prosecutors left open the option of charging him with
first-degree murder, which carries a possible death penalty.
</P>
<P>
	   A co-worker found the body of office manager Janet Welch, 53, at daybreak
Monday inside Maynard's Electrical Supply Inc. in a commercial strip near the
suburb of Irondequoit. The suspect was found hiding in the rafters.
</P>
<P>
	   Owes had been fired several times over the last year, most recently by Welch
on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
	   "He had been fired and hired back and then unfortunately would have further
problems and then would get fired again," said Monroe County District Attorney
Howard Relin.
</P>
<P>
	   "He had problems with coming in when he was supposed to come in - just
normal work-related problems that people have in terms of lateness and failing
to show up," Relin said, adding that "no other unusual things had happened like
problems with other employees."
</P>
<P>
	   Owes was jailed without bail. Prosecutors said they might escalate charges
against him at a preliminary hearing Friday.
</P>
<P>
	   An assailant battered Welch repeatedly around the head and body with a blunt
instrument and then stabbed her multiple times in the torso and the throat with
an unidentified "edged weapon," police said.
</P>
<P>
	   Owes previously served time for unlawful imprisonment and criminal trespass
and was placed on five years' probation, police said, declining to elaborate.
</P>
<P>
	   Welch, who was married, had worked at Maynard's for about 20 years and was
"a wonderful employee and a wonderful human being," said store owner Glenn
Hellman.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
