<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 16:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Unilever To Cut 25,000 Workers  </HEADLINE>
    By ANTHONY DEUTSCH Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ROTTERDAM, Netherlands (AP) -- Unilever, the consumer products company
behind such household names as Lipton, Vaseline and Pepsodent, plans to slash
25,000 jobs, or 10 percent of its work force, over five years as it tries to
reverse a slump in profits and its share price.
</P>
<P>
	   The company, which has headquarters in England and the Netherlands,
announced the cuts Tuesday as part of a reorganization that will also see the
closing of 100 major production sites in Europe and the Americas, leaving 150
factories.
</P>
<P>
	   Unilever, which is eliminating hundreds of lagging brands, also reported
that profits fell 5 percent in 1999.
</P>
<P>
	   Co-chairman Antony Burgmans, the head of Unilever's Dutch arm, told a news
conference the measures "are necessary for the long-term health of the company."
Left unclear was how many of the job cuts would come in the form of layoffs and
which countries would be hardest hit.
</P>
<P>
	   The company reported that its 1999 net profit slipped to 6.14 billion
guilders, or $2.97 billion, down from 6.49 billion guilders in 1998. Sales rose
2 percent to 90.9 billion guilders, or $43.7 billion, compared to 92.4 billion
guilders in 1998. Per share earnings in 1999 were 1 percent stronger at 5.83
guilders, or $2.81, compared to 5.66 guilders the year before.
</P>
<P>
	   Unilever, one of the world's largest manufacturers of beauty, home-care and
cooking products, said in a statement that businesses which fail to meet targets
will be sold or reorganized in coming years. Fragrance and cosmetics unit
Elizabeth Arden and the European bakery operations are under review.
</P>
<P>
	   Also included in Unilever's wide array of brands are Calvin Klein
fragrances, Dove soap, Close-Up toothpaste and Breyer's ice cream.
</P>
<P>
	   As investors have poured billions of dollars into technology stocks in
recent years, many retail shares such as Unilever have been left by the wayside.
The stock slid 30 percent in Amsterdam over the past 12 months and a drastic
restructuring was long awaited.
</P>
<P>
	   Analysts said Tuesday the restructuring wouldn't bring shareholders much
gain in the short term, with earnings remaining weak until 2004. But they were
positive about long-term prospects.
</P>
<P>
	   "They have now presented a more clear strategy," said Robert-Jan Vos with
SNS Securities. "It could enhance organic growth which has been lower than
Unilever's peers."
</P>
<P>
	   Andrew Saunders, an analyst with HSBC in London, will raise his earnings
forecasts after Unilever "did what was necessary" to keep up with its main
competitor, Procter and Gamble.
</P>
<P>
	   "The fact of the matter is that these measures will drive higher returns for
investors and higher profit," he said. "About 75 percent of the portfolio is now
low-growth and low-return."
</P>
<P>
	   Unilever shares jumped nearly 9 percent to 50 euros, or $50, in Amsterdam
after the announcement, but fell back to a 4 percent gain at 47.66 euros.
</P>
<P>
	   Late last year, Unilever disclosed plans to focus on just 400 of its current
1,800 brands. On Tuesday, it said it will invest $1.5 billion to market that
smaller product lineup over the next five years. Procter and Gamble has just 300
brands.
</P>
<P>
	   "The move towards a streamlined, more focused organization will dramatically
improve our ability to market our leading brands," Burgmans said.
</P>
<P>
	   The restructuring will cost an estimated $5 billion and eventually slice
$1.6 billion off annual costs, Unilever said.
</P>
<P>
	   Unilever also plans to increase sales over the Internet, investing $200
million this year for on-line activities, while it continues to look for
acquisition and alliance partners.
</P>
<P>
	   Burgmans forecast per share net earnings growth of between 8 percent and 10
percent this year, driven by stronger sales in emerging markets, Western Europe
and North America.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-22-00 1612 </TRAILER>
