<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 16:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SEC Sues Two Day-Trading Firms  </HEADLINE>
    By MARCY GORDON AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal regulators, taking their first major action
against companies in the day-trading industry, on Tuesday sued two firms and
nine people for allegedly making loans to trader customers that exceeded legal
limits.
</P>
<P>
	   One firm, Investment Street Co., and two of its executives agreed in a
settlement with the Securities and Exchange Commission to pay fines; the other,
All-Tech Direct Inc., is fighting the allegations.
</P>
<P>
	   The electronic day-trading industry has attracted several thousand
individual investors nationwide, who are distinct from the 10 million or so
Americans who occasionally trade stocks over the Internet. Day traders engage in
the risky practice of riding the stock market's ups and downs, trying to squeeze
out profits by rapidly buying and selling shares.
</P>
<P>
	   Host firms such as Investment Street and All-Tech provide trading
facilities, computers and specialized software for their customers, who usually
pay the firms a commission on each trade.
</P>
<P>
	   The SEC alleged, in separate lawsuits filed in federal court, that
Investment Street and All-Tech violated federal margin lending rules. Investors
buy stocks on margin by borrowing part of the purchase price from their
brokerage firm or day-trading firm and putting up the securities as collateral
for the loan.
</P>
<P>
	   Margin requirements, set by the Federal Reserve, generally limit borrowing
to 50 percent of a stock's purchase price. Brokerage and day-trading firms are
allowed to set limits stricter than 50 percent for their customers but they
cannot allow them to borrow more than half of the purchase price.
</P>
<P>
	   Investment Street, based in Miami, neither admitted to nor denied the
allegations in agreeing to the settlement. Investment Street and Dynamic Trading
of Miami Inc., which provided administrative services for Investment Street,
together agreed to pay a $25,000 fine and to refrain from future violations.
</P>
<P>
	   Javier Saenz, president of Investment Street, and Emilio Sardi, one of its
directors, each agreed to pay a $5,500 fine and to be temporarily suspended from
the brokerage industry. The lengths of their suspensions were not immediately
known.
</P>
<P>
	   The SEC said that Montvale, N.J.-based All-Tech, one of the biggest
day-trading firms, made margin loans by using the money of three people
associated with the firm.
</P>
<P>
	   The agency alleged that All-Tech and seven associated people were
responsible for making 103 unsecured loans to customers in 1998 to meet margin
calls totaling more than $3.6 million. In a margin call, an investor is asked to
come up with more money in order to meet the minimum requirement in his or her
trading account.
</P>
<P>
	   The SEC also alleged that four All-Tech executives -- President Mark Shefts;
Harry Lefkowitz, vice president of operations; Lisa Esposito, head of the firm's
margin department; and Barry Parrish, manager of its San Diego office -- aided
the violations by authorizing the margin loans to customers or otherwise helping
them get made.
</P>
<P>
	   "The SEC charges are groundless and baseless," All-Tech's associate general
counsel, Franklin Ogele, said by telephone. "We intend to defend ourselves
vigorously ... and we believe we will be exonerated."
</P>
<P>
	   Harvey Houtkin, All-Tech's founder and chief executive, has been an
outspoken defender of the day-trading industry.
</P>
<P>
	   The SEC and state securities regulators have been concerned about what they
say is an excessive reliance on margin loans by day traders who do not have the
money to meet margin requirements.
</P>
<P>
	   The practice of day-trading on margin came under a public spotlight last
July, when trader Mark Barton shot and killed nine people at two day-trading
firms in Atlanta, including a local office of All-Tech, before killing himself.
</P>
<P>
	   Barton, who had received large margin loans, is believed to have lost nearly
half a million dollars in his day trading -- including $153,000 in one three-day
"binge."
</P>
<P>
	   The SEC and the National Association of Securities Dealers, a self-policing
brokers' group, have scrutinized firms in the day-trading business to see if
they make unrealistic promises of quick riches to investors.
</P>
<P>
	   SEC Chairman Arthur Levitt told Congress in September that several
day-trading firms have used deceptive advertising to lure investors. He said the
agency's inquiry also found that many firms have lax compliance with securities
laws, including sloppy record keeping and inadequate supervision of employees.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-22-00 1616 </TRAILER>
