<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 16:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S., Europe, Asian Markets Falter  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- A late round of bargain-hunting today halted a slide in the
Dow industrials in the first U.S. trading following last week's big drop.
</P>
<P>
	   But the bounce back from today's lows came too late to lift European
markets. As Wall Street retreated on interest rate jitters this morning,
European exchanges gave up early gains and a bid to recover from Monday's losses
faltered. Stocks closed lower in Asia.
</P>
<P>
	   The Dow Jones industrial average, at one point down almost 115 points,
finished the day up 85.32 at 10,304.84 in active trading. The Nasdaq composite
index, off as much as 120 points during trading, regained some lost ground and
was down 29.77 at 4,381.97, according to preliminary figures.
</P>
<P>
	   Last week's selloff encouraged some investors to shop for bargains today,
but interest rate worries continued to hang over the market.
</P>
<P>
	   U.S. stocks plunged on Friday, carrying the Dow down 295 points and the
Nasdaq down 137 after Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan suggested more
rate increases may be needed to cool off the economy and keep inflation under
control. U.S. financial markets were closed Monday in observance of Presidents
Day.
</P>
<P>
	   Today, the National Association for Business Economics predicted the economy
would grow at a slower rate this year and next and said it now expects at least
two more interest rate increases by the Fed this year. And William McDonough,
president of the Federal Reserve Bank of New York, said the central bank would
continue to use higher interest rates as an inflation-fighting tool so long as
the demand side of the economy remains robust.
</P>
<P>
	   European markets, which had been recovering today after a big drop Monday,
gave up gains after Wall Street turned lower.
</P>
<P>
	   The DAX index in Frankfurt, Germany, closed with a 0.2 percent gain after
being up more than 1 percent earlier in the day, and London's FTSE-100 Share
Index fell 1.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   A second straight day of selling in Asia earlier today hit high-tech shares
particularly hard.
</P>
<P>
	   In Japan, the benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average closed down 0.78
percent. On Monday, the average tumbled 245.28 points, or 1.23 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   Markets in Hong Kong and Singapore also suffered today. The Hang Seng index
fell 0.4 percent and Singapore's benchmark Straits Times Index closed down 0.44
percent.
</P>
<P>
	   The losses pointed to one cause: last week's big drop on Wall Street.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
