<DOCNO> APW20000222.0180 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 16:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report Critical of Ex-CIA Director  </HEADLINE>
   By TOM RAUM Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Former CIA Director John Deutch knew that computers
connected to the Internet were vulnerable to attack, but took no steps to
protect some of the nation's most sensitive secrets, said an internal CIA report
released by a congressional panel Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
	   The report also accuses the current CIA director, George Tenet, and other
top ranking agency officials of waiting too long to act in referring the matter
to the Justice Department and to congressional oversight committee.
</P>
<P>
	   Tenet ``should have involved himself more forcefully to ensure a proper
resolution of the matter,'' concluded the report.
</P>
<P>
	   The release of the highly critical inspector general's report by the Senate
Intelligence Committee came as Deutch delivered a personal apology to the panel
in a closed door session.
</P>
<P>
	   Participants said that Deutch appeared contrite.
</P>
<P>
	   The panel voted to release an unclassified 77-page CIA-edited version of the
report which is at the center of the controversy surrounding Deutch, who was
stripped of his CIA security clearances last year as a result of the
investigation.
</P>
<P>
	   Deutch, a former deputy defense secretary, also voluntarily gave up Pentagon
security clearances earlier this month in the face of growing investigations.
Deutch served from May 10 1995 to Dec. 14, 1996 as CIA director.
</P>
<P>
	   The inspector general's report said that Deutch violated agency rules in
using as many as eight separate unsecured computers to process ``a large volume
of highly classified information,'' including information relating to covert
intelligence operations, top secret communications, classified details about
intelligence budgets and drafts of top-secret memos to President Clinton and
Vice President Gore.
</P>
<P>
	   These included desktop computers that Deutch had at his homes at Bethesda,
Md., and Belmont, Mass, his offices in the CIA headquarters and in the Old
Executive Office Building next to the White House, plus a laptop.
</P>
<P>
	   All five these computers had modems enabling them to connect to the
Internet, the report said.
</P>
<P>
	   The internal investigation ``has established that Deutch was aware of
prohibitions relating to the use of unclassified computers for processing
classified information,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Despite this knowledge, Deutch processed a large volume of highly
classified information on these unclassified computers, taking no steps to
restrict access to the information and thereby placing national security
information at risk.''
</P>
<P>
	   Much of the material in the inspector general's report had been reported
before, based on accounts by administration officials and lawmakers familiar
with the document. However, it was the first time that the report had been
released publicly.
</P>
<P>
	   The report disclosed that Deutch had been reprimanded for mishandling
classified information earlier, even before he became CIA director in 1995.
</P>
<P>
	   It also suggests that the CIA investigation into the matter was lax, with
Tenet suggesting ``no one ever raised the issue of reporting the incident to the
Department of Justice or whether Deutch's clearance should be affected.''
</P>
<P>
	   Tenet finally stripped Deutch of that clearance last August, 2 1/2 years
after the investigation began.
</P>
<P>
	   In a written statement Tuesday, CIA spokesman Bill Harlow said that Tenet
``has made it clear that he believes that Dr. Deutch's lax handling of
classified information was inexcusable.''
</P>
<P>
	   Tenet also agreed that the CIA's own investigation into the matter, at least
initially, ``was not well conducted and that Congress, which was first notified
of the ongoing investigation in June 1998, should have been advised of the
situation earlier.''
</P>
<P>
	   The statement said that the report ``paints a picture of individuals
struggling with the challenge of conducting a sensitive security investigation
of the agency's former director. CIA officials faced difficult decisions on how
to carry out a thorough investigation while preserving the personal privacy of
Mr. Detuch.''
</P>
<P>
	   Committee members said that Deutch, in his appearance before the panel,
apologized repeatedly for the mishandling of classified material. ``He was
fairly contrite. There's no doubt about that,'' said Sen. Frank Lautenberg,
D-N.J.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-22-00 1635 </TRAILER>
