<DOCNO> APW20000222.0181 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 16:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Wants Med Mistakes Reported  </HEADLINE>
   By ANNE GEARAN Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton wants to require fuller accounting of
deadly mistakes occurring daily in America's hospitals, but skeptical senators
said Tuesday his plan lacks details and the money to make it work.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This is a worthy endeavor,'' Clinton said as he predicted bipartisan
support for a national plan to cut medical mistakes. At the same time, he tried
to convince doctors and hospitals that reporting serious problems need not lead
to more malpractice lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton wants a nationwide system to report and analyze medical mistakes,
similar to the airlines' reporting program for aviation accidents and safety
risks. He is pressing states to begin reporting within three years, but he
cannot force them to without separate legislation from Congress.
</P>
<P>
	   The White House plan follows an independent report last year that missteps
by medical staff kill between 44,000 and 98,000 hospitalized Americans each year
-- equivalent to a jetliner crash every day.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Reporting is vital to holding health care systems accountable for
delivering quality care, and educating the public about the safety of their
health care system,'' Clinton said Tuesday. ``It is critical to uncovering
weaknesses, targeting widespread problems, analyzing what works and what doesn't
and sharing it with others.''
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton endorsed many of the recommendations in that report from the
Institute of Medicine, including establishing a goal of reducing medical
mistakes by half within five years.
</P>
<P>
	   He also asked Congress for $20 million to set up a national clearinghouse
for patient safety, as the institute recommended. The institute is part of the
National Academy of Sciences, a private organization chartered by Congress to
advise the government on scientific matters.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It is a balanced, commonsense approach based on prevention, not
punishment, based on problem-solving, not blame-placing,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
	   The American Medical Association and other large lobbies staunchly oppose
mandatory reporting, fearing that it opens hospitals and doctors to lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We live in an extraordinarily litigious environment,'' said Dr. Nancy
Dickey, past president of the AMA and a spokeswoman for the doctors' group.
</P>
<P>
	   The White House replies that while its plan offers consumers more
information about the safety records of individual hospitals, it would keep key
details about who did what to whom out of the hands of claims attorneys.
</P>
<P>
	   At a joint Senate subcommittee hearing Tuesday, several lawmakers offered
general endorsements for Clinton's approach but said they are confused as to how
the reporting system will work and who will pay for it.
</P>
<P>
	   For example, they noted that Clinton's proposed $20 million budget is for
research, not reporting. That leaves states on their own unless Congress steps
in with cash. In contrast, a bill already introduced by Sens. Arlen Specter,
R-Pa., and Tom Harkin, D-Iowa, would provide grants to states to help start
reporting systems.
</P>
<P>
	   Specter said he supports mandatory reporting, even though powerful medical
lobbies oppose it. Specter complained, however, that the Clinton plan urges all
50 states to have mandatory reporting systems within three years but specifies
no sanctions if they don't.
</P>
<P>
	   Specter added that Pennsylvania already has a mandatory reporting system but
few hospitals actually comply.
</P>
<P>
	   Already 18 states have varying requirements for reporting medical errors,
but they're scattershot in what they require and how reports are analyzed or
used. Consequently, the Institute of Medicine said few state programs are
effective.
</P>
<P>
	   Sen. Susan Collins, R-Maine, worried that small rural hospitals, some with
as few as 10-15 beds, already are struggling economically and cannot afford to
establish a reporting system.
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton also announced several new requirements that do not need
congressional approval, including an immediate mandatory reporting requirement
for the 500 Defense Department-administered hospitals that serve an estimated 8
million people. The Health Care Financing Administration will require error
reduction plans this year in all 6,000 hospitals that participate in Medicare.
</P>
<P>
	   The Food and Drug Administration has a year to develop new standards to help
prevent medical mistakes caused by sound-alike drug names or look-alike
products. The agency also will devise new standards for labels that highlight
common problems such as errors in dosage size.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Taken together, these actions represent the most significant effort our
nation has ever made to reduce medical errors,'' Clinton said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-22-00 1640 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000222.0182 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 16:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Stand on Taiwan Worries U.S.  </HEADLINE>
   By GEORGE GEDDA Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration expressed deep concern Tuesday
over a warning by China that it could use force if Taiwan delays indefinitely
reunification talks with Beijing.
</P>
