<HEADLINE> Dow Ends Up 85.32; Nasdaq Off 31.07  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- Prices were mixed in a volatile day on Wall Street today as
investors, while searching for bargain stocks, were dogged by worries about
interest rates.
</P>
<P>
	   The Dow Jones industrial average, which had been down as much as 115 points
early in the day, rallied in the afternoon to close up 85.32 at 10,304.84.
</P>
<P>
	   The technology-focused Nasdaq composite index, however, was unable to shake
off concerns about interest rates and fell 31.07 to 4,380.67.
</P>
<P>
	   "The average investor is looking for the opportunity to step in here, but
with the pressure that's been created by the Federal Reserve, this could drag on
for a while," said Bob Dickey, managing director of technical analysis at Dain
Rauscher Wessels.
</P>
<P>
	   In the morning, William McDonough, president of the New York Federal
Reserve, reinforced expectations that the Federal Reserve will likely raise
interest rates again.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's very clear that we will have to use the interest rate tool as long as
the demand side of the economy stays this robust," he said in New York.
</P>
<P>
	   His comments echoed testimony last week from Fed Chairman Alan Greenspan,
who suggested more rate increases may be needed to cool the economy and keep
inflation under control. On Friday, the Dow fell 295 points and the Nasdaq lost
137 points as investors were unnerved by the prospect of higher rates.
</P>
<P>
	   Markets were closed Monday for the Presidents Day holiday, and today
investors traded cautiously. And declining issues outnumbered advancing issues
by about a 4-to-3 margin on the NYSE.
</P>
<P>
	   "What you are really seeing today is what has been oversold, the Dow, is
coming back. And what was overbought, the Nasdaq, is having a correction," said
Rao Chalasani, chief investment strategist at First Union Securities in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
	   One sector that is giving back some of its recent gains is the computer
industry. Investors are beginning to worry that as the Fed put the brakes on the
economy, profits will slow. That sentiment hurt shares of Intel and Cisco.
</P>
<P>
	   The exception today, however, was Texas Instruments, which unveiled two new
processors. The company's stock shot up almost 12 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   In other news, SBC Communications, a regional telephone company, announced
it would spend $3.9 billion in cash to acquire Sterling Commerce Inc., a
provider of Internet integration software. SBC's shares dipped slightly, while
shares of Sterling soared.
</P>
<P>
	   A second telecom deal: Global Crossing Ltd., a long-distance phone company,
said it would pay $3.8 billion for IXNet, an Internet networking company. Global
Crossing's stock fell, while IXNet's shares rose.
</P>
<P>
	   Nextel Communications, a wireless phone company, reported a
lower-than-expected loss in its most recent quarter, and said it would split its
stock 2-for-1. Nextel's shares jumped more than 10 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
