<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 16:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hotel Cribs Found To Be Unsafe  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Eight of every 10 cribs inspected at a national sampling
of motels and hotels were unsafe, the chairwoman of the U.S. Consumer Product
Safety Commission said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
	   Spot checks in 90 hotels in 27 states and the District of Columbia found
loose hardware, unsecured mattress supports, dangerously soft bedding and
too-large adult-sized sheets, all of which can cause death by strangulation or
suffocation, the commission said.
</P>
<P>
	   Ann Brown, the safety commission head, said she had urged the nation's
hotels to join in what she called a ``pre-emptive strike'' to assure the safety
of their youngest guests.
</P>
<P>
	   And she expressed extreme disappointment that only one hotel group has
chosen to take part, Bass Hotels and Resorts. It operates Holiday Inn,
Inter-Continental and Crowne Plaza Hotels.
</P>
<P>
	   The industry trade group, the American Hotel &AMP; Motel Association, said in a
statement that it had had no opportunity to review the crib-safety campaign but
expressed no objections to it.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The safety of all guests, including children, is a top priority for
hoteliers,'' the association statement said. ``We applaud (the commission's)
efforts to spotlight the importance of crib safety, and we encourage the lodging
industry to review the recommendations.''
</P>
<P>
	   Brown said that while 40 infants die in crib-related accidents each year,
none of the incidents has been specifically linked to hotels or motels.
</P>
<P>
	   But she said the spot inspections performed by the National SAFE Kids
Campaign, which identified safety hazards in 82 percent of all inspected hotel
cribs, shows the potential for tragedy exists.
</P>
<P>
	   Heather Paul, executive director of the SAFE Kids Campaign, said the new
warning ``simply raises a red flag for the hotel industry that they might be
putting babies at risk.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``We want hotels to know there are simple steps they can take to help ensure
a safe sleeping environment for their youngest guests,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We should not have to wait for a front-page story of a baby dying in a
(hotel) crib for action to take place,'' she said. ``We shouldn't have to wait
for a body count.''
</P>
<P>
	   Brown said the inspection also discovered that more than half of all
portable play yards and playpens provided by hotel management also had at least
one safety hazard, including holes or tears in the meshing large enough to trap
and strangle babies.
</P>
<P>
	   The commission said it recommends that babies be placed on their backs for
sleep with no soft bedding, which it said can lead to suffocation.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Whether the hotel is on Fifth Avenue or Main Street, there's no guarantee
the cribs you request will be safe and in good repair,'' Brown said. ``Parents
who are traveling should not have to worry about the place they put their child
down to sleep.''
</P>
<P>
	   The safety commission cited estimates it said show that children under 2
years old spend 7 million nights a year at the estimated 65,000 hotels and
motels in the United States.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   The Consumer Product Safety Commission hotline, which has crib-safety and
recall information, is 1-800-638-2772.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
