<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 16:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> RETRANSMITTING to CORRECT cycle  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   LITCHFIELD, Conn. (AP) - Prosecutors in the trial of a police officer
charged with murder after the shooting of a suspect may try to show that the
officer's foot was on the suspect's back, a lawyer said.
<P>
	   Scott Smith, 28, is the first police officer in the state to be charged with
murder for an act in the line of duty. His trial is scheduled to begin Wednesday
morning in Litchfield Superior Court.
</P>
<P>
	   Smith was charged after shooting 27-year-old Franklyn Reid once in the back
on Dec. 28, 1998. Reid was wanted on several warrants and fled on foot when
police tried to arrest him.
</P>
<P>
	   Norman Pattis, a New Haven attorney who is not involved in the Smith trial
but has handled other cases involving alleged police misconduct, said he
believes prosecutors may try to show that Smith's footprint was discovered on
Reid's back.
</P>
<P>
	   "That would raise serious questions on whether he was resisting or making a
furtive movement that would justify the officer's use of deadly force," Pattis
told The News-Times of Danbury.
</P>
<P>
	   Prosecutor John Connelly and Smith's attorney, John Kelly, refused to
discuss the report, citing a gag order imposed by the judge.
</P>
<P>
	   Smith has said he believed Reid was reaching for a weapon. But during a
probable cause hearing last year, Connelly presented a witness who reported
seeing a police officer standing over the suspect, using his left hand to hold
the man's wrists behind his back.
</P>
<P>
	   The officer's left foot was on the black man's back and the officer held
what appeared to be a walkie-talkie over the man's head with his right hand, the
witness said
</P>
<P>
	   "That makes absolutely no sense," Kelly said at the time. "My client would
have shot himself in the left foot."
</P>
<P>
	   Reid was found carrying a knife with a 2-inch blade, but prosecutors say the
knife was out of reach in a jacket that had been discarded.
</P>
<P>
	   In December, Judge Charles Gill rejected a request by prosecutors to move
the trial out of Litchfield, but criticized police and Smith's supporters for
"rash, and ill-advised and ill-considered" actions, such as rallies at the
courthouse and the state Capitol.
</P>
<P>
	   The trial comes less than a week a Hartford police officer was cleared in a
shooting that claimed the life of a 14-year-old boy.
</P>
<P>
	   A special prosecutor declined to bring charges and ruled that Officer Robert
Allan had reason to believe his life was in danger when he shot Aquan Salmon in
the back. Allan had said he believed Salmon was reaching for a weapon.
</P>
<P>
	   Judge Gill has said he expects Smith's trial to continue until the middle of
March.
</P>
<P>
	   Smith is free on bond and has been placed on desk duty by the New Milford
police department.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
