<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 17:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Judge orders hearing on city's homeless shelter plans  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - A Manhattan judge ruled Tuesday that the city may not
force homeless adults to accept workfare jobs in exchange for city shelter.
<P>
	   State Supreme Court Justice Stanley Sklar said the law city officials cite
in support of the requirement may be constitutional, but it violates a consent
decree that requires the city to give shelter for every needy adult who seeks
it.
</P>
<P>
	   The law requiring the homeless to work stems from a 1995 regulation issued
by the state Department of Social Services at the city's request. It requires
anyone seeking shelter in New York City - even for one night - to comply with
welfare eligibility rules.
</P>
<P>
	   The city has been trying to put the rules into effect since the law was
enacted. The rules also require people seeking shelter to be evaluated for
substance abuse rehabilitation, educational programs, and workfare.
</P>
<P>
	   But back in 1981, the city signed a consent decree in which it agreed to
provide shelter to every needy, single adult man who asked for it, and in 1983
it signed a similar agreement for single adult women.
</P>
<P>
	   Sklar ruled that the consent decree holds. The DSS regulation, while legal,
"is declared null and void as it pertains to the population of single adult
homeless persons who are the subject of the consent decree."
</P>
<P>
	   Sklar's ruling applies only to single adults, but lawyers for the homeless
could invoke the equal protection doctrine and ask the courts to extend the
ruling to homeless families with children.
</P>
<P>
	   The city has said it wants to take legal action toward removing children
from adults who refuse workfare jobs because those adults would be denied
shelter, and therefore they would not be providing properly for the youngsters.
</P>
<P>
	   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, who has pushed to put the workfare rules into
effect, denounced Tuesday's decision, saying, "I expect the Court of Appeals to
reverse it pretty quickly."
</P>
<P>
	   Giuliani also took a swipe at Sklar, saying the ruling came as no surprise,
"given the predispositions of the judge."
</P>
<P>
	   "Justice Sklar is clinging to his desire for a city of dependents," the
mayor said.
</P>
<P>
	   "What he's missing is that since that consent decree there's been the
welfare reform law, a change of law and regulations in the state of New York,"
the mayor said.
</P>
<P>
	   Mary Brosnahan, executive director of the Coalition for the Homeless, called
the ruling a "legal slam-dunk" and said Sklar "recognized that the consent
decree's fundamental purpose was to save human life."
</P>
<P>
	   Brosnahan said Sklar found neither the law nor the facts of the case had
changed in ways that would force a modification of 1981 consent agreement.
</P>
<P>
	   "This ruling is a tremendous political blow to Mr. Giuliani," said
Brosnahan. "His position (on homeless issues) has been clearly calculated for
the conservative Upstate vote."
</P>
<P>
	   Steven Banks, a lawyer who works on behalf of the homeless, said Sklar's
ruling "is an important decision that prevents the city from going ahead with a
flawed plan.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's in nobody's interest to have socially and physically dysfunctional
individuals sleeping on the streets," Banks said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-22-00 1708 </TRAILER>
