<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 17:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Schwarz: I wasn't in precinct for Louima attack  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - The police officer convicted of restraining Abner Louima
while a second cop sodomized the bleeding suspect with a broom handle testified
Tuesday that he wasn't even inside the precinct house when the brutal attack
occurred.
<P>
	   Charles Schwarz, testifying for the first time about that infamous August
1997 night, said he was conducting a routine "field search" of his patrol car
when Officer Justin Volpe was apparently attacking the Haitian immigrant.
</P>
<P>
	   Clearly nervous, but speaking in a calm, clear voice, the 34-year-old
Schwarz said he had only accompanied Louima from the patrol car to the front
desk of the 70th Precinct. The attack by rogue cop Volpe occurred in a bathroom
inside the precinct.
</P>
<P>
	   Schwarz's lawyer, Ronald Fischetti, asked his client who had escorted Louima
from the desk to the rear of the precinct.
</P>
<P>
	   "I think it was Tommy Wiese," Schwarz replied. "I'm not 100 percent sure,
but I think it was him."
</P>
<P>
	   Schwarz, Wiese, and Officer Thomas Bruder are on trial in Brooklyn federal
court for conspiring to obstruct justice by concealing Schwarz's role as the
second officer who held Louima down during the broomstick attack.
</P>
<P>
	   But Schwarz insisted that he was outside the precinct, inspecting his patrol
car for weapons or contraband that Louima might have dumped after his arrest.
Such inspections were standard after an arrest, Schwarz testified.
</P>
<P>
	   Schwarz was convicted at an earlier trial of violating Louima's civil rights
by assisting in the attack, but he didn't testify in that case. He could face a
life sentence on the conviction.
</P>
<P>
	   Last May, Volpe pleaded guilty to violating Louima's civil rights and was
sentenced to 30 years. Last week, telling the full story for the first time
under oath, Volpe said that Wiese - not Schwarz - was present, but did not
intervene.
</P>
<P>
	   Schwarz testified that he was unaware of what happened following Louima's
arrest outside a Brooklyn nightclub until two days later, when detectives from
Internal Affairs began grabbing broomsticks and mop handles from the precinct.
</P>
<P>
	   "I assumed they thought he had been beaten with broomsticks or a mop
handle," said Schwarz.
</P>
<P>
	   Louima suffered severe internal injuries, including a ruptured bladder and
colon, and spent two months in the hospital after the Aug. 9, 1997 attack.
</P>
<P>
	   Earlier, a police investigator testified that Louima picked his torturer out
of a police photo array, but was unable to identify the second officer in the
bathroom when he was sodomized.
</P>
<P>
	   Lt. Reinaldo Daniels, who tape-recorded a hospital interview with Louima
while heading the department's internal investigation of the attack, also
admitted under defense questioning that he improperly corrected errors in his
written report.
</P>
<P>
	   The veteran detective conceded that he never showed Louima a picture of
Wiese, 34, who claims that he entered the bathroom as Volpe stood over the
Haitian immigrant, bloody stick in hand.
</P>
<P>
	   "Did he (Louima) tell you the second officer was just standing there, doing
nothing?" Fischetti asked.
</P>
<P>
	   "Yes," replied Daniels.
</P>
<P>
	   Fischetti showed jurors four sets of photos, each containing six mug shots
of cops. They were the same pictures shown to Louima at the hospital.
</P>
<P>
	   The victim failed to pick out Schwarz, Daniels testified, but when he saw
Volpe's mug shot, "his eyes opened up like half dollars."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
