	   HANOVER, Germany (AP) -- Internet service provider AOL Europe
upped the ante today in its ongoing battle against rival Deutsche
Telekom to win the hearts of Germany's younger generation. At the
annual CeBit technology and computer fair in Hanover, AOL Europe
offered bargain-basement access fees to lure thousands of German
schools and millions of students into cyberspace. The two companies
have battled back and forth to win devoted customers in Germany's
up-and-coming Internet age which is poised for big growth. AOL
Europe's move will cost the company about $75 million.
</P>
<P>
	   SEC Sues Day-Trading Firms
</P>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal regulators, taking their first major
action against companies in the day-trading industry, today sued
two firms and nine people for allegedly making loans to trader
customers that exceeded legal limits. One firm, Investment Street
Co., and two of its executives agreed in a settlement with the
Securities and Exchange Commission to pay fines; the other,
All-Tech Direct Inc., is fighting the allegations. The electronic
day-trading industry has attracted several thousand individual
investors nationwide, who are distinct from the 10 million or so
Americans who occasionally trade stocks over the Internet.
</P>
