<HEADLINE> World Premieres, Tribute To Copland  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    WASHINGTON (AP) -- A world premiere of a work by a Puerto Rican composer and
a centenary tribute to Aaron Copland will mark the 70th season of the National
Symphony Orchestra, beginning Sept. 7.
</P>
<P>
	   Roberto Sierra's "Fandangos," tracing the history of that dance music, will
be played next year on Feb. 28, March 2 and March 3, under the baton of music
director Leonard Slatkin. The Philadelphia Orchestra also commissioned a work by
Sierra in 1998, to mark its 100th anniversary.
</P>
<P>
	   Copland, who died in 1990, would have been 100 this year. In 1979 he led the
first of the orchestra's concerts on the lawn of the Capitol, now a regular,
nationally-televised program. The following year a televised performance honored
his 80th birthday. Slatkin will direct six Copland works Sept. 21, 22 and 23.
</P>
<P>
	   Another world premiere in the coming season will be the "Percussion
Concerto" of Steve Martland, a rock composer, part of a British Festival by the
orchestra between May 3 and 19, 2001.
</P>
<P>
	   The annual Beethoven Festival, 10 performances in September, will
concentrate on his work as retouched by Gustav Mahler, himself a distinguished
composer in the Viennese tradition. Mahler died in 1911.
</P>
<P>
	   "For those who know this music well, you'll have fun spotting the
differences," Slatkin said in announcing the season. "And for those who are just
coming to hear Beethoven, it's still Beethoven."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
