<HEADLINE> Hillary Clinton: Debates sound like fun  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   TONAWANDA, N.Y. (AP) - Hillary Rodham Clinton would love to debate in
the Apollo Theater like presidential rivals Bill Bradley and Al Gore did, she
said Tuesday. Even better would be to have debates all over New York.
<P>
	   "It would be kind of fun, travel around the state, engage in debates ...
wouldn't that be fun?" the Senate candidate said during a campaign stop at a
Salvation Army, where a few dozen senior citizens were having lunch. "Stand up
in all sorts of settings all over the state like it used to be done. I'd love
that."
</P>
<P>
	   Although the election is still several months away, Clinton said she was
willing to debate her Republican rival, New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani,
"whenever we could."
</P>
<P>
	   "I don't have any starting time or ending time," she said.
</P>
<P>
	   Giuliani's campaign did not immediately return telephone calls seeking
comment.
</P>
<P>
	   "The more information you give to people and the more you answer questions
and the more you can make the campaign about issues, the better it will be for
everybody," said Clinton, who complained of having to defend herself against "a
charge a day" from the Giuliani camp.
</P>
<P>
	   Also Tuesday, Clinton renewed her call for New York and the other
Northeastern states to have their own home heating oil reserves that could be
tapped in case future shortages make prices skyrocket again.
</P>
<P>
	   The proposal was part of a five-point plan that she said would help
homeowners in the short term and the nation in the long term by decreasing its
dependence on heating oil.
</P>
<P>
	   With OPEC countries limiting production, the cost of home heating oil in New
York has risen from a statewide average of 90.6 cents a gallon in February of
last year to $2.01 a gallon this month.
</P>
<P>
	   Northeastern states have been hardest hit by the price increase. Gertrude
Mohr, a Tonawanda homeowner on hand to hear Clinton's plans, said she paid $220
for her last oil delivery, compared to under $100 per delivery last year.
</P>
<P>
	   "You've got to cut back on other things. No dinners out or anything," the
senior citizen said.
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton's plan also includes support for increased funding for the
Low-Income Home Energy Assistance Program and for a system of swaps which would
allow the federal government to loan oil from the Strategic Petroleum Oil
Reserve to companies that promise to return a larger volume of oil later.
</P>
<P>
	   The country also must develop alternative energy sources to reduce its
reliance on oil, said Clinton, who said she would support investments in cleaner
technologies such as wind, bioenergy, fuel cells and geothermal energy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
