<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Pinochet Assessment Called For  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Responding to a report that found Gen. Augusto Pinochet unfit
to stand trial, Switzerland said Tuesday that ill health should not stop the
former Chilean dictator's extradition. France and Belgium asked for another
medical assessment.
</P>
<P>
	   Home Secretary Jack Straw must consider these and other arguments before
deciding whether to extradite Pinochet to Spain for trial or allow him to go
home. A final decision is not expected before Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   Spain, Switzerland, France and Belgium -- which have all requested
Pinochet's extradition -- had until Tuesday evening to respond to an independent
British medical team's conclusion that the 84-year-old Pinochet is too ill to
stand trial.
</P>
<P>
	   The responses were the latest round in more than a year of complex legal
proceedings to determine whether Pinochet will stand trial for alleged human
rights abuses.
</P>
<P>
	   Pinochet was arrested in London in October 1998 on a warrant from Spanish
Judge Baltasar Garzon while recuperating from back surgery there. He remains
under police guard in a rented mansion west of London. He has diabetes, and
suffered two small strokes last fall.
</P>
<P>
	   For weeks, Straw did not let the countries requesting Pinochet's extradition
see the medical report that found him unfit. He said that would violate
Pinochet's confidentiality. But last week, Britain's High Court ordered Straw to
make the report available to the four countries.
</P>
<P>
	   The report was supposed to be seen only by those countries' officials. But
Spanish newspapers, which received leaked copies of the report, said it showed
Pinochet had suffered brain damage that would prevent his participation in a
trial.
</P>
<P>
	   French investigating magistrate Roger Le Loire has formally asked British
authorities for another assessment of Pinochet's health, Foreign Ministry
spokeswoman Anne Gazeau-Secret said.
</P>
<P>
	   The Swiss argued that international treaties do not allow Britain to refuse
the extradition for health reasons.
</P>
<P>
	   Michel Malherbe, a spokesman for the Belgian Foreign Ministry, said Brussels
magistrate Damien Vandermeersche had found that ``technically the British report
is very good,'' but questioned the interpretation of the result.
</P>
<P>
	   ``For our judge here the deterioration is actually light, which does make
him fit for trial,'' Malherbe said. He said the judge had requested more tests.
</P>
<P>
	   An official Chilean government report says 3,197 people died or disappeared
during the general's 17-year regime, which began when he ousted elected Marxist
President Salvador Allende in a 1973 coup.
</P>
<P>
	   The Spanish government does not support the extradition bid by Garzon, the
judge who issued the Pinochet arrest warrant. It said it will not oppose any
decision by Straw to send Pinochet home.
</P>
<P>
	   But a team of Spanish doctors appointed by Garzon disputes the medical
findings and asserts Pinochet is ``competent to be put on trial,'' the Spanish
news agency Efe reported. Garzon sent the doctors' comments and his own to
London on Tuesday and said the general should now undergo a second medical exam.
</P>
<P>
	   Straw's final ruling was not expected until at least Monday, since he vowed
to report it first to lawmakers in the House of Commons, which does not have a
session until then. But Straw announced last month that the doctors' findings
left him inclined to drop extradition.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-22-00 1758 </TRAILER>
