<DOCNO> APW20000222.0221 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 18:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Euro Is Back To Parity With Dollar  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- Europe's embattled currency clawed back more territory
against the dollar Tuesday, regaining the $1 level for the first time in nearly
a month.
</P>
<P>
	   The euro was quoted at $1.0036 in late trading in New York, up from 98.49
cents late Friday and the first time it has traded above $1 since Jan. 27. U.S.
financial markets were closed Monday for a national holiday.
</P>
<P>
	   The euro had been in a slump over the past few weeks on concerns about
Europe's economic outlook, solid economic fundamentals in the United States and
a perception among traders that European financial authorities were reluctant to
influence the euro's level in the open market.
</P>
<P>
	   But several recent signs of strength in Europe's biggest economies have been
lending support to euro, which was launched at the beginning of last year. In
the latest such sign, German labor officials said Tuesday they expected the
jobless rate to drop below 10 percent in April.
</P>
<P>
	   Despite the rebound against the dollar, some traders said the euro may fall
again below the one-for-one level, or parity, against the U.S. dollar, since
many investors continue to have a negative outlook for the young currency.
</P>
<P>
	   "I think we haven't seen the last of the euro being under parity," said
Joseph Barnea, a currency trader at Bank Leumi in New York.
</P>
<P>
	   In other trading, the dollar initially rose against the Japanese yen but
gave up its gains as the trading day wore on. By late afternoon in New York, the
dollar was worth 110.70 yen, down from 110.96 yen on Friday.
</P>
<P>
	   The dollar was also quoted at 1.6021 Swiss francs, down from 1.6284, and
1.4626 Canadian dollars, up from 1.4512. The British pound rose to $1.6119 from
$1.6000.
</P>
<P>
	   Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no longer
traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate.
</P>
<P>
	   Based on Tuesday's euro rate, the dollar was worth: 1.9490 German marks,
down from 1.9858; 6.5367 French francs, down from 6.6601; and 1,929.52 Italian
lire, down from 1,965.96.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
