<HEADLINE> Dow Ends Up 85.32; Nasdaq Off 29.62  </HEADLINE>
    By NOELLE KNOX AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- Blue-chip stocks broke a three-day losing streak in a
volatile day on Wall Street Tuesday as investors looked for bargains and shunned
usually hot technology stocks.
</P>
<P>
	   The Dow Jones industrial average, which had been down as much as 115 points
early in the day, rallied in the afternoon to close up 85.32 at 10,304.84.
</P>
<P>
	   The technology-focused Nasdaq composite index, however, was unable to shake
off concerns about interest rates and fell 29.62 to 4,382.12. The Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 index rose 6.08 to 1,352.17.
</P>
<P>
	   Tuesday's performance was a marked change from the recent trend on Wall
Street that has pushed the Nasdaq up more than 8 percent this year and sent the
Dow down 11 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   "What you are really seeing today is what has been oversold, the Dow, is
coming back. And what was overbought, the Nasdaq, is having a correction," said
Rao Chalasani, chief investment strategist at First Union Securities in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
	   Some recent favorites on Wall Street were hit hard Tuesday. Cisco fell 1 7/8
to 123 15/16, and Qualcomm dipped 3 15/16 to 130 9/16.
</P>
<P>
	   Investors instead favored companies including General Electric, whose shares
rose 4 1/8 to 129 1/4, and Bank of America, up 1 3/16 to 44 15/16.
</P>
<P>
	   "The average investor is looking for the opportunity to step in here, but
with the pressure that's been created by the Federal Reserve, this could drag on
for a while," Bob Dickey, managing director of technical analysis at Dain
Rauscher Wessels.
</P>
<P>
	   Tuesday morning, William McDonough, president of the New York Federal
Reserve, reinforced expectations that the Federal Reserve will likely raise
interest rates again.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's very clear that we will have to use the interest rate tool as long as
the demand side of the economy stays this robust," he said in New York.
</P>
<P>
	   His comments echoed testimony last week from Fed Chairman Alan Greenspan,
who suggested more rate increases may be needed to cool the economy and keep
inflation under control. On Friday, the Dow fell 295 points and the Nasdaq lost
137 points as investors were unnerved by the prospect of higher rates.
</P>
<P>
	   Markets were closed Monday for the Presidents Day holiday, and on Tuesday,
investors traded cautiously. Volume on the New York Stock Exchange totaled 1.2
billion shares vs. 1.24 billion on Friday.
</P>
<P>
	   Corporate acquisitions, earnings and new products also moved individual
stocks.
</P>
<P>
	   Texas Instruments, which unveiled two new processors, saw its shares shoot
up almost 12 percent, or 14 13/16, to 148 13/16.
</P>
<P>
	   SBC Communications, a regional telephone company, announced it would spend
$3.9 billion in cash to acquire Sterling Commerce Inc., a provider of Internet
integration software. SBC's shares fell 2 to 36 1/4, while shares of Sterling
soared 12 to 43 9/16.
</P>
<P>
	   In another telecom deal: Global Crossing Ltd., a long-distance phone
company, said it would pay $3.8 billion for IXNet, an Internet networking
company. Global Crossing's stock fell about 7 percent, or by 3 3/4 to 48 5/8,
while IXNet's shares rose 2 1/2 to 55.
</P>
<P>
	   Nextel Communications, a wireless phone company, reported a
lower-than-expected loss in its most recent quarter, and said it would split its
stock 2-for-1. Nextel's shares jumped more than 10 percent, or by 12 5/16 to
131.
</P>
<P>
	   Declining issues outnumbered advancing issues on the New York Stock
Exchange, with 1,681 down, 1,390 up and 444 unchanged.
</P>
<P>
	   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 4.73 to 540.95.
</P>
<P>
	   In overseas trading, the Nikkei stock index in Tokyo fell 0.78 percent. In
Europe, the Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100 index fell 1.1 percent, while the
CAC-40 index in Paris edged down 0.07 percent and Frankfurt's DAX index rose
0.23 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
