<HEADLINE> Bond Market Rallies  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- Bond prices rose for a third straight session Tuesday as
investors grew confident that the Federal Reserve is keeping inflation in check.
Bonds also got a boost from the continued volatility in stocks.
</P>
<P>
	   The price of the 30-year Treasury bond rose 15/16 point, or $9.37 1/2 per
$1,000 in face value. The yield, which moves in the opposite direction of price,
fell to 6.08 percent from 6.15 percent late Friday. The bond market was closed
Monday in observance of Presidents Day.
</P>
<P>
	   Though rising interest rates have put pressure on bonds in the past few
months, traders are increasingly confident that the Fed's push to keep the
economy from overheating will keep a lid on inflation. Rising inflation is a
leading threat to the value of investments in long-term bonds.
</P>
<P>
	   On Tuesday, William McDonough, president of the Federal Reserve Bank of New
York reinforced the central bank's willingness to pump up rates if the
consumer-driven economy remains robust, a message that Fed Chairman Alan
Greenspan gave Congress last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   Bonds gained in part as the comments caused stocks to fall. Investors move
to bonds as a safe haven at times of stock market volatility because bonds pay a
fixed rate of return.
</P>
<P>
	   Bonds also gained from the McDonough speech because traders became more
comfortable that the Fed is keeping ahead of inflation, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
	   Elsewhere in the bond market, prices of short-term Treasury securities
ranged from gains of 5/32 point to  1/4 point and intermediate maturities rose
by up to 15/32 point to 15/16 point, according to Bridge Telerate.
</P>
<P>
	   Yields on three-month Treasury bills were 5.80 percent, with the discount
rising 0.06 percentage point from Friday to 5.63 percent. Six-month yields were
6.00 percent as the discount remained unchanged at 5.74 percent. One-year yields
were 6.18 percent, with the discount falling 0.04 percentage point to 5.83
percent.
</P>
<P>
	   Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the discount is the
interest at which they are sold.
</P>
<P>
	   The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between banks, rose
to 5.81 1/4 percent from 5.69 percent on Friday.
</P>
<P>
	   The Bond Buyer index of municipal bonds rose  1/4 to 92 17/32. The yield to
maturity of the index fell to 6.18 percent from Friday's 6.20 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
