<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Morale High on Boeing Picket Lines  </HEADLINE>
    By MICHAEL J. MARTINEZ AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   SEATTLE (AP) -- The strike by engineers and technical workers at The Boeing
Co. neared the end of its second week Tuesday, with both sides suggesting they
may return to the bargaining table. But on the picket lines, resolve seems to be
growing.
</P>
<P>
	   Few thought the Society for Professional Engineering Employees in Aerospace
had the backbone for a walkout, let alone a prolonged strike. But the engineers
-- the brains behind many of Boeing's aerospace programs -- are proving to be
more committed and resilient than expected.
</P>
<P>
	   "I think we've shown we're a force to be reckoned with," said Bill Schivitz,
a flight-control engineer in Boeing's military aviation division who was walking
the line across the street from his offices.
</P>
<P>
	   The nation's top federal mediator, C. Richard Barnes, was in Seattle on
Tuesday to meet with both sides. However, Boeing spokesman Peter Conte said no
face-to-face meetings were planned. Conte said the company was "exploring
approaches to returning to the table," but would not say when that might happen.
</P>
<P>
	   Charles Bofferding, SPEEA's executive director, said the union's talks were
only "maintenance, not a breakthrough," and that a sit-down meeting had not yet
been scheduled.
</P>
<P>
	   Things have not gone well for the company since the strike began Feb. 9.
</P>
<P>
	   Boeing has been forced to handle difficult questions regarding its MD-80 and
DC-9 aircraft, inherited from its merger with McDonnell Douglas, after the crash
of Alaska Airlines Flight 261.
</P>
<P>
	   It has delivered only four airplanes so far this month. In February 1999,
Boeing delivered 47 aircraft to customers.
</P>
<P>
	   And on Tuesday, the German airline Lufthansa briefly grounded 26 Boeing
747-400 jets due to problems with the planes' fire-extinguishing system. Boeing
engineers, mostly SPEEA members, are often called upon to assist airlines with
technical problems like these.
</P>
<P>
	   While SPEEA membership only totals about two-thirds of the 22,600
engineering and technical employees covered by the contract, SPEEA claimed up to
19,000 workers remained on strike Tuesday. Boeing estimates place the number of
strikers at 17,000. Neither estimate has changed since the beginning of the
strike.
</P>
<P>
	   SPEEA members received their last paychecks Thursday, so things might get
more difficult in the coming weeks. However, the Boeing Employees Credit Union
has offered strikers special loans to help cover costs during the strike and has
waived loan repayments until the strike is over.
</P>
<P>
	   Steven Hanling is working at his brother-in-law's machine shop when he's not
on the picket line and is also doing a little carpentry. When not on strike, he
is a stress engineer on Boeing's military F-22 fighter jet project.
</P>
<P>
	   "I'm staying out here as long as it takes," he said. "I haven't had to take
out any loans or waive any payments yet, so I can do this for quite a while."
</P>
<P>
	   Many striking workers noted that while Boeing was once the only high-tech
employer in town, the Internet economy now offers some appealing options.
</P>
<P>
	   "I think we'd all rather see Boeing do well, but if this drags on, I'll
think about sending my resume to other places," said Rick Reuter, a systems
engineer on the Joint Strike Fighter project, a military contract that Boeing
hopes to win.
</P>
<P>
	   The company is competing with Lockheed Martin, and U.S. Air Force officials
have voiced concerns about how the strike might affect Boeing's performance.
</P>
<P>
	   "You can be sure that Lockheed's schedules aren't slipping," Reuter said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-22-00 1824 </TRAILER>
