<HEADLINE> Mexico Requests Singer's Extradition  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) -- Mexico has formally requested the extradition of pop
star Gloria Trevi, her manager Sergio Andrade and choreographer Maria Raquenel
Portillo to face charges of corrupting a 17-year-old girl, the Foreign Ministry
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
	   The Brazilian Supreme Court will rule on the request, based on documents
provided by the Mexican government, the ministry said. The court has no deadline
for its ruling.
</P>
<P>
	   Trevi, Andrade and Portillo, also known as Mary Boquitas, were arrested on
Jan. 13 in Rio de Janeiro and transferred to Brasilia, the capital, on Feb. 10
to await a decision on their extradition.
</P>
<P>
	   Prosecutors from Mexico's Chihuahua state have accused them of corrupting
17-year-old Karina Yapor, whose parents had turned her over to Andrade's care at
age 12 for musical training -- allegedly at Trevi's behest. Yapor abandoned a
baby in Spain in 1998.
</P>
<P>
	   Her family accused Trevi and others of helping lure Yapor and other girls
into Andrade's care and helping him seduce them. Yapor has denied she was
mistreated, and all three suspects denied wrongdoing when questioned by
Brazilian police.
</P>
<P>
	   Trevi rose to fame in the late 1980s with a sexually flamboyant, politically
rebellious image. She spoke of someday running for president, and released a
series of nude calendars that poked fun at Mexican politics.
</P>
</TEXT>
