<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two state troopers file lawsuits against motorists alleging false  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - Two state troopers have filed lawsuits claiming
that two motorists who lodged complaints against them fabricated details about
traffic stops.
<P>
	   The two men, Allen Wade of Ridgefield Park, and Thomas Golden of Lampeter,
Pa., have been indicted by county grand juries for filing false complaints
against the troopers and then for lying either to State Police investigators or
to municipal court officials about the incidents.
</P>
<P>
	   Now the criminal defendants - who face up to 18 months in prison if
convicted - face civil lawsuits in which individual troopers are seeking to
collect financial damages from them for smearing their professional reputations.
</P>
<P>
	   Trooper Gregory March is suing Wade, who is black, for allegedly fabricating
events in which Wade claimed the trooper said to him, "Stay in the car nigger,"
during a traffic stop for speeding in April 1999.
</P>
<P>
	   It was a period when negative publicity was at its peak and tensions were
high over allegations of racial profiling and a 1998 incident in which three
minority men were shot and wounded by state troopers on the New Jersey Turnpike.
</P>
<P>
	   Sgt. Lawrence Gregan is suing Golden for allegedly fabricating events in
which Golden claimed Gregan threatened him and used his firearm to pin Golden's
arm against a car door during a traffic stop in March 1999.
</P>
<P>
	   Both cases are union causes, with a union lawyer explaining the lawsuits at
a news conference Tuesday. Officials claim that videotape from patrol car
cameras show that the alleged infractions did not occur.
</P>
<P>
	   "The unions will not stand by and let their members be targets for
scurrilous, malicious fabrications. There will be a suit and a judgment will be
executed on whatever assets you may have," said union attorney Richard Loccke.
</P>
<P>
	   The State Troopers Fraternal Association is representing March and the State
Troopers NCO Association, the union for sergeants, is representing Gregan.
Loccke, who is the attorney for both unions, said that the troopers could not
speak with news reporters because of State Police policy prohibiting news media
interviews without advanced approval.
</P>
<P>
	   Detective Sgt. Dennis Hallion, head of the State Troopers NCO Association,
said citizens must be confident that action will be taken when troopers do
wrong. But he said if "a certain faction decides that they want to make up
fabrications, lies, false accounts," then they should fear criminal prosecution
and civil liability.
</P>
<P>
	   There was no listing for Wade, and the phone at the number listed for Golden
was not answered Tuesday. It could not be determined if Golden has an attorney
assigned to his case. Donna Wrenn, a public defender representing Wade, was
unavailable Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
	   Troopers have filed private civil litigation in the past. Chuck Davis of the
attorney general's office said there are no state regulations barring troopers
from such litigation, and he said the state would have no comment on it since
officials regard it as a private matter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
