<HEADLINE> Clinton Picks German Ambassador  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton picked a State Department veteran
Tuesday to be ambassador to Germany.
</P>
<P>
	   A. Elizabeth Jones currently is a senior official in the department's Near
Eastern Affairs office after serving as ambassador to Kazakhstan from 1995 to
1998. If confirmed by the Senate, she would replace ambassador John C. Kornblum
in Germany.
</P>
<P>
	   Continuing the tradition of rewarding career foreign service officers with
foreign posts late in a presidential administration, Clinton also named career
diplomats to several other posts.
</P>
<P>
	   Laurence Pope would go to Kuwait, Howard Franklin Jeter to Nigeria, Rose
Likins to El Salvador and John Edward Herbst to Uzbekistan. Herbst is currently
U.S. consul general in Jerusalem.
</P>
