<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 18:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Firm says it can get auto emissions improvements done by June  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - The private contractor running New Jersey's
troubled auto inspection system pledges that it can fix computer troubles and
increase staffing to have centralized lanes running smoothly by June.
<P>
	   In a 38-page "recovery plan" required by state officials, Parsons
Infrastructure and Technology Group says it can meet the state's deadline to
clear up problems that forced long lines at Division of Motor Vehicle inspection
centers and prompted a political firestorm for Gov. Christie Whitman.
</P>
<P>
	   The report was delivered by the firm to the state on Friday, but state
officials refused to make it public, saying they needed to review it. The
document was released on Tuesday. Treasury spokeswoman Mary Lou Murphy said it
was now a public document because the state had forwarded it to federal
officials.
</P>
<P>
	   Parsons' plan for action carries a big price tag. State officials are
withholding a scheduled $10 million capital construction payment from the firm
because the plan was not finished. Murphy on Tuesday said the state is still
reviewing the plan, and that officials would not comment on it.
</P>
<P>
	   The auto inspection system has forced long lines at many stations since it
was implemented Dec. 13 to help New Jersey meet its federal mandate to clean the
air. The Whitman administration says Parsons fell down on the job, but Parsons
officials maintain that state officials also bear some of the blame.
</P>
<P>
	   Whitman has suspended the tougher auto emissions test and a complicated
computer system at the 15 centralized inspection stations that had the biggest
problems. Cars at these lanes are given the old tailpipe emissions test in an
action taken to buy time for Parsons.
</P>
<P>
	   Parsons in the report says it will improve computer systems that have forced
delays as cars move through the inspection process. The report includes changes
to make sure equipment won't freeze, and ways to reduce how much staffers must
enter into computers.
</P>
<P>
	   In addition, Parsons promises to have 950 employees on the job, an 80
percent increase from staffing levels the firm had in December. The plan details
an improved training program and says it will revamp how the lanes are staffed
to keep the lines moving. In addition, the report details the already-planned
construction of about two dozen additional lanes throughout the system.
</P>
<P>
	   Under the plan, the enhanced emissions test will be phased in beginning in
April in a trial run at the 15 inspection stations where it was suspended. Cars
on these lines will continue to be judged by the old tailpipe test. Parsons
spokesman Carl Golden said the trial run of the new test will allow the firm to
iron out the bugs by the time the system goes fully back on line in June.
</P>
<P>
	   "We had to meet the December 13 deadline, and everyone knew that," Golden
said. "That didn't allow us sufficient time to road test all the computer
equipment, and the other equipment. This is a plan that not only increases
staffing and lanes, it gives us time to make sure it's working properly."
</P>
<P>
	   The report did not satisfy Democratic critics of the system. Assemblyman
Neil Cohen, D-Union, and Anthony Impreveduto, D-Hudson, said Parsons should be
dumped from a seven-year contract that calls for at least $400 million in
payments.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's outrageous that we are getting a four-month action plan to fix
problems that were supposed to have been ironed out two months ago," Impreveduto
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-22-00 1846 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
