<DOCNO> APW20000222.0239 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 18:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Parents of Michael Ross victims testify in penalty phase  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW LONDON, Conn. (AP) - The parents of three teen-agers who were killed
by Michael Ross more than 15 years ago choked back their emotions Tuesday and
described for a jury the last time they saw their daughters alive.
<P>
	   Three years after his original death sentence was thrown out on appeal, a
second penalty hearing got underway in New London Superior Court.
</P>
<P>
	   The testimony of the parents, accompanied by large photo portraits of the
smiling girls, set an emotional benchmark for the prosecution's argument that
Ross deserves to be executed.
</P>
<P>
	   Ross, 40, a former Jewett City insurance salesman, has confessed and been
convicted of killing 14-year-olds April Brunias and Leslie Shelley of Griswold,
Robyn Stavinsky, 19, of Norwich and Wendy Baribeault, 17, of Jewett City.
</P>
<P>
	   A jury of nine men and three women must decide if Ross should get the death
penalty or life in prison. Ross' original death sentence was thrown out in 1997
when the state Supreme Court found prosecutors had withheld some psychiatric
evidence from the defense.
</P>
<P>
	   To find that a murder warrants the death penalty, jurors must decide that
the killing was done in an especially cruel, heinous or depraved way, he said.
The killing must be done in a way to inflict extreme pain or torture on the
victim beyond what was necessary to kill.
</P>
<P>
	   The jury also must find there are no mitigating factors that should spare
the Ross' life, such as a mental incapacity or something about the killer's
history or character.
</P>
<P>
	   The case in Superior Court before Judge Thomas Miano is expected to take
several weeks.
</P>
<P>
	   Edwin Shelley, Leslie's father, testified his daughter was a "beautiful
little girl" who had blond hair, blue eyes and weighed about 85 pounds.
</P>
<P>
	   He last saw her April 22, 1984, as she and April left to go to the movies in
Jewett City.
</P>
<P>
	   "It was Easter Sunday," he said, as he briefly lost his composure on the
witness stand.
</P>
<P>
	   He recalled how he made Leslie give him a kiss on the cheek before he would
consent to her trip to the movies.
</P>
<P>
	   April's mother, Ellen Roode, said the last time she heard from April was
when the girl telephoned to say she would be late coming home.
</P>
<P>
	   When the girls did not come home, both families contacted police. Their
bodies were found about 1 1/2 months later.
</P>
<P>
	   Under questioning from defense attorney Karen Goodrow, State Police Capt.
Thomas Snyder admitted Ross led police to the bodies.
</P>
<P>
	   Earlier in the day, Joan Stavinsky testified she became worried about her
stepdaughter Robyn when she failed to come home for Thanksgiving dinner in 1983,
and because she had heard that a girl's body had been found in Norwich.
</P>
<P>
	   Medical examiner Dr. Arkady Katsnelson said his autopsy determined Robyn
died from manual strangulation and was asphyxiated. The strangling cut off blood
supply to the brain by compressing arteries on either side of the neck.
</P>
<P>
	   Such a death could be as quick as 20 seconds, or could take longer,
depending upon how firmly the neck was strangled, he said. Ross was also
convicted of sexually assaulting her.
</P>
<P>
	   Under cross-examination by defense attorney Barry Butler, Katsnelson said
Robyn had no broken bones.
</P>
<P>
	   Katsnelson also said he could find no evidence of multiple strangulations or
signs that Robyn's body had been dragged along the ground. No defensive wounds,
such as cuts to the hands from fighting off an attack, were found.
</P>
<P>
	   Miano began the hearing by telling jurors that the death penalty is not
automatic, even if there are multiple victims.
</P>
<P>
	   Ross has been convicted of six counts of capital felony, for the four
murders and kidnappings of each victim, and additional sexual assaults against
Stavinsky and Baribeault.
</P>
<P>
	   The jury can find for the death penalty in any of the six counts.
</P>
<P>
	   Ross' defense is expected to present evidence that Ross was abused as a
child and that he suffers from a psychological disorder and a brain abnormality
that may have contributed to his crimes.
</P>
<P>
	   He already is serving two life sentences for killing Tammy Williams, 17, of
Brooklyn,and Debra Smith Taylor, 23, of Griswold, in 1982. He has confessed but
has not been prosecuted for killing two other women in New York.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
