<HEADLINE> Letterman Return Gets High Ratings  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- An estimated 12 million people watched David Letterman's
return to television Monday night after heart surgery, giving the "Late Show"
its best ratings in six years, CBS said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
	   Based on an instant Nielsen Media Research measurement of the top 47
markets, CBS' "Late Show" had nearly twice the ratings of its competitor, NBC's
"Tonight Show" with Jay Leno.
</P>
<P>
	   Only Letterman's first two shows after joining CBS in 1993 and a handful of
programs during the Winter Olympics in 1994 scored higher, CBS said.
</P>
<P>
	   Monday night's audience was three times the size of Letterman's average
audience this season.
</P>
<P>
	   Letterman taped his comeback show five weeks after undergoing emergency
quintuple bypass surgery. He rattled off several jokes about it, but turned
serious when he thanked his doctors and nurses for saving his life.
</P>
<P>
	   Bill Cosby was the show's guest host Tuesday. Letterman planned to do the
show Wednesday and Friday this week, and Kathie Lee Gifford was expected to fill
in on Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
