<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 18:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Election Violence Kills 13 in India  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PATNA, India (AP) -- Violent clashes and paramilitary raids left 13 people
dead Tuesday during a crucial state parliamentary election in Bihar, widely
regarded as the most lawless place in India.
</P>
<P>
	   Three other states held legislative elections Tuesday, including Orissa,
Haryana and Manipur.
</P>
<P>
	   Tuesday's violence in the final phase of voting in Bihar, though, brought
the state's death toll for the elections to 45. In two earlier rounds this
month, 32 people were killed and 50 were wounded.
</P>
<P>
	   Federal Rapid Action Force paramilitary commandoes gunned down seven men who
were trying to steal and illegally mark ballot papers in Bihar's northern
Beetiah election district, local election officer Sudhir Prasad said.
</P>
<P>
	   Six others were killed in clashes in Bihar's northern districts that border
Nepal.
</P>
<P>
	   Bihar police had been ordered to shoot people trying to stuff ballot boxes
or indulging in violence during the election, which is widely expected to be won
by members of Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee's coalition, which governs
nationally.
</P>
<P>
	   Election fraud happens frequently in India. Supporters of various political
factions often destroy ballots favorable to a rival, or stuff polling boxes by
stealing fresh ballots and stamping them with a candidate's election symbol.
Symbols, such as a lamp or a bicycle, are used to help illiterate people vote.
</P>
<P>
	   Voting was peaceful in Orissa and Haryana states.
</P>
<P>
	   But in the northeastern state of Manipur, suspected militants ambushed a
candidate's motorcade, killed three paramilitary soldiers and wounded nine,
United News of India news agency reported. Candidate L. Lala was hospitalized
after the attack, but voting in the state was not affected.
</P>
<P>
	   The ballots will be counted Friday, and early results are expected later
that day.
</P>
<P>
	   Some 5,000 federal paramilitary soldiers fanned out across the 108 election
districts of Bihar. The borders with neighboring Nepal were also sealed to
prevent bogus voters or criminals from entering the state.
</P>
<P>
	   The election is crucial to the political future of Laloo Prasad Yadav, whose
Rashtriya Janata Dal party has been in power for nearly 10 years in the state.
Yadav was forced to step down as chief minister some years ago in a corruption
scandal, but he appointed his wife to the top job.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-22-00 1859 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000222.0243 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 18:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Some Airlines Reject Fare Hike  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) -- The latest effort by airlines to boost fares by up
to $30 per round trip has stalled, with several airlines declining to go along
with the move.
</P>
<P>
	   Houston-based Continental started the latest round of increases on Friday,
citing escalating fuel prices, which have doubled in the past year. Five other
large airlines, including Fort Worth-based American, matched the increase.
</P>
<P>
	   But Dallas-based Southwest Airlines, Northwest Airlines and America West
were among the holdouts that chose not to raise prices.
</P>
<P>
	   Faced with rivals offering lower prices on the same routes, American rolled
back its increase two days after putting it in effect, and so did Continental,
Delta Air Lines and several others.
</P>
<P>
	   Just three weeks ago, Continental led another -- and successful -- run at
higher prices, boosting fares $20 per round trip to help compensate for the
increase fuel costs. Fuel is the second-largest expense for airlines, trailing
only labor costs.
</P>
<P>
	   Some analysts had predicted the latest increase also would stick because
publicity about rising fuel costs might make it seem reasonable to air
travelers, who are also paying more to fill their gas tanks.
</P>
<P>
	   Terry Trippler, an airline-industry observer for onetravel.com, an online
discount travel service, said he expects the airlines to try to raise fares
again next weekend in another attempt to get all major carriers on board.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-22-00 1859 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000222.0244 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 19:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Parents of Michael Ross victims testify in penalty phase  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW LONDON, Conn. (AP) - The parents of three teen-agers who were killed
by Michael Ross more than 15 years ago choked back their emotions Tuesday and
described for a jury the last time they saw their daughters alive.
<P>
	   Three years after his original death sentence was thrown out on appeal, a
second penalty hearing got underway in Superior Court.
</P>
<P>
	   The testimony of the parents, accompanied by large photo portraits of the
smiling girls, set an emotional benchmark for the prosecution's argument that
Ross deserves to be executed.
</P>
<P>
	   Ross, 40, a former Jewett City insurance salesman, has confessed and been
convicted of killing 14-year-olds April Brunias and Leslie Shelley of Griswold,
Robyn Stavinsky, 19, of Norwich and Wendy Baribeault, 17, of Jewett City.
</P>
<P>
	   A jury of nine men and three women must decide if Ross should get the death
penalty or life in prison. Ross' original death sentence was thrown out in 1997
when the state Supreme Court found prosecutors had withheld some psychiatric
evidence from the defense.
</P>
<P>
	   To find that a murder warrants the death penalty, jurors must decide that
the killing was done in an especially cruel, heinous or depraved way, Judge
Thomas Miano told the jury. The killing must be done in a way to inflict extreme
pain or torture on the victim beyond what was necessary to kill.
</P>
<P>
	   The jury also must find there are no mitigating factors that should spare
the Ross' life, such as a mental incapacity or something about the killer's
history or character, Miano said.
</P>
<P>
	   The case is expected to take several weeks.
</P>
<P>
	   Edwin Shelley, Leslie's father, testified his daughter was a "beautiful
little girl" who had blond hair, blue eyes and weighed about 85 pounds.
</P>
<P>
	   He last saw her April 22, 1984, as she and April left to go to the movies in
Jewett City.
</P>
<P>
	   "It was Easter Sunday," he said, as he briefly lost his composure on the
witness stand.
</P>
<P>
	   He recalled how he made Leslie give him a kiss on the cheek before he would
consent to her trip to the movies.
</P>
<P>
	   April's mother, Ellen Roode, said the last time she heard from April was
when the girl telephoned to say she would be late coming home.
</P>
<P>
	   When the girls did not come home, both families contacted police. Their
bodies were found about 1 1/2 months later.
</P>
<P>
	   Under questioning from defense attorney Karen Goodrow, State Police Capt.
Thomas Snyder admitted Ross led police to the bodies.
</P>
<P>
	   Earlier in the day, Joan Stavinsky testified she became worried about her
stepdaughter Robyn when she failed to come home for Thanksgiving dinner in 1983,
and because she had heard that a girl's body had been found in Norwich.
</P>
<P>
	   Medical examiner Dr. Arkady Katsnelson said his autopsy determined Robyn
died from manual strangulation and was asphyxiated. The strangling cut off blood
supply to the brain by compressing arteries on either side of the neck.
</P>
<P>
	   Such a death could be as quick as 20 seconds, or could take longer,
depending upon how firmly the neck was strangled, he said. Ross was also
convicted of sexually assaulting her.
</P>
<P>
	   Under cross-examination by defense attorney Barry Butler, Katsnelson said
Robyn had no broken bones, even in her neck where she was strangled.
</P>
<P>
	   Katsnelson also said he could find no evidence of multiple strangulations or
signs that Robyn's body had been dragged along the ground. No defensive wounds,
such as cuts to the hands from fighting off an attack, were found.
</P>
<P>
	   Miano began the hearing by telling jurors that the death penalty is not
automatic, even if there are multiple victims.
</P>
<P>
	   Ross has been convicted of six counts of capital felony, for the four
murders and kidnappings of each victim, and additional sexual assaults against
Stavinsky and Baribeault.
</P>
<P>
	   The jury can find for the death penalty in any of the six counts.
</P>
<P>
	   Ross' defense is expected to present evidence that Ross was abused as a
child and that he suffers from a psychological disorder and a brain abnormality
that may have contributed to his crimes.
</P>
<P>
	   He already is serving two life sentences for killing Tammy Williams, 17, of
Brooklyn,and Debra Smith Taylor, 23, of Griswold, in 1982. He has confessed but
has not been prosecuted for killing two other women in New York.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-22-00 1902 </TRAILER>
