<DOCNO> APW20000222.0245 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 19:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Festival Director Not Quitting  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    SALZBURG, Austria (AP) -- Gerard Mortier, the director of the Salzburg
festival, has changed his mind about quitting this summer, a year before his
contract expires, the Vienna daily Der Standard has reported.
</P>
<P>
	   Mortier announced the change of heart in an interview to be published
Wednesday in the Vienna daily Der Standard. It was carried in part by the
Austria Press Agency.
</P>
<P>
	   The director of what is one of the world's most prestigious music and stage
festivals was quoted as saying that he consulted numerous cultural figures
before making his decision to stay on.
</P>
<P>
	   Those consulted include French philosopher Bernard-Henri Levy, former French
Culture Minister Jack Lang and conductor Pierre Boulez.
</P>
<P>
	   In a recent interview with The Associated Press in Salzburg, Mortier said he
was quitting because he distrusts Joerg Haider's far-right Freedom Party, which
now shares the Austrian government with Chancellor Wolfgang Schuessel's
conservative Austrian People's Party.
</P>
<P>
	   He also cited unpleasant mail he had received from Austrians.
</P>
<P>
	   "Go to Chechnya," advised one writer on the back of a postcard. Another
writer filled more than a page with anti-Semitic drivel before telling the
director: "Go to Israel."
</P>
<P>
	   Mortier told The Associated Press that the growing amount of hate mail, in
response to his decision to leave his position as director of the Salzburg Music
Festival a year early, reflects a climate he fears will get worse under the new
government.
</P>
<P>
	   Earlier, Mortier was quoted as saying the Salzburg festival would revert to
a "yodeling contest" after his departure.
</P>
<P>
	   In the interview with Der Standard, Mortier sharply rejected claims that he
had wanted to quit prematurely in order to secure a job in Berlin and because of
a budget problem next year.
</P>
<P>
	   "Press reports to this effect I call high treason," Mortier was quoted as
saying. "There has never been any secret about the (festival) deficit, it
received the board's blessing, and we will make up for it."
</P>
<P>
	   But he also said, "It must be made clear from our side that we don't agree
with this government."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-22-00 1906 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000222.0246 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 19:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Schwarz: I wasn't in precinct for Louima attack  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - The police officer convicted of restraining Abner Louima
while a second cop sodomized the bleeding suspect with a broom handle testified
Tuesday that he wasn't even inside the precinct house when the brutal attack
occurred.
<P>
	   Charles Schwarz, testifying for the first time about that infamous August
1997 night, said he was conducting a routine "field search" of his patrol car
when officer Justin Volpe was assaulting the Haitian immigrant in a lavatory.
</P>
<P>
	   "I was never in that bathroom," Schwarz, 34, told the Brooklyn federal court
jury.
</P>
<P>
	   Clearly nervous but speaking in a calm, clear voice, Schwarz said he had
only accompanied Louima from the patrol car to the front desk of the 70th
Precinct after helping to arrest him during a street riot.
</P>
<P>
	   Schwarz's lawyer, Ronald Fischetti, asked his client who had escorted Louima
from the desk to the rear of the precinct.
</P>
<P>
	   "I think it was Tommy Wiese," Schwarz replied, referring to his partner.
"I'm not 100 percent sure, but I think it was him."
</P>
<P>
	   Schwarz, Wiese, and Officer Thomas Bruder are on trial in Brooklyn federal
court for conspiring to obstruct justice by concealing Schwarz's role as the
officer who held Louima down during the broomstick attack.
</P>
<P>
	   But Schwarz insisted that he was outside the building, checking his patrol
car for weapons or contraband that Louima might have concealed en route to the
station. Such inspections are standard procedure after an arrest, Schwarz
testified.
</P>
<P>
	   Schwarz was convicted last year of violating Louima's civil rights by
assisting in the attack, and faces a possible life sentence. He did not testify
in the earlier trial.
</P>
<P>
	   Volpe interrupted the same trial last May 20 to plead guilty to violating
Louima's civil rights and was sentenced to 30 years. Last week, telling the full
story for the first time under oath, Volpe said that Wiese - not Schwarz - was
present, but did not intervene.
</P>
<P>
	   Schwarz testified that he was unaware of what happened following Louima's
arrest outside a Brooklyn nightclub until two days later, when detectives from
Internal Affairs began grabbing broomsticks and mop handles from the precinct.
</P>
<P>
	   "I assumed they thought he had been beaten with broomsticks or a mop
handle," said Schwarz.
</P>
<P>
	   Louima suffered severe internal injuries, including a ruptured bladder and
colon, and spent two months in the hospital after the Aug. 9, 1997.
</P>
<P>
	   Calling his arrest "one of the worst moments of my life," Schwarz said, "I
was devastated ... that a United States Marine, a married man, a cop of eight
years, was now being charged with this horrible crime."
</P>
<P>
	   He said phone calls that prosecutors claim are key elements of the
conspiracy were consultations with police union delegates and other cops, but
said he never at any time spoke with Volpe, whom he said he hardly knew.
</P>
<P>
	   In the first trial, the government said phone records showed a call to Volpe
on Schwarz's phone card on Aug. 11, the day the IAB investigation moved into
high gear. Schwarz said on Tuesday that Wiese borrowed his card to make some
calls.
</P>
<P>
	   Earlier, a police investigator testified that Louima picked his torturer out
of a police photo array, but was unable to identify a second officer in the
precinct house bathroom.
</P>
<P>
	   Lt. Reinaldo Daniels, who tape-recorded a hospital interview with Louima
while heading the department's internal investigation, also admitted under
defense questioning that he improperly corrected errors in his written report.
</P>
<P>
	   The veteran detective conceded that he never showed Louima a picture of
Wiese, who claims that he entered the bathroom as Volpe stood over the Haitian
immigrant, bloody stick in hand.
</P>
<P>
	   "Did he (Louima) tell you the second officer was just standing there, doing
nothing?" Fischetti asked.
</P>
<P>
	   "Yes," replied Daniels.
</P>
<P>
	   Fischetti showed jurors four sets of photos, each containing six mug shots
of cops. The same pictures were shown to Louima at the hospital.
</P>
<P>
	   The victim failed to pick out Schwarz from the third array, Daniels
testified, but when he was shown the fourth and last set, which contained
Volpe's mug shot, "his eyes opened up like half dollars."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-22-00 1906 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000222.0247 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 19:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Education Sec.: Teach All Year Long  </HEADLINE>
   By ESTES THOMPSON Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   DURHAM, N.C. (AP) -- U.S. Education Secretary Richard Riley said Tuesday
that teachers must be better paid and work year round if American schools are to
shed outdated ways and improve.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We have an old agrarian schedule, an outdated factory model and an
antiquated wage system,'' Riley said during his annual address on the state of
American education.
</P>
<P>
	   The address, Riley's seventh and final, was made before students, elected
officials and educators at Durham's Southern High School, a previously
low-performing public school that turned itself around.
</P>
<P>
	   ``For the last 100 years, American education has been defined by certain
assumptions,'' Riley said.
</P>
<P>
	   ``One assumption was that the job of a teacher lasted nine months. The
second assumption was that we would always have a ready supply of dedicated
teachers, mostly women, who for relatively low wages would teach our children
their lessons.''
</P>
<P>
	   Riley said he wasn't proposing year-round schools for all children. He said
school schedules were better left to local school boards.
</P>
<P>
	   But he said: ``I believe that making teaching a year-round profession is the
future of American education.''
</P>
<P>
	   Kathleen Lyons, spokeswoman for the 2.5 million member National Education
Association teachers' union, said Riley's proposal is welcome.
</P>
<P>
	   ``They are being compensated for much less than what they are actually
working. The year-round plan and increased pay would move us toward treating
teachers as professionals and compensating them as they deserve,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
	   She said a teacher's work year could be up to 10 months. The average salary
for a public school teacher was $40,582 during the 1998-99 school year.
</P>
<P>
	   Riley said teachers' pay is not catching up with the demands made on them.
Recent studies show that the annual income gap between experienced teachers with
masters' degrees and people in other fields with the same level of education is
at least $32,000.
</P>
<P>
	   ``In this time of economic prosperity, with state coffers expanding, there
can be no excuse for shortchanging our students and their teachers,'' Riley
said.
</P>
<P>
	   Riley released a 29-point report card on education showing improvements in
reading, math and science scores, technology and opportunities for disabled
students. But the report card also showed a worsening of student college debt,
the gap in Internet access between poor and wealthy schools and drug use.
</P>
<P>
	   In the Republicans' official response to Riley's speech, Rep. Heather
Wilson, R-N.M., said Congress over five years has spent $1 billion more than the
Clinton administration has requested.
</P>
<P>
	   Wilson said education decisions must be made locally ``by somebody that
knows your child's name.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-22-00 1910 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000222.0248 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 19:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tuesday's Commodities Roundup  </HEADLINE>
    By DAVE CARPENTER AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   A frenzy of speculative buying drove already-soaring palladium futures up
another 16 percent Tuesday to an all-time high on the Comex division of the New
York Mercantile Exchange.
</P>
<P>
	   In other markets, oil rose to nearly another nine-year high and natural gas
and cocoa tumbled.
</P>
<P>
	   Palladium prices have been rocketing higher since November and doubled in
little more than two months amid the virtual absence of top producer Russia from
the export market and heavy demand by the automative and electronics industries.
</P>
<P>
	   The metal is needed to make catalytic converters and semiconductors, widely
used in laptops and cellphones among other portable communications devices.
</P>
<P>
	   With Russian supplies still at a trickle, the palladium market exploded when
trading limits imposed Monday by the Tokyo Commodity Exchange sent buyers
scrambling to other markets to find the metal.
</P>
<P>
	   On the New York Merc, where trading resumed Tuesday after the Presidents Day
weekend, the result was a whopping increase of $115.55 an ounce, to $816.80,
after the March contract reached as high as $835. That's the largest one-day
gain ever for the metal.
</P>
<P>
	   The palladium market has become so wildly volatile and expensive that some
investors have taken to the sidelines, said analyst Dave Meger, who called the
price rise "insane."
</P>
<P>
	   "The market is trading on pure emotion right now," said Meger, senior metals
analyst for Alaron Trading Corp. in Chicago. "The tightness of supply is
something to take note of. But I don't think it's responsible for these surreal
moves now."
</P>
<P>
	   Elsewhere on the New York Merc, concern over dwindling supplies sent crude
oil up again. The expiring March contract rose 11 cents to $29.62 a barrel,
benefiting from a late trading surge that sent it as high as $30.30 -- just
short of the nine-year high of $30.45 reached last week.
</P>
<P>
	   Investors are worried that heading into a series of key meetings in the next
10 days, there's still no assurance that top world producers led by the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries will substantially raise
production once their agreement on lowered output expires March 31.
</P>
<P>
	   The first of the meetings is Wednesday when oil ministers of the Gulf
Cooperation Council, including OPEC countries, gather in Riyadh, Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
	   But the most critical one is March 2 in London involving the oil ministers
of Mexico, Saudi Arabia and Venezuela. Those three are behind the 11-month-old
agreement that reduced world production by more than 4 million barrels daily.
</P>
<P>
	   Energy analyst John Kilduff said that while everyone expects oil prices to
come back down to the low to mid $20s per barrel later this year, another spike
to as high as $34 or $35 is possible depending on what OPEC says and ultimately
does.
</P>
<P>
	   "The market is real sensitive right now to the various statements coming out
of OPEC officials," said Kilduff, senior vice president at Fimat USA Inc.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's not a done deal that there will be an increase in production," he
said, noting that nations such as Kuwait still are holding out against an
increase in production, particularly a large one.
</P>
<P>
	   Also on the New York Merc, unseasonably mild weather nationwide sent March
natural gas futures plummeting 11.8 cents to $2.515 per million British thermal
units.
</P>
<P>
	   In other energy commodities, March heating oil fell .58 cent to 74.87 cents
a gallon and March unleaded gasoline rose 1.82 cent to 84.49 cents a gallon. In
London, April Brent crude from the North Sea rose 65 cents to $26.58 a barrel.
</P>
<P>
	   Cocoa continued its long slide amid huge harvests coming out of West Africa
onto a glutted world market. May cocoa fell $20 to $795 a ton on New York's
Coffee, Sugar &AMP; Cocoa Exchange.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-22-00 1910 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000222.0249 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 19:11 </DATE_TIME>
