<HEADLINE> Liberty Media To Buy Ascent Group  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    DENVER (AP) -- Liberty Media Group will buy Ascent Entertainment Group in a
$460 million deal that includes the Denver Nuggets, the Colorado Avalanche, an
arena was well as the company's non-sports assets.
</P>
<P>
	   Liberty will pay $15.25 per share for Ascent, and also assume nearly $300
million in debt. The deal is expected to close in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
	   Liberty officials said Tuesday they will continue to look for a new owner
for the Nuggets, the Avalanche, and the new Pepsi Center stadium in Denver.
</P>
<P>
	   Liberty planned to buy the non-sports assets of the Denver-based Ascent last
year but the deal fell through. The company also provides pay-per-view
programming for hotels and satellite service and maintenance to NBC.
</P>
<P>
	   The unsuccessful Liberty deal was contingent on Ascent selling the teams and
the Pepsi Center. Ascent tried to sell the sports assets to Denver billionaire
Donald Sturm, but the deal collapsed over a city mandate that the teams would
remain in Denver for 25 years.
</P>
<P>
	   Liberty plans to sell the teams and the arena, but will keep Dan Issel as
president and head coach of the Nuggets, Pierre Lacroix as general manager of
the Avalanche and Don Elliman as president of Ascent Sports Holdings.
</P>
<P>
	   Issel and Lacroix just signed long-term deals with Ascent.
</P>
<P>
	   The Denver-based Liberty owns video programming, communications, technology
and internet businesses in the United States, Europe, South America and Asia.
Liberty Media Group common stock is a tracking stock issued by
telecommunications giant AT&AMP;T Corp. Liberty Media Corp., which holds most of the
assets included in the Liberty Media Group, is a wholly owned subsidiary of
AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
	   Shares of Ascent rose $4.68 3/4 to $14.81 1/4 in trading on the Nasdaq Stock
Market. Shares of Liberty Group were down 62 1/2 cents to $50 in trading on the
New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
</TEXT>
