<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 19:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More accidents, fewer deaths, in 65 mph zones  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - The number of accidents increased, but fewer people
died in car wrecks along the 475 miles of New Jersey highway where the speed
limit was raised to 65 mph nearly two years ago, according to a report released
Tuesday.
<P>
	   The state Department of Transportation report recommended that motorists be
allowed to continue driving 65 mph in these designated stretches of highway.
But, the department also said lawmakers should hold off on expanding the higher
limit to other sections of roads.
</P>
<P>
	   State officials said they need another 18 months to further study the
effects of the 65 mph limit before recommending whether to expand it, leave it
as it is or lower the limit back to 55.
</P>
<P>
	   Lawmakers have six months to either accept or reject the transportation
department's report.
</P>
<P>
	   The 18-month study was part of a deal that Gov. Christie Whitman struck with
legislators when she signed the bill raising the limit in May 1998.
</P>
<P>
	   The higher limit is allowed on parts of the Atlantic City Expressway, Garden
State Parkway, New Jersey Turnpike, Routes 18 and 55, and Interstates 78, 80,
195, 287 and 295.
</P>
<P>
	   The study compared accidents and other data on the 475 miles of road from
two 18-month periods - June 1998 to November 1999 and June 1996 to November
1997.
</P>
<P>
	   According to the report, accidents increased 18.3 percent, going from about
9,300 to 11,000 after the speed limit was raised.
</P>
<P>
	   The number of people injured in accidents increased nearly 6 percent during
the same time, going from about 4,500 to about 4,800.
</P>
<P>
	   Fatalities, though, dropped 9.6 percent, from 104 to 94.
</P>
<P>
	   "Accidents fluctuate over time," the report said. "It is not possible to
determine whether the increase in accidents in the 65 mph zones represents a
normal fluctuation in accident rates or suggests that increased speed
contributes to increased accidents."
</P>
<P>
	   The report also said that when the speed limit was raised from 55 mph to 65
mph, speeds increased an average of 1 mph in all 65 mph zones, except the New
Jersey Turnpike, where speeds increased 3 to 4 mph.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's real clear to us that 65 mph speed limit has been a success," said
Steve Carrellas, state chapter coordinator for the National Motorists
Association. "We think more mileage of 65 or higher should be added much sooner
than the DOT is recommending."
</P>
<P>
	   But, Richard Retting, transportation engineer at the Insurance Institute for
Highway Safety, said the study is too short-term to draw conclusions. Studies
conducted in other states have consistently documented that, over time, speed
kills, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Retting also called the study "naive" because it failed to consider other
factors that can affect accident and fatality rates, including weather.
</P>
<P>
	   "We know, without any doubt, what the long-term effects are of high speed
limits," Retting said. "We know that speed kills people."
</P>
<P>
	   But John Hagerty, New Jersey State Police spokesman, said speed "did not
contribute to any appreciable increase in accidents in the 65 mph speed zones."
</P>
<P>
	   From June 1996 to November 1997, speed contributed to 11.2 percent of all
fatal accidents on these roads when the limit was 55. But, under the higher
limit, speed contributed to only 4.8 percent, Hagerty said.
</P>
<P>
	   The largest jump in accidents occurred on a 47-mile stretch of I-78, between
Warren and Union counties, where there was a nearly 32 percent increase in
accidents between the two 18-month periods.
</P>
<P>
	   The best results occurred on a 34-mile stretch of Route 55, from Cumberland
to Gloucester counties, where accidents decreased 5.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   One lawmaker said the report is proof that motorists should be allowed to
drive 65 mph on other parts of the 10 designated highways that have been deemed
appropriate for the higher limits.
</P>
<P>
	   "Opponents said if we were to open that flood gate, motorists would be
driving 10, 15 mph faster, leading to carnage on the roads," said Assemblyman
Guy Gregg, R-Morris, who has led the fight to raise the speed limit. "For the
most part, the speed remained the same."
</P>
<P>
	   Gregg said he would meet with state officials to try to work out a
compromise. Failing that, Gregg said he would explore the option of pushing
legislation that would expand the higher limit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
