<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 19:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Jersey governor rebuts Gore but takes swipe at Bradley  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   WASHINGTON (AP) - New Jersey Gov. Christie Whitman chided Vice President
Al Gore Tuesday for saying that "racial profiling practically began in New
Jersey" but concurred that Bill Bradley did little to address the problem when
he represented the state in the U.S. Senate.
<P>
	   Gore made the comment Monday night during a presidential debate in New York.
</P>
<P>
	   He and Bradley, his challenger for the Democratic nomination, shared several
spirited exchanges over the controversial police practice of stopping motorists
based on their skin color or appearance.
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley demanded to know why the vice president has not urged President
Clinton to issue an executive order outlawing the practice.
</P>
<P>
	   Gore said Clinton has issued a directive to prepare for an executive order.
He accused Bradley of not addressing the issue during his 18 years in the Senate
and added for emphasis, "you know, racial profiling practically began in New
Jersey, Senator Bradley."
</P>
<P>
	   Whitman, a Republican, wrote in her letter to Gore:
</P>
<P>
	   "You must have misspoken when you alleged that racial profiling practically
began in New Jersey. The fact is that racial profiling is a national problem
that the president and the Department of Justice have indicated goes well beyond
state borders."
</P>
<P>
	   Whitman also took a shot at Bradley, who narrowly defeated her to win a
third term in the Senate in 1990.
</P>
<P>
	   "I understand that you were trying to make the point that Senator Bradley
did little, if anything at all, to address the problem of racial profiling
during 18 years as a United States senator," she wrote. "On that point you are
absolutely on target."
</P>
<P>
	   Whitman did not specify what, if anything, a U.S. senator could do on the
issue. Her spokesman, Peter McDonough, said Bradley "could have asked for some
federal intervention" to look into complaints about racial profiling.
</P>
<P>
	   Both Democratic campaigns sought to read Whitman's letter to their benefit.
</P>
<P>
	   Gore spokesman Doug Hattaway said Whitman "is obviously in a good position
to judge Senator Bradley's claims about racial profiling. He clearly did little
if anything at all to address the problem that reared its head in New Jersey."
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley spokeswoman Kristen Ludecke said, "Once again Al Gore is called on
the carpet for misrepresenting the facts. But the larger point is that Al Gore
could take a key step toward ending racial profiling tomorrow by simply walking
down the hall" and urging Clinton to ban the practice by executive order.
</P>
<P>
	   Asked about the controversy Tuesday, White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said
the Justice Department has made progress since Clinton issued an order last year
for federal agencies to gather information on police stops.
</P>
<P>
	   "I don't remember any help coming from Senator Bradley, even though it was
his own backyard," Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
	   Whitman herself has been battered by controversy over racial profiling by
New Jersey state troopers.
</P>
<P>
	   The issue exploded in April, 1998, after two troopers shot at a van they had
pulled over on the New Jersey Turnpike. Four black and Hispanic men were inside,
and three were wounded. The troopers were indicted on attempted murder charges.
</P>
<P>
	   Last February, Whitman fired State Police Superintendent Carl Williams for
linking drug trafficking to minorities in a newspaper interview on racial
profiling.
</P>
<P>
	   In April, Attorney General Peter Verniero reported that racial profiling is
"real, not imagined," and that blacks are pulled over more often and are far
more likely to be searched.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
