<HEADLINE> Democrats Swipe At Sen. Ashcroft  </HEADLINE>
   By LIBBY QUAID Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Democrats chided GOP Sen. John Ashcroft Tuesday for
accepting an honorary degree from a Southern Christian college that bans
interracial dating.
</P>
<P>
	   The criticism came from Senate Democrats' campaign arm in advance of a
Missouri visit by George W. Bush, who is under fire for speaking at the same
college, Bob Jones University. The Greenville, S.C., school, which lost its
tax-exempt status in the 1970s because of racial discrimination, is a popular
stop for many GOP candidates seeking conservative support.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It is absolutely sickening that John Ashcroft would lend his personal
endorsement and the prestige of his office to the causes of bigotry, racial
separation and anti-Catholicism,'' said Jim Jordan, DSCC political director.
</P>
<P>
	   The school, whose officials would not accept a reporter's phone calls, also
has been accused of intolerance toward Catholics.
</P>
<P>
	   Ashcroft is battling a re-election challenge by Democratic Gov. Mel
Carnahan, whose campaign said Ashcroft should return the honorary degree.
</P>
<P>
	   The senator's spokesman said an honorary degree is a common courtesy that
cannot be taken as an endorsement. ``In this instance, Senator Ashcroft accepted
an opportunity to speak to the student body, and did not then, and does not now,
have knowledge of their specific teachings,'' spokesman Steve Hilton said.
</P>
<P>
	   ``He totally repudiates attacks on religious denominations or beliefs and
completely embraces the American heritage of the equality of all people and
religious and racial diversity and tolerance,'' Hilton added.
</P>
<P>
	   He also referred questions to Steve Mamanella, spokesman for the St. Louis
archdiocese, who said: ``Certainly, we can say that in all of our experience,
we've never had any reason to believe that Senator Ashcroft in his time as
senator or governor of Missouri has not treated the church or Catholics with
respect.''
</P>
<P>
	   Ashcroft filed Senate travel disclosure reports showing he traveled May 7
and 8 to the school. The school paid $741 for Ashcroft's transportation and
lodging.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
