<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 19:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Attorneys trade charges at close of Diallo trial  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Amadou Diallo forced police to fire a 41-bullet
barrage at him on his Bronx doorstep by refusing to stop for questioning and
pulling what appeared to be a gun, defense attorneys argued Tuesday.
<P>
	   "That's not unreasonable behavior on their part," attorney John Patten said
in closing arguments at the murder trial of four police officers. "That's
unreasonable on his part."
</P>
<P>
	   Although the black object in Diallo's hand turned out to be a wallet, when
he pulled it out, "that was it," Patten told the jury.
</P>
<P>
	   "You can't expect (the officers) to stand there and get blasted away."
</P>
<P>
	   The prosecution countered by portraying the defendants as trigger-happy
patrolmen who made a snap judgment that the victim - an unarmed black immigrant
from West Africa "minding his own business" - was really a bad guy lurking in a
bad neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
	   Diallo, 22, "was being looked at in a way that doomed him from the start,"
said prosecutor Eric Warner.
</P>
<P>
	   Patten argued that with bullets ricocheting around the vestibule of Diallo's
apartment building, the defendants thought they were in a firefight, and made a
split-second decision to defend themselves.
</P>
<P>
	   The officers "were wrong," he said. "They made a mistake. But they honestly
believed this guy was shooting at them."
</P>
<P>
	   In a scathing two-hour closing argument, Warner repeated allegations that
the plainclothes officers cornered the victim in the 5-by-7-foot vestibule at
12:40 a.m. on Feb. 4, 1999, then, without warning or justification, unleashed 41
bullets. The victim was hit 19 times.
</P>
<P>
	   Warner accused the defendants of jumping to false conclusions - and sticking
to them - despite signs Diallo was a "decent man" who lived on a quiet,
working-class street. He singled out Officer Sean Carroll for making the
decision to try to stop Diallo on a shaky "hunch" that he might be a wanted
rapist or robber.
</P>
<P>
	   The shooting "wasn't a mistake," Warner said. "It was a terrible series of
conscious decisions."
</P>
<P>
	   Mocking defense claims that Diallo's dimly lighted doorstep contributed to a
tragic mistake, Warner charged that the officers "took a dim view of that block.
... And it was downhill from there."
</P>
<P>
	   Diallo "didn't do anything wrong that night, and they didn't do anything
right," he added.
</P>
<P>
	   The closing arguments came after nine days of testimony in the trial of
Carroll, 37, Edward McMellon, 27, Kenneth Boss, 28, and Richard Murphy, 27. The
defendants - all white - have pleaded innocent to second-degree murder.
</P>
<P>
	   The case was moved to Albany after a judge ruled the defendants could not
get a fair trial in New York City because of the publicity surrounding the case.
The jury was to begin deliberating on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   If convicted of murder, the officers face a maximum sentence of 25 years to
life in prison. However, State Supreme Court Justice Joseph Teresi opened the
door for a compromise verdict last week by ruling that jurors would be able to
consider less serious charges such as second-degree manslaughter, which would
mean the defendants could get only probation.
</P>
<P>
	   The defense argued Tuesday there was not enough proof to convict the
officers on any charge. They said a medical examiner's theory that most of the
bullets hit Diallo as he was going down or already on the ground was flawed and
biased.
</P>
<P>
	   Attorneys also attacked prosecutors for not calling the only eyewitness
other than the officers. Called by the defense, the witness, Schrrie Elliott,
testified that she heard one officer yell "Gun!" before shots erupted, and that
the victim appeared to stay upright.
</P>
<P>
	   Warner said prosecutors considered Elliott too unreliable to put on the
stand. But he also reminded jurors of her testimony that the officers jumped out
of the car with their guns drawn and shot Diallo without telling him to stop.
</P>
<P>
	   Murphy's attorney, James Culleton, argued that his client opened fire only
after Carroll and McMellon shot first. Murphy also saw McMellon fall off the
stoop, and assumed he had been shot, the lawyer said.
</P>
<P>
	   Another defense attorney, Steven Brounstein, warned against the
prosecution's "mantra of 41 bullets. ... This is not a case of 41 shots."
</P>
<P>
	   Culleton also said the officers followed police procedure when they stopped
to question Diallo.
</P>
<P>
	   "They didn't know he lived in that building," said Culleton. "And they had
an obligation, following proper police procedure, to stop, to walk up to Mr.
Diallo and ask, 'Who are you?' and 'Why are you in this area?"'
</P>
<P>
	   "Why Mr. Diallo acted the way he did to this simple request to talk, we'll
never know," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
