<HEADLINE> Tuesday's Canada News Briefs  </HEADLINE>
   By The Associated Press Note: All dollars are Canadian unless otherwise noted
Trucker Protest Turns Frenzied
<TEXT>
<P>
	   AMHERST, Nova Scotia (AP) -- The truckers' protest at the Nova Scotia-New
Brunswick boundary turned into a frenzy of roaring engines and angry shouts
Tuesday as several rigs bolted from the blockade.
</P>
<P>
	   The two-day standoff on the Trans-Canada Highway turned ugly shortly after
it appeared the truckers and the RCMP had reached a deal to clear the roadway
and allow trucks through that didn't want to be part of the protest.
</P>
<P>
	   But as some of the trucks started to move to the shoulder of the highway
several vehicles tried to break free of the blockade altogether.
</P>
<P>
	   Two of the rigs were stopped by irate protesters who threw themselves in
front of the 18-wheelers.
</P>
<P>
	   Dave Fowler, an independent trucker from nearby Truro, Nova Scotia, laid
down on the highway in front of a huge truck driven by an angry driver who was
determined to get back on the road.
</P>
<P>
	   The driver slammed on the truck's brakes just short of Fowler.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I don't know... it's just too hard,'' a visibly shaken Fowler said when
asked why he would risk his life.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I figure it's better to die trying than just do nothing.''
</P>
<P>
	   Following the close encounter, RCMP officers imposed order on the situation,
keeping the protesters to one side of the road and allowing several trucks to
slip away from the protest.
</P>
<P>
	   The blockade began Sunday night as a way to draw attention to rising fuel
costs, toll highways and low wages.
</P>
<P>
	   ---
Chretien Shrugs Off Bankrupt Firms That Got Job Grants
</P>
<P>
	   OTTAWA (AP) -- Prime Minister Jean Chretien isn't bothered that 51 companies
that got federal job creation grants went out of business before completing
their projects.
</P>
<P>
	   Only communist countries guarantee nobody will go bankrupt, he said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
	   ``In a market economy some people fail,'' Chretien told the Commons. ``What
is good about Canada (is) so many are successful.''
</P>
<P>
	   Reform deputy leader Deborah Grey was unimpressed by the explanation,
complaining that $12 million in taxpayers money had evaporated instead of
generating jobs.
</P>
<P>
	   Federal records made public Monday showed 51 firms that got money under the
Transitional Jobs Fund between 1996 and 1999 went bankrupt or otherwise closed
their doors before the projects were finished.
</P>
<P>
	   Officials at the Human Resources Department point out that more than 1,000
grants worth $298 million were handed out in those three years.
</P>
<P>
	   They say a failure rate of around five per cent of recipients is acceptable
-- especially since many grants went to businesses in depressed economic regions
with high unemployment.
</P>
<P>
	   ---
Feds Approve Viagra for Use by Veterans
</P>
<P>
	   OTTAWA (AP) -- The federal government has included Viagra on its list of
drugs for which some veterans can receive benefits, raising a protest from one
MP that government has no place in the bedrooms of the nation.
</P>
<P>
	   Tuesday's decision to use public money to reinforce sexual performance with
pills is a first for Canada and came after Veterans Affairs received up to 1,000
requests a month for Viagra since it was approved last March.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It's a go,'' said Veterans Affairs Minister George Baker, who approved the
plan to provide veterans of the First and Second World Wars, Korea and some
younger veterans with up to six pills a month.
</P>
<P>
	   With a $15 pill good for one session, the plan will cost millions, say
federal documents.
</P>
<P>
	   A total waste, said Tory Elsie Wayne.
</P>
<P>
	   ``With all the problems we have in our Armed Forces, that we would spend any
money on this,'' raged Wayne. ``Now really and truly, I just can't believe this
one. Glory be, for heaven's sakes.
</P>
<P>
	   ---
Ujjal Dosanjh To Be Sworn in As British Columbia Premier
</P>
<P>
	   VICTORIA, British Columbia (AP) -- Ujjal Dosanjh will be sworn in as
Canada's first Indo-Canadian premier Thursday in Victoria, but a cabinet shuffle
will wait.
</P>
<P>
	   Dosanjh will take over the job from interim premier Dan Miller after he won
a leadership race at an NDP convention last weekend.
</P>
<P>
	   Dosanjh is currently the attorney general.
</P>
<P>
	   It's expected Dosanjh won't ask for his new cabinet to be sworn in for at
least another week.
</P>
