<HEADLINE> Palestinian, Israel Talks Stalled  </HEADLINE>
   By DANA BUDEIRI Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   RAMALLAH, West Bank (AP) -- Negotiations with Israel are still deadlocked,
Palestinians said Tuesday night, expressing disappointment with messages relayed
by a top U.S. envoy from Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak.
</P>
<P>
	   In his meeting with Clinton envoy Dennis Ross, Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat urged the American administration to intervene in the negotiations,
Palestinian negotiator Saeb Erekat said.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We are going through a real crisis and the peace process needs to be put
back on track,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Ross relayed Barak's answers to Palestinian demands, including the handover
of three Arab suburbs of Jerusalem as part of an interim agreement.
</P>
<P>
	   While the Israelis were prepared to consider other Palestinian demands
regarding the overdue handover of 6.1 percent of West Bank land, ``these changes
will not include the three villages around Jerusalem,'' said a senior
Palestinian official, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
	   Speaking after the meeting, Ross said ``certainly there are difficulties,
but we will continue to move forward.''
</P>
<P>
	   However, expectations were low that Ross would succeed. Israel has been
resisting U.S. intervention, while the Palestinians have demanded a more intense
mediation effort by Washington.
</P>
<P>
	   The Palestinians have said they would not resume negotiations unless Israel
reaffirms a promise to carry out a West Bank troop withdrawal ahead of a final
peace accord, in addition to the overdue 6.1 percent pullback.
</P>
<P>
	   Israel has proposed to skip the next pullback, arguing there was no point in
dealing with interim issues when a final treaty is being discussed. The deadline
for the final status agreement is Sept. 13.
</P>
<P>
	   The two sides are also at odds over whether in the interim phase, Israel
alone can determine what areas of the West Bank it will hand over.
</P>
<P>
	   Israeli officials have accused the Palestinians of creating an unnecessary
crisis and being inflexible on relatively minor issues.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I don't know who is scoring points, but I know who is losing -- the peace
process,'' Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy said after a meeting with Ross.
</P>
<P>
	   Palestinian Planning Minister Nabil Shaath said principles were at stake.
Barak's refusal to let the Palestinians have a say in sketching withdrawal maps
indicated that ``there is not even a minimum of partnership,'' Shaath said.
</P>
<P>
	   The two sides have already missed a major peace deadline -- a Feb. 13 target
date for formulating a blueprint for a peace treaty. The Palestinians have
suggested that the framework -- which was Barak's idea from the start -- be
skipped and negotiators try to work on a full treaty instead. Barak has
suggested that May be set as a new deadline for a treaty framework.
</P>
<P>
	   Israeli commentators have outlined what they say is Barak's own timetable.
They say that if by the end of April, peace talks with Syria are not in full
swing, Barak will take the first steps toward a unilateral troop withdrawal from
Lebanon, Syria's client state, and only then move ahead full force on the
Palestinian track.
</P>
<P>
	   Also Tuesday, Barak aide Yossi Kucik said Israel has approved construction
of 27 new vacation cottages on the Golan Heights and will continue building as
long as there is no agreement with Syria.
</P>
<P>
	   Security officials, meanwhile, have warned Barak that the crisis with the
Palestinians could lead to widespread unrest in the West Bank and Gaza Strip,
the Haaretz daily said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
	   Two anti-Israeli protests were staged Tuesday in the West Bank.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-22-00 2104 </TRAILER>
