<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 21:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Close on Congo Force  </HEADLINE>
   By EDITH M. LEDERER Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- The U.N. Security Council is ``very close'' to
approving a plan to send U.N. military observers to monitor Congo's cease-fire,
but negotiators must settle some differences, the council president said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It's very likely that we're going to vote tomorrow (Wednesday),'' said
Argentina's U.N. Ambassador Arnoldo Listre, who holds the rotating council
presidency. ``I think we are close to an agreement, very close.''
</P>
<P>
	   The United States, which sponsored the resolution, would like it adopted to
coincide with the summit of leaders from six African nations involved in the war
in Congo. The summit begins Wednesday in Lusaka, Zambia.
</P>
<P>
	   The rebels launched their campaign in August 1998, accusing Congolese
President Laurent Kabila of mismanagement, corruption and warmongering.
</P>
<P>
	   A cease-fire agreement was signed July 10 by Kabila and his allies --
Zimbabwe, Angola and Namibia -- and by Rwanda and Uganda. The main rebel
factions signed on in the weeks that followed.
</P>
<P>
	   But fighting continues in the north and southeast, with both sides accusing
each other of violations. Foreign troops have made no move to withdraw.
</P>
<P>
	   U.N. diplomats cautioned after Tuesday's council meeting and contacts
between governments which continued into the evening that a vote could be
delayed until later in the week.
</P>
<P>
	   The council could not vote before Wednesday because the U.S. Congress
requires 15 days notification of any U.N. peacekeeping operation. No
Congressional objection had been received by Tuesday night, clearing the way for
U.S. approval.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We're making good progress and I'm confident we'll come to a final
resolution soon,'' said deputy U.S. Ambassador Nancy Soderberg, the top U.S.
negotiator.
</P>
<P>
	   The resolution calls for observers to monitor implementation of a
cease-fire. The observers would also verify the separation and redeployment of
opposing troops and lay the groundwork for possible deployment of a much larger
U.N. peacekeeping force.
</P>
<P>
	   Listre said one of the unresolved questions is the number of U.N. military
observers to be deployed.
</P>
<P>
	   Secretary-General Kofi Annan recommended a force of 500 military observers
backed by 5,037 security and logistics personnel.
</P>
<P>
	   Some council members who favor a larger force want the resolution to
authorize ``at least'' 500 observers, leaving the secretary-general the option
of beefing up the force if there is a need. Others want the resolution to
authorize ``up to'' 500 observers.
</P>
<P>
	   Leaders of the six nations are expected at Wednesday night's summit to try
once again to save the fragile peace process.
</P>
<P>
	   Meanwhile, a pro-government militia says it has killed close to 275 Rwandan
and Angolan fighters while defending Congo's southeastern Shabunda region
against rebel attack, state-run radio in Congo's capital of Kinshasa reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
	   Mai-Mai militia Gen. Padiri Kalendu told state-run radio that his forces
were in control of the region in South Kivu state. His claims could not be
independently confirmed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-22-00 2124 </TRAILER>
