<HEADLINE> Legend Airlines Postpones Launch  </HEADLINE>
    By CHRISTY LEMIRE Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   DALLAS (AP) -- Legend Airlines postponed its debut flights from Dallas Love
Field after the Federal Aviation Administration found several problems during an
inspection Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
	   The Dallas-based startup initially had planned its first flight Feb. 29, but
aircraft inspectors on Tuesday found about 60 items that would not pass
certification, said John Clabes, spokesman for the FAA's regional office in
Oklahoma City.
</P>
<P>
	   "Some of them are fairly simple things they overlooked when they redesigned
the airplane. Some are major," said Clabes, who would not specify what the
problems were.
</P>
<P>
	   Legend president and CEO T. Allan McArtor said the airline has asked the FAA
to delay the certification process for a few days to perfect the installation of
custom-designed gourmet kitchens and in-flight television systems.
</P>
<P>
	   Each DC-9 in Legend's fleet is being reconfigured to seat 56 passengers and
to add satellite telephones, live television and power outlets for portable
electronic devices. In addition, the airline has developed new kitchens that
will require FAA engineering approval.
</P>
<P>
	   "We had a lot of things that weren't ready -- very, very minor things. ...
There was absolutely nothing of major importance at all," McArtor said Tuesday
night in a telephone interview with The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
	   "The primary delay problem for us is the technologically advanced system --
the television, the galleys, the laptop power supply."
</P>
<P>
	   McArtor said the airline must rework the flight schedule, and said any
customers who have booked seats on canceled flights will be placed on Delta Air
Lines or offered full refunds. Legend also is offering a buy-one, get-one-free
deal for inconvenienced passengers.
</P>
<P>
	   McArtor said he would know later this week how many flights would be delayed
and when the first flights would be rescheduled. He would not say how much money
the delays would cost the airline.
</P>
<P>
	   Clabes said the FAA recommended that Legend begin flying in early March.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
