<DOCNO> APW20000222.0290 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 22:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-China Internee Sues Mitsubishi  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    SANTA ANA, Calif. (AP) -- A Chinese immigrant sued two major Japanese
corporations on Tuesday, alleging he was among thousands of Chinese civilians
who were brutalized and forced to work as slaves during World War II.
</P>
<P>
	   Shang-Ting Sung, a naturalized U.S. citizen, says he was interned by
Japanese soldiers at age 10 and forced for years to work in mines owned and
operated in China by Mitsubishi Corp. and Mitsui Corp.
</P>
<P>
	   The lawsuit is among a growing number of civil actions filed against big
Japanese companies under a California law that specifically allows the filing of
forced-labor lawsuits against foreign companies.
</P>
<P>
	   In Japan, Minoru Sasaki, a spokesman for Mitsui Mining Co., said the company
could not comment because its American subsidiary was unable to confirm the suit
was filed.
</P>
<P>
	   Officials of Mitsubishi Corp. did not immediately return a call for comment.
</P>
<P>
	   Sung's lawsuit is the first in the United States to be filed on behalf of a
Chinese civilian, said Sheldon Harris, a California State University,
Northridge, emeritus professor of history who has written extensively about
Japanese atrocities during the war.
</P>
<P>
	   Other lawsuits filed in this country have been brought on behalf of former
American prisoners of war who worked in slave labor camps.
</P>
<P>
	   Sung, about 69, lives in the suburban San Gabriel Valley east of Los
Angeles. He said he isn't sure about his exact age because his birth records
were destroyed during the war.
</P>
<P>
	   Sung's suit seeks class-action status for thousands of other Chinese
civilians who allegedly performed slave labor for the Japanese.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-22-00 2227 </TRAILER>
