<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 22:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Picks UN Reform Nominee  </HEADLINE>
   By EDITH M. LEDERER Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- After a 10-month search, Secretary-General Kofi Annan
nominated a management expert from Singapore on Tuesday to take charge of
streamlining U.N. operations and eliminating waste and fraud.
</P>
<P>
	   As U.N. inspector-general, Dileep Nair will be in charge of the Office of
Internal Oversight Services, which was established in 1995 under pressure from
the United States and some other countries to reform the U.N.'s bloated
bureaucracy and cut costs.
</P>
<P>
	   In a note to the General Assembly, the secretary-general recommended Nair
for a single five-year term as director of the office with the rank of
undersecretary-general. The General Assembly is expected to approve the
appointment shortly.
</P>
<P>
	   The inspector-general's job is considered one of the most important at the
United Nations.
</P>
<P>
	   Nair is currently managing director of DBS Bank, the Development Bank of
Singapore, which is the country's largest bank.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It's a happy ending to a long, tortuous 10-month process,'' U.N. spokesman
Fred Eckhard said. ``We're looking forward to his turning in a strong
performance.''
</P>
<P>
	   Nair will replace Karl Paschke, a career diplomat from Germany who headed
the office from its creation until he stepped down late last year. Nair is
expected to start on April 24.
</P>
<P>
	   Nair worked for many years in Singapore's elite administrative service,
initially in the Ministry of Finance.
</P>
<P>
	   In 1986, he was appointed deputy secretary in the Ministry of Trade and
Industry and three years later he transferred to the Ministry of Defense as
deputy secretary in charge of manpower, finance and information technology.
</P>
<P>
	   Nair became chief executive officer of POSBank, which was Singapore's
national savings bank, in 1997. The following year, POSBank was acquired by DBS
Bank and he became managing director in charge of creating a processing and
servicing hub for the DBS Group.
</P>
<P>
	   In 1996, Nair served as a member of the U.N. efficiency task force that
advised the secretary-general on aspects of U.N. reform.
</P>
<P>
	   Presenting his final report in October, Paschke said his office had saved
the United Nations $70 million during his five-year tenure by identifying and
targeting areas of waste and fraud.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-22-00 2245 </TRAILER>
