<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Crown Prince Attacks Press  </HEADLINE>
   By JOSEPH COLEMAN Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese Crown Prince Naruhito on Wednesday criticized media
coverage of his wife's pregnancy and miscarriage last year as ``deplorable,'' in
a statement marking his 40th birthday.
</P>
<P>
	   The pregnancy, reported first by the national Asahi newspaper, triggered a
media frenzy, with camera crews trying to track Crown Princess Masako's every
move and staking out her parents' home.
</P>
<P>
	   After officials announced on Dec. 31 that Masako had been pregnant but
suffered a miscarriage, the Asahi faced a wave of public criticism that its
report had placed the princess under harmful pressure.
</P>
<P>
	   In comments at a news conference on Monday and released on Wednesday,
Naruhito accused the media of reporting the pregnancy too soon.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I do find it truly deplorable that ... at a highly uncertain stage before
medical examinations had even taken place, a great amount of reporting was
conducted,'' the crown prince said.
</P>
<P>
	   Naruhito, the heir to the throne held by his father, Emperor Akihito, also
accused the media of prying into the couple's private life and publishing false
information. He did not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I hope that in the future, such issues will be handled in a more prudent
and considerate way, taking the nature of the matter into consideration,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
	   It was the first time Naruhito had publicly criticized reporting over
Masako's brief pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
	   After six years of marriage, Naruhito and Masako have yet to have a child,
raising concerns about the future of the imperial line since only men can
succeed to the throne in Japan. Naruhito's brother Akishino has two children,
but they are both girls.
</P>
<P>
	   After the miscarriage, the Asahi defended its coverage, arguing that the
royal family are public figures and that imperial succession is of great
interest to the nation.
</P>
<P>
	   Naruhito said Masako was steadily recovering, and he thanked the public for
messages of support. Masako, a Harvard graduate, was a diplomat before her
marriage to Naruhito.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-22-00 2246 </TRAILER>
