<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 22:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Stocks Edge Higher  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks declined Wednesday morning on profit-taking
and continued selling of cross-held issues. The dollar was lower against the
yen.
</P>
<P>
	   The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average, which had been up some 138
points early in the session, shed 17.54 points, or 0.09 percent, to 19,373.04 at
the end of the morning session. On Tuesday, the average closed down 153.17
points, or 0.78 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   The dollar bought 110.36 yen, down 0.84 yen from late Tuesday in Tokyo and
also below its late New York level of 110.70 yen.
</P>
<P>
	   On the stock market, the Nikkei average opened modestly higher Wednesday as
investors were encouraged by Tuesday's gains in New York, where the Dow Jones
industrial average rose 85.32 points to close at 10,304.84.
</P>
<P>
	   But prices moved into negative territory toward the morning session close on
profit-taking and selling of cross-held issues.
</P>
<P>
	   Japanese companies often unwind shares they hold in other companies prior to
the close of each fiscal year, which ends March 31.
</P>
<P>
	   Tuesday's recovery on Wall Street offered some relief to the Tokyo market,
which has been increasingly anxious about the prospect of a major downward
correction in U.S. stocks. On Friday, the Dow Jones index tumbled 295.05 points,
or 2.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the first
section was down 0.47 points, or 0.03 percent, to 1,644.12. The TOPIX closed
down 36.13 points, or 2.15 percent, the day before.
</P>
<P>
	   In currency dealings, traders said the dollar was under selling pressure
against the yen amid the euro's strength against the greenback. On Tuesday, the
euro rose against the dollar on speculation some European nations may raise
interest rates.
</P>
<P>
	   Against the Japanese currency on Wednesday, the euro was traded at 110.06
yen, down from 111.31 yen late Tuesday in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
	   The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond fell to 1.8300
percent from Tuesday's finish of 1.8550 percent. Its price rose 0.21 point to
99.74.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
