<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 22:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Notes, Quotes From Campaign Trail  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTHFIELD, Mich. (AP) -- First George W. Bush put a line in his stump speech
that sounded suspiciously like John McCain's complaint about soldiers on food
stamps.
</P>
<P>
	   Then, the Texas governor started tooling around in a bus like McCain's
``Straight Talk Express,'' but fancier.
</P>
<P>
	   Now, the Bush campaign is replicating another idea that, while hardly new,
has been used to good effect by McCain: confetti and balloons.
</P>
<P>
	   After noticing how often and well McCain's picture played in newspapers and
magazines because of his frequent use of confetti, streamers and balloons, the
Bush camp has tried with mixed results to do the same thing.
</P>
<P>
	   At campaign events over the past week, confetti blowers have dribbled out
colored paper after Bush has finished his speech. After one in Charleston, S.C.,
Bush jumped as explosives detonated overhead to send confetti falling his way.
</P>
<P>
	   On several occasions, netting on the ceiling that was supposed to let
balloons cascade down has instead released all at once, dropping a clump of
balloons that hid Bush from the television platform.
</P>
<P>
	   And after a speech at Lawrence Technological University in Southfield, the
blowers blew but only a smattering of confetti flew.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   BY THE NUMBERS:
</P>
<P>
	   58 -- Number of Republican delegates at stake in Michigan's primary Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
	   30 -- Number of Republican delegates at stake in Arizona's primary Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   VOTER'S VOICE:
</P>
<P>
	   ``People say they don't like it, but it works. People don't like wrestling,
but they watch it.'' Steve Comben, 40, of suburban Detroit, on negative
campaigning. He voted for Bush.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   THIS DATE FOUR YEARS AGO:
</P>
<P>
	   Bob Dole said Republicans would lose in the House, Senate, and state
legislatures if Pat Buchanan won the GOP nomination. But he denied he was
picking on Buchanan or trying to get other GOP leaders to do so. ``We're just
talking about some of his ideas,'' Dole said in Colorado Springs, Colo.
</P>
<P>
	   Buchanan, saying GOP leaders are the ones risking party unity, ruled out
running as an independent if denied the Republican nomination, because he would
``not do anything to re-elect Bill Clinton.'' Buchanan rode a wagon in a parade
in Tucson, Ariz., where he ignored some boos and catcalls.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   TUESDAY'S ROUNDUP:
</P>
<P>
	   McCain sweeps Bush in GOP primaries in Michigan and his home state of
Arizona, with Keyes finishing third in both contests. Pulling his criticisms of
Al Gore together into a single theme, Democratic rival Bill Bradley said his own
views on abortion, guns and other issues were ``clear, consistent, reliable.''
``What do we really know about Al Gore?'' he asked. Gore took the day off in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   WEDNESDAY'S TRAIL:
</P>
<P>
	   McCain heads to Washington state to meet voters in Spokane and Bremerton.
Bush discusses the election with Hispanic voters for a Univision special in Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley makes an economic speech at Columbia University in New York before
flying to Washington state, where he will remain for about a week. Gore
discusses senior citizen health issues and rising prescription drug costs in
Deerfield Beach, Fla.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
