<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 23:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
   By The Associated Press Fernando Benitez
<TEXT>
<P>
	   MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Fernando Benitez, a journalist famed for a four-volume
study of Mexico's Indian cultures, died Monday. He was variously listed from 88
to 90.
</P>
<P>
	   Benitez began his career as a reporter in 1934 and worked for 65 years,
continuing to write brief columns last year for the daily La Jornada. For
decades, he edited the cultural section of newspapers such as El Nacional,
Novedades and Unomasuno and promoted the works of generations of young Mexican
writers.
</P>
<P>
	   Benitez also served as Mexico's ambassador to the Dominican Republic from
1990 to 1994.
</P>
<P>
	   His most famous work ``The Indians of Mexico,'' was published in 1967.
</P>
<P>
	   He is survived by his wife, Georgina Conde, and his son Fernando.
Donald Tecumseh Carson
</P>
<P>
	   AUSTIN (AP) -- Donald Tecumseh ``Tee'' Carson, a former pianist who filled
the chair once occupied by jazz legend Count Basie, died Feb. 13. He was 70.
</P>
<P>
	   When Basie died in 1984, it was Carson who took his place as the band's
pianist, managing ``to suggest Mr. Basie's manner without adopting it, using
single-note lines that are a variant of Mr. Basie's lines, and dropping gentle
but propitious chords behind the soloists.''
</P>
<P>
	   His jazz career began in San Francisco in the 1970s, where he played and was
a jazz disc jockey on WCSM radio.
David Cyr
</P>
<P>
	   OMAHA, Neb. (AP) -- Dr. David Cyr, a nationally known clinician and Boys
Town researcher in the treatment and diagnosis of balance disorders in infants
and children, died Thursday of cancer. He was 52.
</P>
<P>
	   Cyr was director of the Balance Disorders Clinic at Boys Town National
Research Hospital. He also helped the Mayo Clinic in Minnesota set up its own
balance-disorder program.
</P>
<P>
	   He was a professor at Creighton University Medical School and at the
University of Nebraska Medical Center.
Jesse Wayne Forrester Jr.
</P>
<P>
	   ASTORIA, Ore. (AP) -- Jesse Wayne ``Bud'' Forrester Jr., the former editor
of The Daily Astorian, died Tuesday. He was 86.
</P>
<P>
	   Forrester combined journalism and public service in a career that spanned
from the 1930s to the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
	   For most of his career, he worked with his wife, Eleanor, running news and
business departments at newspapers in Coos Bay, Pendleton and Astoria, where he
was known for his powerful editorials and community-minded news pages.
</P>
<P>
	   He worked at a number of papers, including the Oregon Journal, The
Oregonian, The East Oregonian, and the Coos Bay Harbor (now the North Bend
News). His work earned him a number of journalism awards and he sat on the
Pulitzer Prize jury.
</P>
<P>
	   He is survived by his wife; sons, Mike and Steve, both newspapermen in Salem
and Astoria, respectively, and four grandchildren.
Husam el-Din Mustafa
</P>
<P>
	   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) -- Husam el-Din Mustafa, an American-trained film director
who created about 100 films and dozens of popular Egyptian soap operas, died
Tuesday of a stroke. He was 64.
</P>
<P>
	   He began his career as an assistant to American director Cecil B. De Mille.
Mustafa graduated from the University of Southern California in 1951 before
assisting De Mille in the film ``The Greatest Show on Earth.''
</P>
<P>
	   On his return to Egypt in 1956, he directed his first film, ``Enough, My
Eyes,'' a tragedy that introduced him as a serious director and producer.
</P>
<P>
	   Among his prize-winning movies are ``The Bullet Still in My Pocket,'' about
the 1973 Arab Israeli War, along with ``Enemy Brothers'' and ``The Devils.''
</P>
<P>
	   His soap operas were mostly historical, dealing with events in the early
centuries of Islam. His better-known soap operas included: ``The Knights,''
``The Heroes,'' ``Ibn Hazm'' and ``The Age of The Imams.''
</P>
<P>
	   Mustafa had been working on a popular television series, ``The Eagle of the
East.''
William Rocheleau Jr.
</P>
<P>
	   LEWISTON, Maine (AP) -- William Rocheleau Jr., a lawyer, ex-mayor of
Lewiston and former president of the North American Hockey League, died
Saturday. He was 74.
</P>
<P>
	   Early in his nearly 40-year law career, he was Lewiston's lawyer and went on
to serve as mayor from 1967-68.
</P>
<P>
	   He owned a nightclub, the Cavalier Inn of Lewiston; a professional hockey
team, the Maine Nordiques; and was a partner in an auto dealership.
Jimmy Rush
</P>
<P>
	   CHICAGO (AP) -- Jimmy Rush, the father of U.S. Rep. Bobby Rush, died Sunday
of congestive heart failure. He was 72.
</P>
<P>
	   The congressman's son, Huey Rich, was shot to death in October. Two men have
been charged in the killing.
</P>
<P>
	    Jan Stevens
</P>
<P>
	   FLAGSTAFF, Ariz. (AP) -- Jan Stevens, an editor and reporter for the Arizona
Dailt Sun in Flagstaff and an author of children's books, died Monday of cancer.
She was 46.
</P>
<P>
	   Stevens covered all aspects of community life in Flagstaff, writing features
about the town, its people, their interests and their projects and
organizations.
</P>
<P>
	   Stevens, writing under the name Jan Romero Stevens, was also the author of
the bilingual ``Carlos'' children's books.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Carlos and the Squash Plant'' was published by Northland Publishing in
1993, and since then she's had four other Carlos books published, as well as
``Twelve Lizards Leaping; a Christmas Tale.''
</P>
<P>
	   Stevens is survived by her husband, Fred M. Stevens; two sons Jacob and
Paul; her mother, Charlotte Farmer; and a sister, Lang Secrest.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-22-00 2300 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
