<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 23:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Air To Stay With Star Alliance  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) -- Thai Airways International said Wednesday that it
would remain in the Star Alliance linking more than half-dozen major airlines,
which last week it said it was considering leaving.
</P>
<P>
	   In a news release, the airline said reports of the possibility of Thai
Airways leaving the grouping were "incorrect."
</P>
<P>
	   "Thai's President, Thamnoon Wanglee, has never said that the airline wanted
to leave the alliance and confirms that Thai would remain in the alliance," said
the airline's announcement, dated Tuesday but sent Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   The issue arose last week after Thamnoon told journalists that the airline
had asked its financial adviser "to consider whether it is better to stay with
the Star Alliance or whether it is better to leave."
</P>
<P>
	   Thai Airways' more powerful regional rival, Singapore Airlines, is scheduled
to join Star in April. The group also includes United Airlines, Lufthansa, Air
Canada, Air New Zealand, All Nippon Airways, Scandinavian Airlines System and
Varig.
</P>
<P>
	   Star Alliance is one of a handful of such groupings in which airlines
cooperate in certain services and offer passengers benefits such as the right to
consolidate frequent flyer mileage acquired from different member airlines.
</P>
<P>
	   A decision to review Star membership came after figures showed Singapore
Airlines cost Thai Airways $10 million last year by taking over some
non-alliance code-sharing agreements with Lufthansa on flights from Europe.
</P>
<P>
	   Meanwhile, Thai Airways is preparing to sell a stake to a strategic partner
later this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-22-00 2333 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
