<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 23:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Trade Surplus Declines in Jan.  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    TOKYO (AP) -- Japan's trade surplus with the world fell in January to its
lowest level in two years as recovering domestic demand and surging oil prices
fueled imports, the government said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   The merchandise trade surplus, the measure of all goods exported minus those
imported, shrank 30.7 percent compared to the same month last year to $4.75
billion (522.6 billion yen), the Ministry of Finance said. The surplus was
unadjusted for seasonal factors.
</P>
<P>
	   It was the smallest monthly tally since January 1998, when the surplus hit
$3.68 billion.
</P>
<P>
	   The politically sensitive trade surplus with the United States also fell,
slipping 1.9 percent on year to $4.34 billion.
</P>
<P>
	   It was the tenth straight month in which Japan's overall surplus fell from
levels a year earlier. Analysts said budding domestic demand, together with a
strong yen, continues to spur growth in imports.
</P>
<P>
	   "I think the smaller surplus is mainly due surging imports reflecting the
economic recovery in Japan," said Kazuhiko Ogata, senior economist at ABN AMRO
Securities (Japan) Ltd.
</P>
<P>
	   The shrinking surplus also shows the effect of surging oil prices, which
boosts the value of the country's imports, analysts said. Crude oil prices more
than doubled in January from a year earlier to $25.70 per barrel.
</P>
<P>
	   Those two factors are likely to continue to support import growth, analysts
said. They predicted the surplus will continue shrinking in the coming months.
</P>
<P>
	   But some said they believe exports will catch up in the coming months, as
demand around the globe continues to firm. That could slow the trend toward a
smaller surplus or, according to some, even turn the trend around.
</P>
<P>
	   Japan is fighting to emerge from its worst economic downturn in 50 years. It
has been under heavy pressure from the United States and other trading partners
to rein in the surplus by bolstering its weak economy to spark demand for
imports.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-22-00 2348 </TRAILER>
