<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Man Sentenced in Fatal Truck Tug  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRECKENRIDGE, Minn. (AP) -- A man whose friend died in a truck tug-of-war
after an argument over who had the most powerful pickup was sentenced Tuesday to
a year in jail.
</P>
<P>
	   Bobby G. Olson, 34, pleaded guilty last month to criminal vehicular homicide
in the death of Arnold Motzko, 24. Both men were from Barnesville, a town of
2,066 about 16 miles east of the Minnesota-North Dakota border.
</P>
<P>
	   They had been drinking Oct. 30, 1998, when they decided to settle an
argument over who had the toughest truck. They drove to a county road, chained
their trucks together and began to pull. Motzko's truck rolled, throwing him
from the cab and killing him.
</P>
<P>
	   Under a plea agreement, Olson will serve a year in jail, pay Motzko's
funeral expenses and serve 10 years probation.
</P>
<P>
	   Olson's lawyer, Craig Richie, called the contest more an act of stupidity
than anything else.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
